(95, 3, '2010-10-03 14:11:14', '2010-10-03 21:11:14', 'When I first coined the phrase, “The Power of Food,” I was referring to food’s potential benefit for our health. Now as I think about the power of food, I am referring to much more than its potential health benefits. I myself originally began eating healthier foods little by little but little did I know  would build a repertoire of foods that would act as my staples to lose weight, give me energy, fuel my workouts and prevent disease. All this at the same time that I found comfort with more enjoyment than ever before.\n\nMy early morning hours didn’t lend itself to my cooking breakfast, nor did I feel like pouring cereal into a bowl. I’ve always been a dairy girl since childhood, so I decided to grab a yogurt on the run. Little did I know that this would begin my love affair with yogurt long before words such as probiotics were commonplace, I just knew that yogurt was light, easy to eat, portable, and gave me a start to my day much like getting gas for the car before a drive. I now know that when we start early by eating within an hour of awakening, we feed our brain along with our body. This helps us to feel, and think better too. We also manage cravings later in the day when we start our day with fuel too. And when we choose a food that has natural sugars such as we find with a healthy yogurt, we really take in a combo of nutrients to start our day.\n\nOver the years I’ve chosen different yogurts, all from low fat, no fat to full fat.  I chose yogurts based upon all natural ingredients. After eating different yogurts for almost 20 years, I found Voskos!  I’d never been a fan of Greek yogurts. I tried Voskos plain non-fat and all I can say is that I went from being unable to eat plain yogurt ever, to eating a whole pint in one sitting! Creamy, tasty, high in protein, nonfat, and with 5 different live bacterial strains, I found myself amused that I couldn’t stop eating it.\n\nIf we think about eating more healthy foods more often and to feel better vs. what not to eat, or focusing only on our weight, we can begin the change process to being healthier and stronger and changing our perceptions about food for the long haul.\n\nHave you had “a Yogurt a Day,” today?  What’s your most life-changing discovery.', 'The Power of Food!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'power-of-food', '', '', '2010-10-03 14:11:14', '2010-10-03 21:11:14', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=95', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(100, 3, '2010-10-02 14:14:03', '2010-10-02 21:14:03', 'How your skin looks depends on many factors, including your age, gender, genetics, and how well you take care of your skin. Most of us know by now that strict avoidance of smoking and the daily use of a broad-spectrum sunscreen are a must for a healthy skin.\n\nBut an often-overlooked aspect of maintaining a good skin is our diet. What we eat and drink does affect how our skin looks. Here are a few tips for helping your skin look its best:\n\n1. <strong>Stay hydrated</strong>. Adequately hydrated skin cells reward us with enhanced health, increased energy, and a radiant complexion. Dehydrated skin over a period of time can become dry and wrinkled.\n\n2. <strong>Minimize alcohol consumption</strong>. Alcohol will make you dehydrated and could make your skin look dull and lifeless.\n\n3. <strong>Avoid saturated fats, but don’t avoid fats altogether</strong>. In fact, healthy fats, such as the omega-3 fatty acids, are incredibly important and may help to prevent dry, patchy skin. Studies have found that people whose diets were high in these fatty acids had less skin wrinkling than those with diets high in saturated fats.\n\n4. <strong>Get enough protein</strong>. Foods high in protein, such as Voskos Non-Fat Greek Yogurt, are good for our skin because we need protein to repair our cells. Women in particular often do not have protein-adequate diets, and this can result in accelerated aging.\n\n5. <strong>Get enough B Vitamins</strong>. Deficiencies in B vitamins, particularly B6, B12, biotin and niacin can cause dermatitis, skin hypersensitivity, and dry skin. B vitamins are found in whole grain, green leafy vegetables, meats, fish, eggs and milk.\n\n6. <strong>Get plenty of vitamin C</strong>. Vitamin C is a powerful anti oxidant, and a necessary component in the formation of collagen.\n\n7. <strong>Want to combine as many of these nutrients as possible in a single meal?</strong> Mix 8 oz Voskos Greek Yogurt with a cup of fresh berries and a handful of walnuts, and accompany your meal with a tall glass of freshly squeezed orange juice. This meal is low in saturated fats and high in protein, omega 3 fatty acids, calcium and vitamin C.\n\n8. <strong>Eating Voskos Greek Yogurt has an added bonus</strong>: it contains five live and active multibacterial strains, which means that each 100 gram serving of Voskos Greek Yogurt contains billions of live and active bacterial bases. These help maintain gut flora and boost immune system functioning and nutrient absorption, all essential to a healthy skin and body.', 'Benefits of Greek Yogurt: Better Looking Skin!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'benefits-of-greek-yogurt', '', '', '2010-10-02 14:14:03', '2010-10-02 21:14:03', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=100', 0, 'post', '', 3),
