(120, 6, '2010-10-06 05:00:11', '2010-10-06 12:00:11', '<a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Voskos Greek yogurt</a> is an excellent choice for pregnant women who need additional protein for their growing bodies.  It also provides essential nutrients including calcium, which is essential for building strong, dense bones early in life, and maintaining strength and bone health later in life.  \n\n<strong>Protein:</strong>\n\nDuring pregnancy, protein needs are elevated due to the needs of the growing baby.  Amino acids, or broken down proteins, are needed to build cells essential for the growth of the baby.  Particularly during the second and third trimesters, women should consume at least 70 grams of protein per day.  As compared to non-pregnant women, who require on average, about 50 grams per day, protein needs during pregnancy are significantly increased.  With one 8 oz Voskos Greek yogurt, women can meet about 1/3 of their protein requirements!  Other protein sources include: \n\n3 oz lean beef – 21 g \n3 oz roasted chicken breast – 27 g\n3 oz salmon – 23 g\n2 TBSP peanut butter – 8 g\n½ cup canned black beans – 9 g\n1 egg – 6 g\n½ c tofu (firm) – 20 g\n1 c skim milk – 8 g\n \nThus, eating about 4 protein rich foods per day will assist in meeting pregnant women’s protein needs.  An example day includes: 2 glasses skim milk, 3 oz chicken breast, ½ cup beans, and 8 oz Voskos Greek yogurt.  Vegetarian women need to be mindful to ensure they are meeting their protein needs. It is important to utilize the excellent vegetarian protein sources available including a variety of canned beans, soy protein products, and even whole grains, including oatmeal which contains 6 grams protein per cup. \n  \n<strong>Calcium:</strong>\n\nPregnant women need to ensure they are meeting their calcium requirements, which are approximately 1000 mg per day.  If deficient, calcium is taken from the mother’s bones to ensure the growing baby receives a sufficient quantity. Voskos Greek Yogurt is a perfect way to ensure calcium needs are being met. Just 8 ounces provides approximately 400 mg of bone building calcium.  Other calcium sources include salmon (3 oz) 181 mg, cooked spinach (1/2 c) 120 mg, or calcium fortified orange juice (6 oz) 200 mg. \n\nChoose Voskos Greek Yogurt as a fantastic snack, to keep hunger at bay, and get valuable nutrition at the same time. Try it. Once you go Greek, there is no turning back!	', 'Vital Nutrition for a Healthy Pregnancy', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-pregnancy-nutrition', '', '', '2010-10-06 05:00:11', '2010-10-06 12:00:11', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=120', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(123, 8, '2010-10-05 05:00:41', '2010-10-05 12:00:41', 'You may be asking yourself the same question.  Well, I can certainly tell you.  I took a tour of the plant and was pleasantly surprised.  Now, as a dietitian, it comes with my territory to be a bit of a “foodie.”  So, I LOVE to know how foods are manufactured in such large quantity and the process used in preparing the food for consumption.\n\nFor starters, the Voskos plant is spotless and they take great pride in keeping the facilities and the offices extremely clean.  Anyone who’s ever taken a risk to eat in a “hole in the wall” restaurant and suffered severe food poisoning, such as I have, will really appreciate the fact that the standard for clean at Voskos is impeccable.\n\nVoskos starts the whole yogurt-making process with high quality, local milk that is then pasteurized.  As the milk then moves along from station to station, it goes through a proprietary straining process that separates out the whey protein.  This creates the thick, creamy texture of Voskos Yogurt without all the liquid at the top of the carton that has to be stirred before eating.\n\nAnd, I love the fact that I get more protein per serving with Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a>, also due to the straining process.  Voskos yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free and has double the amount of probiotic cultures required for yogurt, which helps support healthy digestion.  Not to mention, Voskos’ Yogurt isn’t imported from another country.  It’s manufactured right here in the good ole’ USA, so when you choose Voskos, you are supporting American workers.\n\nVoskos Yogurt sets an excellent standard for Greek yogurt.  If you haven’t tried it yet, you should.  I think you’ll be amazed at the quality and the difference you’ll taste.  Have you tried it?  Let me know what you think.  Opah!', 'What’s So Cool About Voskos Greek Yogurt?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-yogurt-benefits', '', '', '2010-10-05 05:00:41', '2010-10-05 12:00:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=123', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(131, 7, '2010-10-07 05:00:55', '2010-10-07 12:00:55', 'When I was a kid I drank gallons of milk, so thanks to my mom I had a solid foundation to build a strong skeleton. As an adult I’m not as diligent (ok, I’m lazy) so I’ve been taking calcium supplements for the last 25 years, believing that I’m still doing a decent job of protecting my bones. Imagine my surprise when I read about a recent report in the British Medical Journal which reported that calcium supplements may increase the risk of heart attack by 30 percent. Say what?\n\nA few important points about this report: \n\n1. Called a meta-analysis, this study was actually a collection from 11 different calcium studies which included 12,000 people (mostly women over 50) taking at least 500 mg calcium supplement a day. This is notable because the results may not hold true for people taking less than 500 mg a day.\n\n2. This study did NOT directly investigate calcium and heart attacks. There was no direct cause-and-effect link.\n\n3. None of the studies included vitamin D. Nowadays, nearly all women over 50 taking calcium supplements ALSO take a vitamin D supplement. We don’t know what effect that combo has on heart attack rates.\n\n4. There was no increase in risk among those who boosted their calcium intake the old-fashioned way― through food.\n\n5. Other scientists called this report “concerning but not convincing,” meaning that more research needs to be done. \n\nSo, what should you do? First, I don’t recommend making any changes to your diet based on the results of a single study. Second, my recommendation is, and always will be, get your nutrients from food first.  The U.S. Recommended Daily Allowance (RDA) for calcium for adult men and women age 19 – 50 is 1,000 mg per day and 1,200 mg per day for the over 50 set. \n\nIn case you’re wondering how you can eat your way to the calcium RDA, the list below can guide you:\n\nVoskos Original Greek Yogurt, 8 ounces - 300 Milligrams (mg) per serving\n\n2 % lowfat milk, 8 ounces - 297 Milligrams (mg) per serving\n\nMozzarella, part skim, 1.5 ounces - 275 Milligrams (mg) per serving\n\nAlmonds, 3 ounces - 210 Milligrams (mg) per serving\n\nCottage cheese, 1% fat, 1 cup - 138 Milligrams (mg) per serving\n\nSpinach, cooked, ½ cup - 120 Milligrams (mg) per serving\n\nThe reality is that most people don’t get enough calcium from their food. Speak to a dietitian to help you decide if you should use supplements to fill in any gaps between what your diet provides and the recommended intake.\n\nIf you do choose to take a calcium supplement, be sure it has at least 400 IU’s of vitamin D. That’s the current RDA but most health experts agree that a minimum daily intake of 1,000 IU’s of vitamin D is best. Personally, I cover all the bases by eating <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Voskos Greek yogurt</a> (love the strawberry!) everyday and taking a calcium plus vitamin D supplement.\n\nTake Home Message: The best things you can to protect your bones AND your heart is to eat a nutrient-rich, well-balanced diet, exercise daily― be sure to include resistance training or weights! ― manage your stress, and spend time with people you love.', 'Do calcium supplements cause heart attacks?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'calcium-supplement-heart-attack', '', '', '2010-10-07 05:00:55', '2010-10-07 12:00:55', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=131', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(164, 8, '2010-10-12 05:00:14', '2010-10-12 12:00:14', 'Lately, I’ve been seeing flashes of footballs, black & white uniformed men and stadiums filled with crowds of fans on T.V…  ’Tis the season for football fanatics!  It’s here, and ladies if you’re not a football fan and your guy is, I don’t have to remind you that this is the time that you will see your man gazing into the TV while glued to his chair until “his” team makes a touchdown…  And, if he plays fantasy football – forget about ever watching a regular show until after the Superbowl!  \n\nBut, if you happen to be a casual fan of football, such as I am, you can enjoy a moderate dose of watching a game or two now and then.  And, along with all the watch parties and multitude of hours spent in front of the TV, there are creative ways to make very tasty yet healthier snacks.  One of my favorites is Pigskin Potatoes.  This is so super easy and so super healthy, it might even make it past the finals and into the Superbowl watch party.  \n\nBasically, just make some baked potatoes and lay out toppings buffet style.  Instead of using high-fat, high-calorie sour cream, replace it with Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Plain Greek Yogurt</a>.  The Greek yogurt has a thick and creamy texture, very similar to sour cream, but without all the calories and saturated fat.  Make sure to serve chives, other veggies and instead of butter, use a butter spray to reduce calories and fat also.  \n\nOf course, we can’t forget the chips and dip.  Again, here’s an opportunity to replace the regular dips with Voskos Plain Yogurt.  Add in a package of dry Ranch Dressing into the yogurt and.. viola!  You’ve got a tasty dip with the same consistency as regular dip but minus the saturated fat and calories.  Make sure you add veggies for the dip and baked chips to further reduce calories and saturated fat.  \n\nSo if you don’t necessarily enjoy football, you can still enjoy the snacks with your football fan or watch party friends and “sideline” the calories and fat.  For more recipe ideas, visit the <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/">Voskos Recipe Blog</a>. \n', 'Football Frenzy', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-football-snacks', '', '', '2010-10-12 05:00:14', '2010-10-12 12:00:14', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=164', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(169, 7, '2010-10-14 05:00:21', '2010-10-14 12:00:21', 'I know the drill: if you set one toe outside, put on sunscreen. I know how important skin protection is, especially for fair-skinned, light-eyed people like me. But, it’s such a PAIN to put the stuff on! Plus, it gets on my clothes and I smell like a coconut. That’s how I rationalize not practicing safe skin care. So, I’m always looking for ways to make up for my negligence and I found a great one. Sun protection from the inside out!\n\nThe answer lies in food rich in anti-oxidants. Such foods reduce the free radical assault caused by scorching sun rays. Free radicals are highly reactive oxygen molecules that damage cells, and are the cause of many skin problems, from dryness to wrinkles to cancer.\n\nEven if you don’t burn easily, it’s still worth treating your skin to a second line of defense. You could see such foods as your body’s insurance against aging and damaged skin.\n\nEarlier research has suggested that certain compounds in the foods you eat may help protect against sun damage. A more recent study backs this up. In a study published in the journal Nutrition Reviews, Israeli researchers recommend “going Greek” with your diet by upping Mediterranean staples such as olive oil, fish, whole grains, beans, fruits, vegetables and yogurt. They suggest that in addition to regular application of sunscreen and appropriate body coverings― hats, beach coverups, etc― a Greek-style diet can help fight the damaging effects of the sun.\n\nMost of the sun-protection benefit is attributed to phytonutrients― compounds that plants make to protect itself against environmental insults. These compounds have tongue-twisting, scientific names such as lycopene, zeaxanthin, and ellagic acid. Brightly colored fruits and vegetables are the best source of these natural sunscreens.\n\nThe best way to protect your skin is to avoid prolonged exposure to sunlight. Do a better job than I do and slather on the sunscreen. You can boost the vitality and resilience of your skin so that sunlight isn’t as likely to transform you skin cells into dangerous little mutants. And you can enjoy brief steps out into the sunlight happy in the knowledge that your skin is well supported by some carefully chosen, delicious foods. I like to think that every time I eat some Voskos Greek yogurt I’m doing something good for my skin. And, I don’t smell like coconut! \n \nFull Study, "Nutritional approach to sun protection: a suggested complement to external strategies" originally <a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1753-4887.2009.00264.x/abstract" target="_blank">published</a> in the January online edition of Nutrition Reviews. \n\n\n', 'Sunscreen In Your Food', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sun-protection-nutrition', '', '', '2010-10-14 05:00:21', '2010-10-14 12:00:21', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=169', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(174, 4, '2010-10-19 05:00:14', '2010-10-19 12:00:14', 'Those who eat breakfast may be less likely to be obese or develop diabetes or heart disease.  If you’re trying to control your weight or lose weight and lower your risk of heart disease and diabetes-breakfast may be the key.  Those who eat breakfast end up eating fewer calories at the end of the day.  In addition, they eat less saturated fat and cholesterol and have better overall nutritional status than those that skip that meal.\nStarting the day with a balance of carbohydrate, protein and a healthy fat choice can get your day off and running.  \n\nWe know that breakfast is not the meal to miss but choosing the right combination is the challenge.  Often, we choose foods that leave us hungry by 10 AM or foods the require preparation and no time so we don’t eat.  What you choose may be more important than if you eat at all.\n\nA lot of people make the statement-“I don’t have enough time” or “When I eat breakfast, I’m hungry for the rest of the day.”   It doesn’t take a long time to eat a meal but the preparation takes time.  The key is to establish a routine and a plan.  It may be helpful to set it out the night before or pack it to go!  \n\nI eat breakfast everyday.  I run every morning but not without my Voskos Greek Yogurt concoction!  I have tried going the distance without the ‘mix’ but I don’t end up getting very far.\n\nFor the past year, I have added pre-nutrition to my run.  The recipe is so simple but oh so satisfying.\n\n1 cup non-fat Voskos Greek Yogurt -plain\n½ cup blueberries\ndrizzle of honey or sweetener to taste\nsprinkling of Nature’s Path Peanut Butter Granola\n\nThis is the perfect mix of protein and carbohydrate for me-I can go the long run and if I need additional nourishment after the run, I may repeat the ‘recipe’ again.\n\nWhen I get the urge to have dessert (which is often), I prefer to have Voskos Greek Yogurt over ice cream.  I love the texture of the non-fat/plain.  I usually top it with a drizzle of chocolate sauce and top with a crunchy cereal.  So fulfilling and satisfying.  Plus, it provides an extra dose of protein (24 grams) to keep me going strong.  It satisfies me and eliminates my reaching for ‘extras’ in the evening.\n', 'Breakfast Is For Champions!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'importance-breakfast', '', '', '2010-10-19 05:00:14', '2010-10-19 12:00:14', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=174', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(178, 4, '2010-11-16 05:00:46', '2010-11-16 12:00:46', 'As I age (ever so gracefully), I am more mindful of what the benefits of a healthy diet involve.  The choices I make have an impact on my health and being healthy and active is how I want to ‘age gracefully.’  Eating a variety of nutrient-dense foods is the key.\n\nAs we age, it is more important that we eat more calcium, fiber, iron, protein and vitamins C, D and folacin.  We lose lean body mass which contributes to a decrease in basal energy metabolism.  To avoid gaining weight, we must reduce our caloric intake or increase activity.  The goal is energy balance-weight maintenance.\n\nThe amount of total body fat typically increases with age.  Generally, it is due to too many calories and not enough activity.  As we age, fat tends to concentrate in the upper body-trunk area and around vital organs.\n\nIn addition, bone density is lost. After menopause, women tend to lose bone mass at an accelerated rate.  The focus has been on osteoporosis-which can lead to fractures and the inability to be as active as we would prefer.\n\nSensory changes also affect our nutritional intake as we age.  Loss of smell and taste make food less appetizing and impact the pleasure of eating.  Trying a variety of foods and new flavors can be the key.\n\nWith all the changes associated with aging, key answers to the problems would be to choose foods high in nutrients in relation to their calories.  These foods are considered “nutrient-dense” foods.  For example, low-fat dairy products are more nutrient-dense than whole-fat products.  The nutrient content is the same (sometimes higher) but they have fewer calories and less fat.  \n\nPeople of all ages need to consume more than 40 nutrients to stay healthy.  With age, choosing a variety of foods and nutrients becomes the key to healthy aging.  Some suggestions to get out of the food rut are:\n     *Eat breakfast foods for lunch/dinner\n     *Choose foods that are colorful and have different textures\n     *Eat at least 5 servings of fruits and vegetables-color is key\n     *Add whole grains to your diet \n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a> has a great consistency and you can make it as sweet as you’d like.  Add some fruit, your choice of sweetening and maybe some crunch for the top and you have a great dessert or morning meal.  \n\nMy favorite is Voskos non-fat plain Greek yogurt.  I usually eat it for breakfast but if I want a light dessert I place about a cup of Voskos in a glass dessert dish, drizzle chocolate sauce on top and a few chopped nuts-Yum!', 'Aging Gracefully', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-aging', '', '', '2010-11-16 05:00:46', '2010-11-16 12:00:46', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=178', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(182, 6, '2010-11-11 05:00:46', '2010-11-11 12:00:46', 'Dairy products are essential for growing bodies. Rich in calcium, potassium, vitamin D, and protein, parents need to ensure their kids are getting enough dairy products in their diet to keep them healthy.\n\nDairy products, such as Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a>, contain calcium to help build and maintain bone mass throughout life.  Specifically during childhood and adolescence, bone mass is built, and a foundation of bone is made.  This foundation is critical to prevent future bone health issues such as osteopenia or osteoporosis (reduced bone mineral density or “porous bones”).  Most research suggests consuming calcium rich foods can prevent these problems.\n\nPotassium is also important for growing bodies. Used to maintain fluid and electrolyte balance, prevent muscle contraction, and essential in brain and nerve function, potassium rich foods such as Voskos Greek Yogurt are important to include on a daily basis.\n\nHow many dairy products do we need to receive daily?\n\nChildren (2-8 years old) = 2 cups daily\nGirls &amp; Boys (9-18 years old) = 3 cups daily\nMen &amp; Women (18 years+) = 3 cups daily\nPregnant &amp; Lactating Women (18 years+) = 3-4 cups daily\n\nIn general, 1 cup yogurt or milk, 1 ½ ounces natural cheese, 1/3 cup shredded cheese, 1 cup pudding, 1 cup frozen yogurt, 2 cups cottage cheese, or ½ cup ricotta cheese is considered 1 cup dairy product.\n\nDairy products make excellent choices as snacks as alternatives to other foods such as chips, cookies, and the like.  These junk foods are traditionally high in salt, fats, and sodium and provide little benefit to kids growing bodies.  Dairy products such as Voskos Greek yogurt are low in fat, and rich in protein, in addition to providing the nutrients as outlined previously.  Switching your kid’s daily snack to a delicious Greek yogurt will reduce the empty calories from these junk foods and nourish their bodies with good nutrition.  Try this recipe for Frozen Greek Yogurt for a sweet after-school or after-dinner treat.\n<h3>Frozen Greek Yogurt Recipe</h3>\n<h4>Ingredients:</h4>\n3 cups plain 0% fat Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 tablespoon lemon juice\n5 tablespoons honey\n10 chopped fresh mint leaves\n<h4>Directions:</h4>\nStir together the yogurt and lemon juice until smooth in a freezer-safe metal bowl. Combine the honey and mint in a small bowl. Pour the honey mixture on top of the yogurt, stir so that the honey combines with the yogurt but is not blended in completely. Cover bowl and freeze for 1 to 2 hours. OPTIONAL: use all fruit preserves instead of honey for variation of this fantastic treat!\n\nRemember your dairy products! Choose <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Voskos Greek Yogurt</a> for a healthy snack, and to provide essential nutrients for your growing kids!\n\nPhoto credit: <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/galant/2552806811/" target="blank">The Bitten Word</a>', 'Dairy for Kids', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dairy-for-kids', '', '', '2010-11-11 05:00:46', '2010-11-11 12:00:46', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=182', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(192, 6, '2010-11-02 05:00:25', '2010-11-02 12:00:25', 'Fall is here, the leaves are changing color, and holidays are just upon us.  The fall season is actually one of the most abundant seasons of the year when it comes to finding fresh produce.  Produce is vibrant with color, which also means it is packed full of nutrients such as fiber, vitamins and minerals.  The following are some excellent choices during this season:\n\nFruit: Apples, Grapes, Pears, Plums, Rhubarb, Tomatoes\n\nVegetables:  Bell peppers, Cabbage, Cauliflower, Corn, Cucumbers, Eggplant, Greens, Lettuce, Okra, Onions, Peas, Potatoes, Pumpkins, Radishes, Spinach, Squash, Sweet Potatoes, Turnips\n\nPurchasing produce in-season provides a product with a higher nutritive content, due to the fact that the fruits and vegetables do not need to be stored or transported at length to get to your food stores. The longer the food has to travel, the more energy it takes to get it there, and the lower the vitamin and mineral content. This sustainable way of eating reduces the impact on our environment (less fuel costs and gas emissions in our air).  Further, the quicker the food is picked and consumed, the greater amount of vitamins and minerals in our food.  Check what is available locally in your area at localharvest.org.\n\nPumpkins are one of the wonderfully abundant produce items available this season, and aside from pumpkin pie, this squash can be used in many ways in recipes.  Pumpkin is a good source of fiber, Vitamin A, Vitamin C, Vitamin E, riboflavin, potassium, copper and manganese.\n\nThe following recipes are a great way to incorporate one of our season’s abundant squashes, but also a great way to incorporate calcium and protein in your diet with Voskos Greek Yogurt.\n<h3>Pumpkin Pie Smoothie</h3>\n1 cup pumpkin puree, chilled (canned pumpkin can be used if fresh is not available)\n1 banana, frozen\n8 oz Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain, non-fat)\n1 cup skim milk\n½ tsp cinnamon\n½ tsp nutmeg\n1 TBSP honey\n\nDirections:\nAdd all ingredients to blender, and blend until smooth. Enjoy!\n<h3>Pumpkin Pancakes</h3>\n1 cup whole wheat flour\n1 TBSP sugar\n2 tsp baking powder\n½ tsp cinnamon\n1 cup skim milk\n2 TBSP light butter, melted\n1 egg or 1 banana, mashed\n½ cup pumpkin puree, chilled (canned pumpkin can be used if fresh is not available)\n6 oz Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain, non-fat)\n\nDirections\nIn a small mixing bowl, combine milk, light butter, egg or banana, pumpkin and yogurt. Mix well. Combine flour, sugar, baking powder, and cinnamon in a large mixing bowl.  Add wet ingredients to flour mixture and stir until moist.  Batter should be lumpy.  Lightly coat a griddle or skillet with cooking spray and bring to medium heat.  Pour batter on hot griddle and cook until bubbles form, flip and cook until golden brown.  Serve with warm syrup or dust with cinnamon sugar. Enjoy!\n\nRemember when you are choosing produce; try to pick in-season options because this will give you the greatest nutritive content, and better yet, most often the best value for your dollar. Seasonal produce is abundant, thus typically at a lower cost for you!\n\nPhoto credit: <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/hlkljgk/4061179726/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Heather Katsoulis</a>', 'How to Incorporate Voskos in your Seasonal Recipes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pumpkin-recipes', '', '', '2010-11-02 05:00:25', '2010-11-02 12:00:25', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=192', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(235, 3, '2010-10-07 10:02:31', '2010-10-07 17:02:31', 'Tomorrow, Friday October 8th, Voskos will be at the <a href="http://www.blogher.com/blogherfood-fete-welcome-party" target="_blank">Blogher/Food Fete event</a> to showcase Voskos Greek Yogurt and to announce the launch of our excitign new product, <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.facebook.com/YoGreek">YoGreek</a>, live, to 300 food bloggers! Many bloggers in the BlogHer network have already blogged about Voskos. This is our opportunity to finally meet some of you in person. We can''t wait!\n\nFollow us on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://twitter.com/GoVoskos">Twitter</a> this Friday as we''ll be live-tweeting highlights from the event.\n\nBon appetit!', 'Blogher Food Fete Party is here!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cant-wait-for-the-blogherfood-fete-party', '', '', '2010-10-07 10:02:31', '2010-10-07 17:02:31', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=235', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(239, 3, '2010-09-13 12:42:31', '2010-09-13 19:42:31', 'Eating a lot of Greek yogurt these days? Well besides the traditional, topping  it with fruit, nuts, or granola try using it in things like dressings, sauces, and dips. Check out our Roasted Red Pepper Dip – it’s filled with flavor, veggies, and protein.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n\n2 cloves garlic\n1, 7-oz jars roasted red peppers\n1, 8 oz <strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt (Plain, Non-Fat)</strong>\n1/2 teaspoon cumin\n1/2 cup chopped tomato\n1/4 cup chopped green onions\n2 cucumbers, sliced\n2 green peppers, sliced\n1 pkg of mini cut and peeled carrots\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n\nStrain juice from the jar of peppers. Combine the garlic and peppers in a food processor and blend until smooth. Transfer to a bowl and hand-blend in Voskos Greek Yogurt, cumin, tomato, and onions. Season with salt and pepper.\n\nCover and refrigerate at least 4 hours. Serve with cut vegetables and enjoy!', 'Voskos Roasted Red Pepper Dip', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-roasted-red-pepper-dip', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=239', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(252, 3, '2010-09-15 11:59:56', '2010-09-15 18:59:56', 'In the mood for some chocolatey goodness? A crunchy chocolate graham crust and creamy Voskos Greek Yogurt filling make this pie a standout. Be sure to use the Non-Fat Vanilla Bean flavor. This recipe is courtesy of Ward W. Bond, Ph.D. <a title="Dr. Ward Bond" href="http://www.drwardbond.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">www.drwardbond.com</a>\n\nServings: 8\nTotal Time: 2 Hours\nActive Time: 5 minutes\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 Organic Chocolate Graham Crust (Oreo if you must)\n1 8 ounce Organic Whipped Topping\n1 8 ounce Voskos Greek Yogurt Non-Fat Vanilla Bean yogurt (Any Voskos flavor or Plain will work, too!)\n1/2 - 1 tsp Vanilla Extract\n1  Dagoba Organic Dark Chocolate (59%) Bar optional for topping\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nGently combine whipped topping and yogurt in a large bowl until well blended. Do not use a mixer. Mix by hand only until well blended.\nPour into graham cracker crust. Grate chocolate shavings on top for presentation. Break some into chucks at top.\n\nPlace in refrigerator (uncovered) at least two hours or until set. 24 hours is best.\nNo Guilt! Be creative! Your family and friends will love it!', 'Voskos Low-Fat Greek Yogurt Pie', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-low-fat-greek-yogurt-pie', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=252', 0, 'post', '', 4),
(257, 3, '2010-10-04 12:07:33', '2010-10-04 19:07:33', 'Ready for a great low-carb alternative to mashed potatoes? Using cauliflower instead of potatoes for your traditional "mashed potatoes" is a great, healthy alternative because it''s without all the starch of potatoes. Add some non-fat Voskos Greek Yogurt, and you won''t miss a thing! \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 (5.3-ounce) container plain, fat-free Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 head cauliflower, cored and roughly chopped\n1 small or 1/2 medium onion, peeled and quartered\n2 cloves garlic, peeled\n2 tablespoons butter\n1/4 cup grated Pecorino Romano cheese\nSalt and pepper to taste\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nBring a large pot of water to a boil. (You can boil your cauliflower in some chicken broth for a bit of extra flavor.) Add cauliflower and cook for about 8 minutes or until fork tender. Drain. In a food processor, blend onion and garlic. Add cauliflower, butter, greek yogurt, cheese, salt and pepper and blend some more. You want the finished product to be like a thick puree. \n\nNutritional Information (1/2 cup) \n124 calories; 6.3 g total fat; 2.2 g saturated fat; 4 mg cholesterol; 168 mg sodium; 10.8 g carbs; 4.1 g fiber; 2.3 g sugars; 8.8 g protein.\n', 'Cauliflower Mashed Potatoes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'cauliflower-mashed-potatoes-2', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=257', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(267, 3, '2010-11-04 05:00:35', '2010-11-04 12:00:35', 'In this video, <a href="http://www.christineavanti.com/" target="_blank">Christine Avanti</a>, celebrity nutritionist and author of the book "Skinny Chicks Don''t Eat Salads," explains that you can eat a lot of great food, feel full, and still lose weight. Christine talks about the power of stabilizing blood sugar and how it helps to lose weight.\n\nChristine warns against trying crazy fad diets and explains, "You can eat carbs and protein in each meal, speed up your metabolism and lose weight. The only way to lose weight is to eat real food, stabilize your blood sugar and speed up your metabolism."\n\nSample meals Christine recommends include egg white and veggie scramble plus avocado and fruit for breakfast, Greek yogurt with nuts and fruit for lunch, baked chips, cheese and fruit for a snack, and a dinner of salmon, brown rice and asparagus.\n\n<strong>Christine explains she likes Voskos Greek Yogurt because "It has more protein than any other yogurt out there on the market" and adds "When you find it, buy a lot of it, because you get a lot of protein for a lot less money." </strong>\n\n"It''s all about getting away from the idea of starving yourself and putting yourself on a diet. It needs to be a lifestyle change," says Christine. We couldn''t agree more!\n\n<object width="480" height="385"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/lITfkju0grA?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/lITfkju0grA?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="480" height="385"></embed></object>', 'VIDEO: Skinny Chicks Don’t Eat Salads!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'video-skinny-chicks-dont-eat-salad', '', '', '2010-11-04 05:00:35', '2010-11-04 12:00:35', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=267', 0, 'post', '', 1);
