(413, 3, '2010-11-09 05:00:32', '2010-11-09 12:00:32', 'Current research states infants should start solid foods between 4-6 months; however it is important for parents to ensure developmental readiness in their children.  There are some signs to look for to determine if your little one is ready to start solids:\n\n1) Can your child sit up with help or support?\n2) While on their tummy, can he/she push up on his/her arms with straight elbows?\n3) Does your infant still have an extrusion reflex (pushes food out of mouth with tongue)?\n4) Can your baby move pureed food forward/backward in mouth with tongue?\n5) Does he/she recognize the spoon and hold his/her mouth open as spoon approaches?\n\nIf you answered YES to all of these, your infant is ready to start solids.  But before you go out and purchase jarred foods, look to your own kitchen for ideas of where to start. \n\nHomemade baby foods are easy to make, and if you take some time to plan, making your own baby food can be:\n1) Less costly – jarred food adds up! Making your own foods enables parents to use foods they may be preparing for the rest of the family. \n2) Creative – jarred foods are limited in variety.  Making your own expands your choices, and will also increase your child’s future taste preferences.  \n3) Convenient – use the foods in your own refrigerator and pantry to prepare for your baby. \n\nWhere to start? Typically, it is recommended to start with vegetables, due to an infant’s innate preference for sweets. Try starting with orange vegetables including: squash (including acorn, butternut, and pumpkin), carrots, sweet potatoes. Then progress to green vegetables: peas, green beans, broccoli, and spinach.  Continue with avocado, broccoli, cauliflower, zucchini, the possibilities are endless.  \n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt is a great addition to a baby’s diet.  Plain, original Voskos is a great source of fat recommended for baby’s brain development.  Further, it is wonderful mixed into homemade baby foods for additional protein, probiotics, and calcium.\n\n<a href="http://www.wciu.com/youandme.php?section=home&assets=videos&assetID=10003890" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">WCIU TV</a> asked me to give my input on homemade baby foods. What to make, how to make it, and foods to avoid in homemade baby meals:\n\n<object width="425" height="344"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/u32WfyO73jY?hl=en&fs=1"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/u32WfyO73jY?hl=en&fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="425" height="344"></embed></object>\n \nPhoto Credit: <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/yoshimov/24885536/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Yoshimov</a>', 'VIDEO: Homemade Baby Foods for your Infant', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'homemade-baby-food', '', '', '2010-11-09 05:00:32', '2010-11-09 12:00:32', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=413', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(415, 3, '2010-08-10 14:06:42', '2010-08-10 21:06:42', 'Makes 2 9-inch layers\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n¼ pound butter, at room temperature\n1 ½ cup sugar\n2 eggs\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\n2 ¼ cups unsifted all-purpose flour\n2 teaspoons double acting baking powder\n¾ teaspoon baking soda\n½ teaspoon salt\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 cup mashed very ripe bananas (about 3 bananas)\n½ cup coarsely chopped walnuts or pecans\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a large mixing bowl cream the butter and sugar until thoroughly blended.\n2. Add the eggs, one at a time, beating well after each.\n3. Beat in the vanilla extract.\n4. Sift together the flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt.\n5. Add to the creamed mixture in 3 parts, alternating with the yogurt and beginning and ending with the flour.\n6. Stir the batter after each addition until smooth.\n7. Stir in the bananas and nuts, mixing until just blended.\n8. Turn into 2 well-greased 9x1 ½ inch round cake pans dusted with flour.\n9. Bake in a preheated 350°F oven about 35 minutes or until a food pick inserted in the centers of the cakes comes out clean.\n10. Remove from the oven and let cool in the pans 10 minutes.\n11. Remove from the pans and cool thoroughly on wire racks.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Banana Cake', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'banana-cake', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=415', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(417, 3, '2010-08-10 14:09:37', '2010-08-10 21:09:37', 'Makes 10 to 12 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n24 ounces cream cheese, at room temperature\n6 eggs, separated\n1 cup sugar\n2 tablespoons all-purpose flour\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 teaspoon freshly squeezed and strained lemon juice\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\n1 ½ teaspoons grated lemon rind\n1 ½ teaspoons grated orange rind\n¼ teaspoon cream tartar\n1 quart strawberries, hulled\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a large mixing bowl beat the cream cheese with the egg yolks until the mixture is very smooth.\n2. Beat in the sugar, flour, yogurt, lemon juice, vanilla extract, lemon rind, and orange rind.\n3. Beat the egg whites with the cream of tartar until they stand in soft, stiff peaks.\n4. Fold into the cheese mixture.\n5. Pour into an ungreased 9x3 ½-inch spring-form pan.\n6. Bake in a preheated 325°F oven about 1 hour and 30 minutes or until the center of the cake is firm.\n7. Remove the cake from the oven and allow it to cool at room temperature 2 hours before removing it from the pan.\n8. Serve at room temperature or chilled, accompanied with a bowl of the strawberries.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Cheesecake with Strawberries', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'cheesecake-with-strawberries', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=417', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(421, 3, '2010-08-11 14:12:32', '2010-08-11 21:12:32', 'Makes 24 squares\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup unsifted all-purpose flour\n½ cup sugar\n3 tablespoons cocoa\n1 teaspoon double acting baking powder\n¼ teaspoon salt\n¼ pound butter\n1 egg, separated\n1 teaspoon vanilla extract\n½ cup finely chopped walnuts\n8 ounces cream cheese, at room temperature\n1 cup sugar\n½ cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 tablespoon all-purpose flour\n¼ teaspoon salt\n2 teaspoons grated orange rind\n½ teaspoon vanilla extract\n1 egg\nShaved sweet chocolate\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Line the bottom and 2 opposite sides of a 9x9-inch baking pan with a strip of aluminum foil that overlaps the sides.\n2. Grease the foil and the exposed pan sides.\n3. In a mixing bowl combine the 1 cup flour, ½ cup sugar, cocoa, baking powder, and salt.\n4. Cut in the butter until the mixture resembles coarse meal.\n5. Add the egg yolk to the flour mixture (reserve the egg white).\n6. Add the 1 teaspoon vanilla extract and walnuts and mix well.\n7. Turn into the baking pan and press firmly over the pan bottom.\n8. Bake in a preheated 325°F oven 15 minutes.\n9. Meanwhile, in a large mixing bowl combine the cream cheese, ⅓ cup sugar, yogurt, 1 tablespoon flour, salt, orange rind, ½ teaspoon vanilla extract, egg, and the reserved egg white. Beat until well blended.\n10. Remove the pan from the oven and pour in the cheese mixture.\n11. Bake about 25 minutes or until set.\n12. Remove from the oven and cool the cake in the pan 1 hour.\n13. Garnish the top with the shaved chocolate.\n14. Cover and chill thoroughly.\n15. To serve, lift out the cake by grasping the overlapping aluminum foil and cut into squares.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Chocolate Cheese Squares', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chocolate-cheese-squares', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=421', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(423, 3, '2010-08-11 14:15:07', '2010-08-11 21:15:07', 'Serves 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n3 cups Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a>\n1 cup hulled strawberries, raspberries, or blueberries\n1 cup cherries, stemmed and pitted\n1 cup sliced peaches or nectarines, sprinkled with fresh lemon juice to prevent darkening\nHoney\nGround cinnamon\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Turn the yogurt into an attractive glass bowl placed in a larger bowl filled with crushed ice.\n2. This will keep the yogurt well chilled.\n3. Surround with dishes of the berries, cherries, and peaches, or nectarines.\n4. Serve accompanied with a small pitcher of honey and, if you wish, the cinnamon.\n5. Allow guests to help themselves.\n6. Each person spoons some yogurt into a bowl, adds the fruit of his choice, drizzles with honey, and tops with a dusting of cinnamon, if desired.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Fresh Fruit with Greek Yogurt', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'fresh-fruits-with-yogurt', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=423', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(426, 3, '2010-08-12 14:19:18', '2010-08-12 21:19:18', 'Serves 4 to 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup heavy cream\n½ cup sugar\n1 ½ teaspoons unflavored gelatin\n3 tablespoons cold water\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n2 tablespoons Grand Marnier or strawberry liqueur\n2 cups hulled strawberries or raspberries, crushed and sweetened\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Combine the cream and sugar in a small saucepan.\n2. Cook over low heat until the sugar is dissolved, stirring constantly.\n3. Remove from the heat.\n4. Soften the gelatin in the cold water and stir it into the cream mixture until it is dissolved.\n5. Let cool, then beat in the yogurt with a wire whisk or a rotary beater until the mixture is well blended and smooth.\n6. Stir in the Grand Marnier or strawberry liqueur. \n7. Pour into lightly oiled 2-cup mold or individual molds.\n8. Cover and chill until form.\n9. Remove from mold and serve with the strawberries or raspberries.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Yogurt Cream Dessert', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'yogurt-cream', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=426', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(428, 3, '2010-08-12 14:21:36', '2010-08-12 21:21:36', 'Serves 4 to 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 envelope (1 tablespoon) unflavored gelatin\n¼ cup cold water\n2 eggs, separated\n½ cup sugar\n¼ teaspoon salt\n½ cup milk\n½ teaspoon vanilla extract\n½ cup very strong black coffee\n1 cup Voskos Greek yogurt \nLadyfingers\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Soften the gelatin in the water.\n2. Beat the egg yolks in the top part of a double boiler.\n3. Add ¼ cup of the sugar and the salt.\n4. Gradually stir in the milk.\n5. Cover over hot water, until thickened, stirring constantly.\n6. Add the gelatin and stir until it is completely dissolve.\n7. Stir in the vanilla extract and coffee and chill until slightly thickened.\n8. Beat the egg whites until stiff.\n9. Gradually beat in the remaining sugar.\n10. Fold into the gelatin mixture, then fold in the yogurt.\n11. Line dessert glasses with the ladyfingers.\n12. Spoon the gelatin mixture into the glasses.\n13. Cover and chill until firm.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Coffee Mousse', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'coffee-mousse', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=428', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(430, 3, '2010-08-13 14:24:44', '2010-08-13 21:24:44', 'Makes 1 ½ quarts\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 cups milk\n4 egg yolks\n¾ cup sugar\n4 ounces semisweet chocolate, melted\n1 ½ teaspoons vanilla extract\n2 cups Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a medium enameled or stainless steel saucepan bring the milk almost to a boil.\n2. Remove from the heat and set aside.\n3. Combine the egg yolks and sugar in a bowl.\n4. Beat them with a wire whisk or rotary or electric beater until pale yellow and thickened.\n5. Gradually beat in the hot milk.\n6. Pour the mixture back into the saucepan and cook over moderately low heat, it thickens to a custard that lightly coats the spoon.\n7. Do not allow the mixture to boil or it will curdle.\n8. Stir in the melted chocolate and vanilla extract.\n9. Strain the custard through a fine sieve into a large mixing bowl and allow it to cool to room temperature.\n10. In a bowl beat the yogurt with a wire whisk until smooth.\n11. Add to the cooled custard and mix thoroughly.\n12. Freeze in a 2-quart or larger hand-crack or electric ice cream freezer, following the manufacturer’s directions.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Frozen Chocolate Yogurt', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'frozen-chocolate-yogurt', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=430', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(432, 3, '2010-08-13 14:26:29', '2010-08-13 21:26:29', 'Makes 1 quart\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 egg\n6 tablespoons sugar\n¼ cup light corn syrup\n¾ cup heavy cream\n¾ cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 ½ teaspoons vanilla extract\n¼ teaspoon salt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Place all the ingredients in a medium-sized bowl and mix thoroughly.\n2. Refrigerate 2 hours or until well chilled.\n3. Freeze in a 1-quart or larger hand-crack or electric ice cream freezer, following the manufacturer’s directions.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Vanilla Yogurt Ice Cream', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'vanilla-yogurt-ice-cream', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=432', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(434, 3, '2010-08-14 14:28:31', '2010-08-14 21:28:31', 'Serves 4\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n6 ounces cream cheese or Neufchâtel cheese, at room temperature\n1 cup finely crumbled feta cheese\n½ cup or more Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n2 tablespoons finely chopped chives or scallions (include 2 inches of the green tops of the scallions)\n2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh dill\n2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh mint\nSalt to taste\n1 small garlic clove, crushed, or to taste\nTomato slices\nCucumber slices\nBlack olives\nParsley sprigs\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a mixing bowl mash the cream cheese with a fork. \n2. Add the feta cheese and yogurt and beat vigorously with a wooden spoon until the mixture is well blended and fluffy.\n3. Beat in the chives, dill, mint, salt, and garlic.\n4. Taste and adjust the seasoning.\n5. Cover and chill.\n6. Close to serving time, mound the cheese and herb mixture in the center of a platter.\n7. Arrange the tomato and cucumber slices, olives, and parsley sprigs in a decorative pattern around it.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Cheese and Herb Spread', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'cheese-and-herb-spread', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=434', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(436, 3, '2010-08-14 14:30:24', '2010-08-14 21:30:24', 'Serves 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n½ pint low-fat cottage cheese, drained\n½ cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n2 teaspoons caraway seeds, crushed or whole\n1 tablespoon capers, minced (optional)\n¾ teaspoon dry mustard\nSalt to taste\nFreshly ground black pepper to taste\n½ small cucumber, peeled, seeded, and finely chopped\n4 scallions, finely chopped, including 2 inches of the green tops\n½ cup finely chopped parsley\nSweet Hungarian paprika\nSalad greens\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Force the cheese through a ricer or fine sieve into a mixing bowl.\n2. Add the yogurt, caraway seeds, capers (if desired), mustard, and salt and pepper and stir until well blended.\n3. Add the cucumber, green pepper, scallions, and parsley and mix gently but thoroughly.\n4. Taste and adjust the seasoning.\n5. Cover and chill 1 hour.\n6. Transfer to a serving dish.\n7. Sprinkle with the paprika and garnish with the salad greens.\n8. Serve with rye or pumpernickel bread.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Vegetable and Cheese Appetizer', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'vegetable-and-cheese-appetizer', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=436', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(438, 3, '2010-06-15 19:59:58', '2010-06-16 02:59:58', 'Voskos Greek Yogurt offers a beauty solution for our skin.  Our food choices are connected to the function, appearance, and health of our body.  Consumers spend a lot of money on skincare products and these items can be costly.  Voskos Greek Yogurt offers a more affordable and tasty beauty solution that can improve the skin from within. \n \nThe human skin is the largest and most visible organ of the body.  It can enhance or detract from physical appearance.  The skin covers other organs, serves as a barrier against germs, helps to regulate body temperature and contains sensory nerve receptors. How we feed it is important as it affects our health, well-being and of great importance in American society, how we look. \n \nFeeding our skin means giving it the “raw materials" that it needs.  These raw materials are found in foods packed with nutrients, helping our skin look and function at its best. Some of these raw materials include:\n \n<strong>Water</strong>: 65% of our body is made up of this vital nutrient.  Adequately hydrated skin cells reward us with enhanced health, increased energy, and a radiant complexion.  Dehydrated skin over a period of time becomes dry and wrinkled. \n \n<strong>Essential Fatty Acids</strong>: Americans don’t eat enough essential fatty acids found in omega 3s, which help to prevent skin lesions including dry, patchy skin.  Studies have found that people whose diets were high in these fatty acids had less skin wrinkling than those with diets higher in saturated fats. \n \n<strong>B Vitamins</strong>: Deficiencies in B vitamins, particularly B6, B12, biotin and niacin can cause dermatitis, skin hypersensitivity, and dry skin. B vitamins are found in whole grain, green leafy vegetables, meats, fish, eggs and milk.  \n \n<strong>Vitamin C</strong>: Vitamin C is a necessary component in the formation of collagen, an important protein in skin. A deficiency in Vitamin C can cause rough, scaly discolored skin. \n\n<strong>Iron</strong>: Iron works with Vitamin C to build and maintain collagen. Iron is found in meats, fish, and legumes to name a few. A deficiency in iron can cause dry, itchy skin, and a clinical deficiency can contribute to concave nails.\n \n<strong>Phenolic Compounds</strong>: These compounds have antioxidant properties and have shown to activate endothelial nitric oxide production.  Nitric oxide helps blood vessels to expand and remain elastic, improving circulation and delivering nutrients to skin tissues. Black tea, green tea, and red wine contain phenolic compounds. \n\n<strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt</strong>: While not a direct raw material, Voskos Greek Yogurt plays an important role in enhancing the absorption and utilization of raw materials. Voskos Greek Yogurt contains five live and active multi-bacterial strains to improve and help maintain our own gut flora. This boosts immune system functioning as well as nutrient absorption, all essential to our skin and body.  \n\nAccording to <a href="http://healthnewsdigest.com/site/lay.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">June Lay</a>, nutritionist and author of It’s Not a Diet, It’s Creative Eating, “It is important to note that a yogurt containing active live culture will NOT necessarily offer all the health benefits.  Probiotics are live bacteria that are beneficial to your health, when eaten in an adequate amount.”  Voskos Greek Yogurt has five different strains of bacteria, containing billions of live and active bacterial bases on a 100 gram serving -- adequate to offer health benefits.\n', 'BEAUTY AND THE GREEK', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'beauty-and-the-greek', '', '', '2010-06-15 19:59:58', '2010-06-16 02:59:58', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=438', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(440, 3, '2010-08-15 14:34:00', '2010-08-15 21:34:00', 'Makes about 16 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup fine French bread crumbs, lightly toasted\n3 tablespoons freshly grated Parmesan cheese\n28 ounces cream cheese, at room temperature\n4 eggs\n¾ cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Combine the bread crumbs and Parmesan cheese.\n2. Sprinkle the inside of a buttered metal cheesecake pan 8 inches wide and 3 inches deep with the mixture.\n3. Shake the pan so that the bottom and sides are thoroughly coated with the crumb mixture.\n4. Shake out the excess crumbs.\n5. In a large mixing bowl combine the cream cheese, eggs, and yogurt.\n6. Beat until thoroughly blended and smooth.\n7. Turn the batter into the prepared pan and shake gently to level it.\n8. Place the pan in a slightly larger pan, making certain that the edges of the pans do not touch. \n9. Pour boiling water into the larger pan to a depth of 2 inches.\n10. Bake in a preheated 300°F over 1 hour and 40 minutes or until the center of the cake is firm.\n11. When done, turn off the oven and allow the cake to remain inside 1 hour longer.\n12. Lift the cheesecake out of the layer pan and place it on a wire rack to cook 2 hours or until it reaches room temperature.\n13. To unmold, place a flat plate over the cake pan and invert.\n14. Carefully remove the cake pan.\n15. Gently place a serving plate over the cake and invert again, being careful not to exert pressure on the cake.\n16. Serve at room temperature, or cover and chill well before serving.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Savory Cheesecake', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'savory-cheesecake', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=440', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(441, 3, '2010-09-03 20:05:46', '2010-09-04 03:05:46', '<strong>GET BACK TO HEALTHY EATING WITH VOSKOS FOR BACK-TO-SCHOOL</strong>\n<em>Improve Children’s Dietary Intake with Proper Breakfast and Lunch Boxes</em>\n\n<strong>Sun Valley, CA—September 01, 2010—</strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt helps avoid “dining hall disasters” along with preventing childhood obesity with easy back-to-school lunch preparation tips.  School is starting, which means kids are back in the lunchroom making healthy and not-so-healthy eating decisions.  Parents and children alike can make better, healthier choices by packing more nutritious school lunches.\n\nRecent research from the Journal of Epidemiology Community Health reported that lunch accounts for 25-35% of daily intake for children.  However, packed lunches may be lacking in nutritional value, specifically high in sodium and added sugars.  This research from Europe reviewed the new UK requirements for school lunch programs in an attempt to improve the contents of packed lunches.  Government school meal standards in England, as similar to the National School Lunch Program, indicate school meals must contain a portion of fruit, vegetables, dairy, good quality meat, fish or protein food, and low-fat starchy food such as potatoes and pasta.\n\nUS Research from Preventing Chronic Disease2 found that adolescents who typically brought their lunch from home five days per week ate fast food on fewer occasions; consumed fewer servings of soda, fried potatoes, and high-sugar foods; and ate more fruit and vegetables compared with adolescents who never brought their lunch to school.\n\n“Getting your kids involved with packing lunch will assist in making healthier eating decisions”, says <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.feedkids.com/" target="_blank">Lara Field</a>, MS, RD, CSP, LDN.  “It is vital to make time in advance, perhaps the night before, and pack a sensible lunch to get your kids on a healthy track,” adds Field.  Lunch preparation can be a fun activity for the whole family. Having children get hands-on with lunch preparation can help them feel in control and proud to eat their meal.\n\nMs. Field suggests lunch boxes should include the following:\n\n1) <strong>Calcium-rich dairy product, such as Voskos Greek Yogurt</strong>.  “I love Greek yogurt due to its creamy texture, and high protein content”, remarks Field.  “Protein will keep your kids feeling fuller for longer, and crave less empty calories later in the day.”\n\n2) <strong>Fresh fruit</strong>; Avoid canned or processed fruit which contain excess sugar.\n\n3) <strong>Lean meat or protein alternative</strong>; try low-fat turkey breast or soup filled with beans, which has added fiber to keep your kids feeling satisfied.\n\n4) <strong>Sliced vegetables</strong>; vary the colors, try jicama, bell peppers, cucumbers, sugar snap peas – the possibilities are endless – and veggies pack a satisfying crunch, taking the place of chips.\n\n5) <strong>Whole grains</strong>; Choose products with at least 3 grams of fiber per serving.\n\n# # #\n\nMedia Contact:\nVanessa Nielsen\nvoskos.com\nvanessa@voskos.com\n818.504.1775', 'GET BACK TO HEALTHY EATING WITH VOSKOS ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'back-to-school-nutrition', '', '', '2010-09-03 20:05:46', '2010-09-04 03:05:46', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=441', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(442, 3, '2010-08-16 14:35:42', '2010-08-16 21:35:42', 'Serves 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 Partially Baked Pie Pastry\n3 large eggs\n¾ cup milk\n¾ cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n½ teaspoon salt or to taste\n1/8 teaspoon ground white pepper \n1/8 teaspoon ground nutmeg \n6 slices bacon, cooked crisp and crumbled\n4 ounces Gruyère cheese, grated\n¼ cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese (optional)\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Prepare the pastry as directed in the recipe and set aside.\n2. In a large bowl beat the eggs, then beat in the milk, yogurt, salt, pepper, and nutmeg until well blended.\n3. Mix in the bacon.\n4. Spread the cheese evenly over the bottom of the partially baked pastry.\n5. Pour the egg mixture over the cheese.\n6. Bake in preheated 375°F oven about 35 minutes or until the custard is set and a knife inserted into it comes out clean. Serve at once.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Cheese and Bacon Quiche', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'cheese-and-bacon-quiche', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=442', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(444, 3, '2010-08-16 21:56:26', '2010-08-17 04:56:26', 'Serves 4\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 ¼ pounds pumpkin, peeled and cubed\n2 ¾ cups chicken broth\n½ cup chopped onion\n1 cup chopped scallions (white portions only)\nSalt to taste\nGround white pepper\nGround cayenne pepper to taste \n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n4 thin slices tomato\nNon-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt (garnish)\n¼ cup finely chopped scallions (green portions only)\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a heavy pot or saucepan combine the pumpkin, chicken broth, onion, and white portions of scallions.\n2. Bring to a boil over high heat.\n3. Reduce the heat to low, cover, and simmer about 20 minutes or until the pumpkin is tender.\n4. Force the mixture through a fine sieve or purée in an electric blender. Season with the salt and pepper.\n5. Cover and chill thoroughly.\n6. Stir in the yogurt until well blended.\n7. Taste and adjust the seasoning.\n8. Ladle the soup into chilled individual bowls or cups and top each serving with a tomato slice, a dollop of yogurt, and a sprinkling of chopped green scallion tops.\n9. Serve immediately.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Pumpkin Soup', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'pumpkin-soup', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=444', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(445, 3, '2010-11-09 20:19:56', '2010-11-10 03:19:56', '<strong>VOSKOS GREEK YOGURT KICKS THE COMMON COLD TO THE CURB</strong>\n<em>The Secret to Preventing Sickness Is In the Food We Eat</em>\n\n<strong>Sun Valley, CA—November 09, 2010—</strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt offers fuel to fight sickness this winter. Depending on where we live, temperatures typically drop in September, rain begins in October, and fireplaces heat up through March. It is important to stay warm, drink lots of fluids, keep hands clean to avoid germs, and eat the right food. \n\nThe foods we eat directly affect our immune systems both positively and negatively. While there are variables we cannot control such as genetic predispositions and many environmental factors, we can control the food we put into our bodies. The Food Pyramid says we should eat 3-4 servings of veggies; 2-4 servings of fruits; 2-3 servings of protein; and 6-11 servings of grains per day to maintain good health. Additionally, the daily amount of dairy recommended varies depending on age: children 2-8 years old should have 2 cups per day and once over the age of 9, both males and females should consume 3 cups per day. To top that off, we should consume an adequate amount of probiotics in our daily food-dose, especially this winter.\n\nProbiotics promote health, prevent disease and strengthen the body''s immune responses. A strong immune system maintains heath and reduces illness, including the flu! Probiotics are essentially the bacteria that keeps us healthy. According to a health and nutrition article1, “Most of us think of bacteria as the bad guys causing disease and illness. However, certain types of bacteria help keep us healthy.” Probiotics are the good guys that help maintain and restore the balance of both "good" and "bad" bacteria that is necessary for a healthy digestive and immune system. \n\nThe ABC News Medical Unit released new evidence last year that probiotics may fight against the common cold and flu because they have a preventive effect. The article discussed a study sponsored by Danisco (Danish nutritional supplement company that makes probiotics products), which found evidence that "about 60 to 80 percent of our immune cells are associated with gut [cells]. Hitting the immune system through the gut makes sense.” Additionally, the Medical Director of the Atlanta Center for Holistic and Integrative Medicine, Dr. Tasneem Bhatia, says, "introducing friendly bacteria into the digestive system improves how we absorb vitamins, nutrients and co-factors, so overall, immunity is boosted.”\n \n<strong>So, how do we give germs the boot while boosting our immune system?</strong>\nEat Voskos Greek Yogurt! Voskos Greek yogurt contains live and active probiotics, which confer a health benefit to the body when administered in adequate amounts. No other probiotic supplement on the market gives us the taste and additional nutrients like Voskos Greek yogurt. Voskos Greek yogurt contains extensive multi-health benefits and an amount of bacteria cells that research indicates is beneficial to our diets. \n\nStudies show that “probiotics – live bacteria that can benefit health – might have a place alongside vegetables, legumes, whole grains and regular exercise in our strategies to lower [the] risk of cancer” and staying healthy year-round.  Additionally, Voskos Greek Yogurt contains a whopping 24 grams of protein per one 8 ounce container. Each 7 grams of protein is equal to 1 ounce of meat (2-3 ounces of meat equals 1 serving).  Hence, eating one container of Voskos gives our body not only one-third its daily requirement of calcium, but also one full serving of high quality protein (milk and egg products have higher bioavailablity than meat protein!).\n\nRegistered Nutritionist, <a href="http://healthnewsdigest.com/site/lay.html" target="_blank">June Lay</a>, recommends Voskos Greek Yogurt over other Greek and regular yogurt products. “When it comes to probiotics, both quality and quantity are very important. Voskos contains billions of live and active bacteria based on a 100-gram serving, which provide the adequate amount of probiotics.  You get five active strains essential for a truly healthy digestive system.”  Ms. Lay, also the author of It’s Not a Diet, It’s Creative Eating, adds, “By eating Greek yogurt, we’re giving our bodies the ammunition it needs to fight, or even prevent sicknesses—from the common cold to winter’s toughest flu.”\n\n<strong>REGISTERED NUTRITIONIST JUNE LAY OFFERS THE FOLLOW TIPS TO STAY HEALTHY THIS WINTER:</strong>\n1. <strong>Get a flu shot</strong> – local pharmacies may offer flu shots on walk-in basis (At CVS, they’re free!)\n2. <strong>Wash your hands or use hand sanitizer</strong> - antiseptic alcohol destroys 99% of germs.\n3. <strong>Try to sleep 8 hours a night and drink at least eight 8oz of fluids</strong> (that means water!) per day.\n4. <strong>Take an over-the-counter Vitamin D supplement </strong>(800IU daily), which will also help with bone health.\n5. <strong>Keep watch on your sugar consumption</strong>, as sugar depresses the immune system.\n6. <strong>Get the Pros on your side</strong>.  Defend yourself with Probiotics!\n\nSo, the next time you''re ready for a meal or snack, consider how your choice will affect your body. Choose to start each day with Voskos Greek Yogurt – a true boost for your immune system.	\n\n# # #\n\n<strong>Media Contact:</strong>Vanessa Nielsen\nvoskos.com\nvanessa@voskos.com\n818.504.1775\n	\n', 'VOSKOS KICKS THE COMMON COLD TO THE CURB', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-greek-yogurt-kicks-common-cold', '', '', '2010-11-09 20:19:56', '2010-11-10 03:19:56', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=445', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(449, 3, '2010-11-10 05:00:41', '2010-11-10 12:00:41', '<strong>VOSKOS GREEK YOGURT FOR THE NOT-SO-DESPERATE HOUSEWIVES</strong>\n<em>The Housewives’ Strong-Bone Solution To Calcium Deprivation</em>\n\n<strong>Sun Valley, CA—November 10, 2010—</strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt offers real health solutions for real housewives. Let’s face it, we all love watching the Real Housewives reality TV show – they’re beautiful, wealthy, eccentric and strong!  The reality is, what makes women even stronger is having strong bones. Our food, vitamins, and nutritional supplement choices are connected to the function, appearance, and health of our bodies. How we feed ourselves is important, as it affects our well-being, how we look, and our health. Women are more prone to developing weak bones as they age and need to take in the proper amount of calcium to prevent osteoporosis and bone fractures.\n\nAccording to a women’s health article, “the body absorbs nutrients easier from food than supplements.” The article’s featured study from the Washington University School of Medicine suggests dietary calcium better protects bone health. “The study found that women who get most of their daily calcium from food have healthier bones and higher bone density than women whose calcium comes mainly from supplemental tablets.” The study also confirms that estrogen, a hormone needed to maintain bone mineral density, is higher in calcium-consuming individuals.\n\nFurthermore, new research reveals that calcium supplements without vitamin D may actually increase the risk of heart attack. “If vitamin D is not present to help the body absorb the calcium then calcium deposits can occur.” Calcium deposits can harden blood vessels and make blood more susceptible to clotting, which could eventually lead to heart attack. However, researchers found that “foods containing calcium did not increase the risk of heart attack, since food doesn’t provide the calcium in short bursts.” The article discloses the recommended daily calcium intake for women: ages 19-50 need 1000mg per day and women 50+ need 1200mg of calcium, which equates to 3-4 servings of calcium-rich foods daily.\n \nSo, how do we consume the necessary amount of calcium per day using food and not supplements? \nVoskos Greek Yogurt provides one-third of a woman’s daily requirement of calcium in one 8 ounce container.  This superfood is also all-natural, gluten-free, hormone-free, lower in lactose, and has twice the protein as other yogurts.  \n\n“Voskos Greek Yogurt makes it really easy and tasty to ensure proper intake of calcium without risk,” says <a href="http://www.bite-sizenutrition.com/index.php" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Melissa Hooper</a>, registered dietitian and healthy lifestyles consultant. “Voskos can be used to make a smoothie in the morning for breakfast; an 8 ounce container can be enjoyed as a snack; and it can be used as a substitute for many higher fat foods such as sour creams and mayonnaise,” adds Hooper.  Moreover, those who have lactose intolerance digest Voskos more easily than other dairy and calcium-rich foods due to the Voskos ProStrain™ process, a proprietary method that balances whey and casein.\n\n<strong>Hooper gives some suggestions for women of all ages to increase calcium intake through Voskos Greek Yogurt:</strong>\n1. Enjoy any of the flavorful varieties of Voskos Greek Yogurt individual cups \n2. Blend in smoothies for breakfast and/or snacks\n3. Base ingredient a dips, excellent with veggies and/or low-fat chips\n4. Use in cooking sauces and creams \n\nWith Voskos Greek Yogurt, women can enjoy strong bones and healthy hearts with lower risk and significantly reduced “desperation.” Voskos Greek Yogurt is the not-so-desperate health solution for real housewives!\n\n# # #\n\n<strong>Media Contact:</strong>\nVanessa Nielsen\nvoskos.com\nvanessa@voskos.com\n818.504.1775\n', 'VOSKOS FOR THE NOT-SO-DESPERATE HOUSEWIVES', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-greek-yogurt-women', '', '', '2010-11-10 05:00:41', '2010-11-10 12:00:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=449', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(451, 3, '2010-08-17 22:07:54', '2010-08-18 05:07:54', 'Serves 1\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n3 eggs\n3 tablespoons Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 tablespoon finely chopped parsley\n1 tablespoon finely chopped chives\n½ teaspoon finely chopped fresh basil, or ¼ teaspoon crushed dried basil\n¼ teaspoon finely chopped fresh rosemary, or 1/8 teaspoon crushed dried rosemary\nSalt to taste\nFreshly ground black pepper to taste\n1 tablespoon butter\n1 sprig parsley\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a mixing bowl beat the eggs with a fork or whisk.\n2. Add the yogurt, parsley, chives, basil, rosemary, and salt and pepper and mix well.\n3. In a small skillet melt the butter over high heat and swirl it around in the pan.\n4. Pour in the egg mixture and reduce the heat to moderate.\n5. Run a thin spatula under the egg mixture as soon as it begins to set and lift to allow the uncooked portion to flow underneath.\n6. When the mixture is set, fold it over.\n7. Transfer to heated plate and serve at once, garnished with the parsley sprig.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Herb Omelet', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'herb-omelet', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=451', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(454, 3, '2010-08-17 22:11:32', '2010-08-18 05:11:32', 'Serves 4\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n6 slices French bread, crusts removed\n4 tablespoons butter, melted\n4 ounces small cooked shrimp\n1 cup grated Gruyère cheese\n2 tablespoons finely chopped chives\n2 tablespoons finely chopped parsley\n3 eggs\n1 cup milk\n½ cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n½ teaspoon Dijon-style mustard\n½ teaspoon salt or to taste\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Cut each slice of bread in half diagonally.\n2. Brush on both sides with the butter.\n3. Arrange half of the bread in an 8-inch-square baking dish.\n4. Scatter half the shrimp over the bread.\n5. Sprinkle with half each of the cheese, chives, and parsley.\n6. Cover, making layers, with the remaining bread, shrimp, cheese, chives, and parsley.\n7. Beat the eggs until frothy.\n8. Add the milk, yogurt, mustard, and salt and blend thoroughly.\n9. Pour the egg mixture over the layers.\n10. Cover and chill several hours or overnight.\n11. Bake in a preheated 350°F oven about 35 minutes or until lightly browned and puffy.\n12. Serve immediately.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Shrimp and Cheese Casserole', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'shrimp-and-cheese-casserole', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=454', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(457, 3, '2010-08-18 22:15:08', '2010-08-19 05:15:08', 'Serves 4\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 3-poound chicken, quartered\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n2 large garlic cloves, crushed\n1 ½-inch piece ginger root, peeled and grated\n1 ½ teaspoon ground coriander\n¾ teaspoon ground cumin\n¼ teaspoon ground cardamom or aniseed\n1/8 teaspoon ground cayenne pepper\n¼ cup freshly squeezed and strained lemon juice\n1 ½ teaspoon salt\nVery thin onion rings\nThin slices tomato\nLime or lemon wedges \n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Dry the chickens with paper towels.\n2. In a large bowl combine the yogurt, garlic, ginger, coriander, cumin, cardamom, cayenne, lime juice, and salt and mix well.\n3. Add the chicken pieces and turn to coat them thoroughly with the mixture.\n4. Cover and marinate in the refrigerator at least 12 hours, turning the chicken pieces from time to time.\n5. Remove the chicken pieces from the marinade and arrange on a greased rack in a shallow baking pan.\n6. Roast in a preheated 400°F oven 50 to 60 minutes or until golden brown all over but still tender inside, basting occasionally with the butter.\n7. Or broil the chickens over charcoal about 30 minutes or until tender, turning and basting frequently.\n8. Transfer onto a heated serving platter and garnish with the onion rings, tomato slices, and lime wedges.\n9. Serve immediately.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Chicken Tandoori', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chicken-tandoori', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=457', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(459, 3, '2010-08-18 22:18:24', '2010-08-19 05:18:24', 'Serves 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 4-ounce can peeled green chili peppers\n4 tablespoon corn oil\n1 medium onion, finely chopped\n1 small garlic clove, finely chopped\n3 medium tomatoes, peeled, seeded, and finely chopped\n¼ teaspoon crushed dried oregano\nSalt to taste\n1 ½ cups shredded cooked chicken \n4 ounces mild Cheddar cheese, grated\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n12 corn tortillas\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Drain and rinse the green chili peppers.\n2. Remove the seeds.\n3. Chop the peppers finely.\n4. Take care not to touch your face while handling the peppers, and wash your hands well when finished.\n5. In a heavy skillet heat 1 tablespoon of the oil over moderate heat.\n6. Add the onion and garlic and sauté until golden, stirring frequently.\n7. Add the chili peppers, tomatoes, oregano, and salt.\n8. Simmer over low heat about 30 minutes or until the mixture thickens.\n9. Remove from the heat and set aside.\n10. Combine the chicken, cheese, yogurt, and additional salt.\n11. Heat the remaining 3 tablespoons oil and drip in the tortillas, one at a time, just until they become limp (they must not be crisp).\n12. Drain on paper towels.\n13. Fill each tortilla with a little of the chicken mixture and roll it up.\n14. Arrange the rolls seam sides down and close together in a greased shallow baking dish.\n15. Pour the sauce over them\n16. Bake in a preheated 350°F oven about 20 minutes or until thoroughly heated.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Chicken Enchiladas', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chicken-enchiladas', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=459', 0, 'post', '', 0);
