(461, 3, '2010-08-18 22:20:48', '2010-08-19 05:20:48', 'Serves 4\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1/3 cup olive oil\n1 medium onion, finely grated\n1 teaspoon crushed dried thyme\n1 teaspoon salt\n¼ teaspoon freshly ground black pepper\n2 pounds boneless leg of lamb, trimmed of excess fat and cut into 1- to 1 ½-inch cubes\n8 pita bread halves\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt, at room temperature\nSalt to taste\nFreshly ground black pepper to taste\n2 tablespoons butter\n2 teaspoons paprika\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Combine the oil, onion, thyme, 1 teaspoon salt, and ¼ teaspoon pepper in a large bowl and mix well.\n2. Add the lamb cubes and turn them about to coat thoroughly with the mixture.\n3. Cover and let stand at room temperature 2 to 3 hours or in the refrigerator 5 to 6 hours, turning the meat from time to time.\n4. Remove the lamb cubes from the marinade and thread them on long skewers, leaving a few inches exposed at each end.\n5. Broil, preferably over charcoal, about 15 minutes or until the lamb is richly browned outside and pink and juicy inside, turning and basting now and then with the marinade.\n6. Arrange the pieces of bread on 4 heated dinner plates.\n7. Using a fork, push the lamb off the skewers onto the bread.\n8. Beat the yogurt until smooth.\n9. Season to taste with salt and pepper and spoon over the lamb.\n10. Heat the butter and stir in the paprika.\n11. Drizzle the paprika butter over the yogurt and serve.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Turkish Kebabs with Yogurt', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'turkish-kebabs-with-yogurt', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=461', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(463, 3, '2010-08-19 22:24:40', '2010-08-20 05:24:40', 'Serves 4 to 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 ½ pounds tenderloin or top sirloin of beef, trimmed of fat\nSalt to taste\nFreshly ground black pepper to taste\n¼ cup all-purpose flour\n6 tablespoons butter\n4 ounces mushrooms, thinly sliced\n½ cup finely chopped onion or scallions (include 2 inches of the green tops of the scallions)\n1 medium garlic clove, finely chopped\n1 tablespoon tomato paste\n1 cup beef broth\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt, at room temperature\n2 tablespoons finely chopped parsley or fresh dill\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Cut the meat into thin strips about 2 inches long and ¼ inch wide.\n2. Season with the salt and pepper and dredge in 3 tablespoons of the flour.\n3. In a heavy skillet melt 4 tablespoons of the butter over moderate heat.\n4. Add the meat strips and sauté, turning them to brown on all sides.\n5. Remove to a plate and keep warm.\n6. Add the remaining 2 tablespoons butter to the skillet and heat.\n7. Add the mushrooms, onion, scallions, and garlic and sauté until lightly browned, stirring frequently.\n8. Sprinkle the remaining 1 tablespoon flour over the vegetables and mix well.\n9. Stir in the tomato paste and broth and simmer a few minutes.\n10. Remove from the heat and stir in the yogurt until well blended.\n11. Return the meat to the skillet.\n12. Cover and simmer over low heat 2 or 3 minutes until heated through.\n13. Taste and adjust the seasoning.\n14. Sprinkle with the parsley or dill and serve.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Beef Stroganov', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'beef-stroganov', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=463', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(469, 3, '2010-08-19 22:33:37', '2010-08-20 05:33:37', 'Makes 24\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n½ cup currants or raisins\n2 ½ to 2 ¾ unsifted all-purpose flour\n½ teaspoon salt\n½ cup sugar\n2 teaspoons double acting baking powder\n1 teaspoon baking soda\n6 tablespoons butter\n1 egg, beaten\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a>\nRind of ½ lemon, grated\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Dredge the currants in 2 tablespoons of the flour and set aside.\n2. Sift the remaining flour with the salt, sugar, baking powder, and baking soda.\n3. Cut in the butter until the mixture resembles coarse meal.\n4. Add the beaten egg to the flour mixture along with the yogurt, currants, and lemon rind.\n5. Mix well. Divide the dough into 24 balls.\n6. Flatten to ½ inch thick round cakes.\n7. Arrange on a lightly greased cookie sheet.\n8. Bake in a preheated 425°F oven about 12 minutes or until lightly browned.\n9. Cool on wire racks or serve warm with butter and jam.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Greek Yogurt Scones', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-scones', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=469', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(471, 3, '2010-08-20 22:37:38', '2010-08-21 05:37:38', 'Serves 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\nExtra virgin olive oil\n2 white onions, peeled and minced\n2 lbs. potatoes, peeled and diced\n2 bay leaves\n1 stalk celery, halved\n1 carrot, peeled and halved\n½ cup dry white wine\n2 quarts beef stock\nSalt\nFreshly ground white pepper\n1 black truffle, diced\n¼ cup Voskos Greek Yogurt, drained\n10 oz. bread dough\n1 egg yolk\n6 tbsp. grated cheese, such as Fontina\n3 tbsp. butter, sliced\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Heat a drizzle of oil in a medium-large saucepot and cook the onion over low heat until golden.\n2. Add the potatoes, bay leaves, celery, and carrot.\n3. Sauté, carefully add the white wine, and bring to a boil.\n4. When the wine is completely evaporated, add the beef broth and bring to a boil.\n5. Cook over moderate heat until the potatoes are nearly cooked.\n6. Remove the bay leaves, carrot, and celery and season with salt and white pepper.\n7. Place the truffle in the Voskos Greek Yogurt to marinate. Set aside.\n8. Pour the soup into small, deep oven-safe bowls, distributing the truffle Voskos Greek Yogurt evenly among them.\n9. Divide the bread dough into size balls of equal size, roll them out with a rolling pin, and cover each bowl of soup completely with dough.\n10. Brush the dough with the egg yolk, sprinkle with the grated cheese, and place a piece of butter in the middle. Bake at 475ºF until the crust is golden; serve.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Potato Soup', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'potato-soup', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=471', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(473, 3, '2010-11-16 05:00:09', '2010-11-16 12:00:09', 'It was SO difficult for us to pick just five winners out of all your beautiful, inspiring entries. But we had to, so we did. \n\nThe following entries have been chosen to receive a HUGE <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/news/voskos-contest">Voskos prize package</a>:\n\n<strong>Jake Bray</strong>: "I am thankful that my mom never allowed me to feel sorry for myself and my handicap. I am an awesome power soccer player, have a beautiful girlfriend, and Muscular Dystrophy. Below is a picture of my girlfriend and I."\n\n<strong>Melinda Utendorf</strong>: "I am thankful to be cancer free after a long battle with breast cancer and going through chemo and 15 surgeries in the last 2 years. I’m also thankful that my husband is employed again after 10 months of unemployment!"\n\n<strong>Kathy Beckett</strong>: "I am grateful for my daughter with Down syndrome. She is the light of our lives."\n\n<strong>Linda Henderson</strong>: "I am thankful every day for my youngest granddaughter. When my daughter was 23 weeks pregnant she was laying in a hospital bed trying to hold onto the baby it had taken her seven years to conceive. We were given no hope of her survival. They were already discussing funeral homes and arrangements. We were told that unless she tried to draw a breath, they wouldn’t try to save her because she wasn’t considered viable at that stage. Well, she fooled all of them. She came out at 1 pound 3 ounces and was 11 1/2 inches long and she fought to breathe so they got her on the machines and off to the NICU she went. We had her baptised that night because they weren’t all that hopeful, but we figure God’s got plans for her because after 4 months in the NICU she came home a couple of days before her due date. She’s still a tiny little thing, but she’s a walking,talking miracle. She’s what I’m most thankful for."\n\n<strong>Melissa Anderson</strong>: "I am grateful that I have taught my children to be compassionate to others. My 7-year-old boy is giving up Christmas presents this year, in hopes of <a href="http://www.mycharitywater.org/scorpions" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">raising $5,000</a> for communities and villages that need clean drinking water."  \n\nThank you so much. Many of your entries have brought tears to our eyes. And if you didn''t win this contest, stay around for the next! ', 'We Have Five Winners!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'we-have-five-winners', '', '', '2010-11-16 05:00:09', '2010-11-16 12:00:09', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=473', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(475, 3, '2010-08-21 22:47:55', '2010-08-22 05:47:55', 'Makes about 2 dozen\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 lbs. equal parts ground beef, veal, and pork\n1 onion, chopped\n2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce\n1 tablespoon parsley, chopped\n2 teaspoon paprika\n1 teaspoon salt\n¼ teaspoon pepper\n½ teaspoon lemon rind, grated\nDash of nutmeg\n2 eggs, slightly beaten\n½ cup dried mustard\n2 tablespoons parsley, chopped\n\nSauce:\n1 can (10 ½ oz.) onion soup\n1 tablespoon cornstarch\n1 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\n2 tablespoons chopped pickles\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Combine the ground meat, onion, Worcestershire sauce, parsley, paprika, salt, pepper, lemon rind, and nutmeg; stir in the eggs.\n2. Shape into meatballs about 1 inch diameter.\n3. Roll in the mustard, then broil until browned.\n4. Heat together the onion soup and cornstarch, then stir in the yogurt and chopped pickles.\n5. When ready to serve, top with yogurt sauce and sprinkle with chopped parsley.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'German Party Meatballs', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'german-party-meatballs', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=475', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(477, 3, '2010-08-11 22:51:08', '2010-08-12 05:51:08', 'Makes 1 quart\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 cans (20 oz. each) garbanzo beans/chickpeas, drained\n1 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\n2 tablespoons oil, preferably peanut\n½ cup toasted sesame seeds\n½ cup alfalfa sprouts\n1 clove garlic, minced\n1 teaspoon cumin\n½ teaspoon salt\n¼ teaspoon cayenne pepper\nVegetable dippers or toasted pita bread\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Drain and puree the garbanzo beans/chickpeas in a food processor.\n2. Blend in the yogurt, peanut oil, sesame seeds, alfalfa sprouts, garlic, cumin, salt and cayenne pepper.\n3. Chill until ready to serve, then use as a dip for fresh vegetables or toasted pita bread.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Hummus', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'hummus', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '2013-08-05 21:01:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=477', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(479, 3, '2010-12-01 05:00:23', '2010-12-01 12:00:23', 'It''s the season for giving back and getting involved in our community. We''ve already asked you "<a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/news/voskos-contest" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">What are you grateful for</a>?" - and were deeply moved as we were reading your amazing, inspiring responses. \n\nToday we''d like to talk about giving back. We''ve all been through a prolonged recession. We''ve all been struggling. Many of your contest entries mentioned being unemployed or some other type of financial hardship. And it''s not the end yet! So, how do you give back when you have so little to give?\n\nI''ll share a story with you. My late grandmother was not a wealthy woman. On the contrary: she struggled  financially her entire life. But every time I went to visit her, as a child, poor people would knock on her door asking for help, and she always had something to give them. It could have been a few coins, a glass of water, a piece of bread. Nothing major. But whatever it was, they never left her house empty handed. And she gave them something just as important: her attention, a listening ear, and a warm smile.  \n\nI remember asking her about it one day. How come you always give, I wondered, when you should really keep more for yourself? Her reply: "But I have so much. I have a roof over my head, and food to eat, and a family that loves me. Of course I can give."\n\nI will never forget that answer. \n\nHere at Voskos, we''re trying to give back too. Yes, we are a for-profit corporation, but we never forget that even corporations have a soul - and that they need to keep in touch with their communities and give back. That''s why we have <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/videos/empower-yourself-with-voskos">partnered</a> with amazing events and causes, including Solvang Century, Revlon Run/Walk for Women, Keep LA Running, and more. \n\n''Tis the season to be merry - and the season to give back. \n\n\n\n', 'Thoughts on Giving Back', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'thoughts-on-giving-back', '', '', '2010-12-01 05:00:23', '2010-12-01 12:00:23', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=479', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(480, 3, '2010-08-22 22:55:32', '2010-08-23 05:55:32', 'Serves 2 to 3\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 can (7 ½ oz.) white albacore tuna, drained\n2 cups bean sprouts\n1 can (7 ½ oz.) water chestnuts, slices and drained\n½ cup white radishes, thinly sliced\n½ cup cucumber, peeled, seeded, and chopped\n1 green pepper, cut in slivers\n½ cup green onions, sliced\nLettuce greens\n\nDressing\n2 tablespoons soy sauce\n1 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\n½ teaspoon celery salt\n\nGarnishes\nTomatoes\nHard-cooked eggs\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Combine the white tuna, bean sprouts, water chestnuts, radishes, cucumber, green pepper, and green onions; put over lettuce greens.\n2. Top with a dressing made from a mixture of the soy sauce, yogurt, and celery salt.\n3. Garnish with sliced tomatoes and hard-cooked eggs.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Chinese Tuna Salad', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chinese-tuna-salad', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '2013-08-05 21:01:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=480', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(482, 3, '2010-08-23 23:01:08', '2010-08-24 06:01:08', 'Makes 8 to 10 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n5 eggs, separated\n1/3 cup sugar\nDash of salt\nJuice and rind of 1 lemon\n½ cup flour\nConfectioner’s sugar\n\nFilling\n1 can (11 oz.) condensed cheddar cheese soup\n1 cup of Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\n½ cup sugar\n1/3 cup cornstarch\n3 tablespoons dark rum\n½ teaspoon vanilla extract\n3 egg yolks, slightly beaten\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 400°F.\n2. Beat the 5 egg yolks together with the sugar, salt, and lemon juice and rind until thick and lemon-colored.\n3. Stir in the flour.\n4. In a separate bowl, beat the 5 egg whites until stiff, then gently fold into the batter.\n5. Pour into 2 greased and floured 8-inch square cake pans and bake for 15 minutes.\n6. Remove and cool.\n7. Make the filling: in a saucepan blend the soup, yogurt, sugar, cornstarch, rum, and vanilla; cook over low heat until thickened.\n8. Pour some of the yogurt mixture into the 3 egg yolks, mix until smooth, and then return to the heat and cook until thickened.\n9. Remove, cover with waxed paper, and cool to room temperature.\n10. When ready to assemble, cut each of the cake layers in half horizontally and spread the filling between the layers.\n11. Stack and top with confectioner’s sugar.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Holiday Rum Cake', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'holiday-rum-cake', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=482', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(484, 3, '2010-12-09 05:00:50', '2010-12-09 12:00:50', 'Saving money is on everyone''s mind these days. In fact, A <a href="http://www.cnbc.com/id/39312510/A_Very_Different_Christmas_Holiday_Forecast_A_Dismal_Outlook" target="_blank">record high</a> 43 percent of American shoppers plan to spend less during the last quarter of this year than they did in 2009. \n\nStill, for many of us, the holiday season is not just a source of <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/beauty-health-fitness/stress-free-holiday-season">stress</a>, but also a source of spending. Here are a few useful tips for keeping holiday spending in check:\n\n<h3>1. Whenever possible, use coupons</h3>\n\nWhether you cut them out of your Sunday paper or find and print them online, shopping for an item that has a coupon without using that coupon is like throwing money away! For Voskos coupons, simply head over to our <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" rel="nofollow">Facebook page</a> or to the Coupons tab on our <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">website</a>. \n\n<h3>2. Declare a “No Christmas Gifts” Holiday</h3>\n\nYou may feel that the young children on your list should still receive gifts, but for everyone else, especially the adults in your family, consider declaring this year a year of spending quality time together, sharing meals and laughs, without stressing over finding - and paying for - the "perfect" gift. \n\n<h3>3. If you do shop for gifts, create a budget</h3>\n\nJust like with any other type of spending, creating a gift budget ahead of time and sticking with it can mean the difference between a worry-free holiday season, and serious overspending that can get you into nasty credit card debt. \n\n<h3>4. Keep entertainment costs down</h3>\n\nRent videos in lieu of going to the movies; save on restaurants with discounted restaurants.com gift certificates; instead of an expensive dinner, host a cookie baking event or a potluck dinner where everyone shares the load.\n\n<h3>5. Holiday decorations: stick with the basics!</h3>\n\nUnless you''re a newlywed couple, you surely have your box of decorations from last year. Use it and don''t feel compelled to buy new, shiny decorations. There''s a lot of beauty in using the same decorations year after year. They become the treasured, heirloom family decorations that you probably remember from your own childhood. \n\nThe most important thing to remember this holiday season is that the holidays are about so much more than exchanging gifts. They are, above all, about spending quality time together with beloved family members and friends, sharing food, hugs and laughs.\n\nHappy Holidays!', 'Save Money This Holiday Season', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'saving-money-holiday-season', '', '', '2010-12-09 05:00:50', '2010-12-09 12:00:50', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=484', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(486, 3, '2010-08-23 23:17:18', '2010-08-24 06:17:18', 'Serves 6 \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 ½ cups Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 ½ tablespoons olive oil\n¼ cup freshly squeezed and strained lemon juice or to taste\n1 ½ teaspoons curry powder or to taste\nPinch crushed dried thyme\n4 ½ cups tomato juice\nSalt to taste\nFinely chopped chives or scallion tops\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Spoon the yogurt into a large mixing bowl and beat until smooth.\n2. Add the olive oil, lemon juice, curry powder, and thyme and mix well.\n3. Gradually stir in the tomato juice until thoroughly blended.\n4. Season with the salt.\n5. Cover and chill.\n6. Serve in individual soup bowls or cups sprinkled with the chives or scallion tops.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Chilled Tomato Soup', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chilled-tomato-soup', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=486', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(488, 3, '2010-08-23 23:19:24', '2010-08-24 06:19:24', 'Makes 6 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 tablespoons unsalted butter\n1/3 cup finely chopped onion\n2 pounds pumpkin, peeled and cubed\n1 quart low-sodium chicken broth\n1 small bay leaf\n½ teaspoon dried thyme\n1 cup half-and-half\n1 cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 teaspoon kosher salt\n1/2 teaspoon ground white pepper \n1/3 cup dry sherry\nNon-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt for garnish\n¼ cup finely chopped chives for garnish\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a heavy saucepan melt the butter over medium heat. Add the onion and sauté until golden, stirring frequently.\n3. Add the pumpkin, chicken broth, bay leaf, and thyme. Reduce the heat to low, cover, and simmer about 20 minutes or until the pumpkin is very tender.\n5. Remove the bay leaf. Purée the soup in an electric blender. Stir in the half-and-half and Voskos Greek yogurt and simmer over low heat for 5 minutes, then season with the salt and pepper and stir in the sherry.\n11. Ladle the soup into individual bowls. Serve immediately, topping each serving with a dollop of yogurt and a sprinkling of chives.\n\n<strong>Nutrition per serving</strong>\nCalories 161.9\nTotal Fat 8.5 g\nSaturated Fat 5.3 g\nCholesterol 27.8 mg\nSodium 767.6 mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 10.0 g\nDietary Fiber 1.0 g\nSugars 3.0 g\nProtein 7.9 g', 'Cream of Pumpkin Soup', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'cream-of-pumpkin-soup', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=488', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(490, 3, '2010-08-24 23:23:38', '2010-08-25 06:23:38', 'Serves 4 to 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 lbs. ground beef and pork\n2 eggs, slightly beaten\n1 onion, chopped\n1 cup bread crumbs\n4 tablespoons tomato paste\n½ teaspoon salt\n¼ teaspoon thyme\nDash of nutmeg\n½ cup beef bouillon\n1 cup of Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\nDill, to garnish.\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Slightly beat the eggs, then mix with the ground beef and prok, onion, breadcrumbs, tomato paste, salt, thyme, and nutmeg.\n2. Form into tiny meatballs about 1 inch in diameter.\n3. Cover with the bouillon and wither bake at 350°F about 20 minutes, or put in a slow-cooking pot for several hours or follow the manufacturer’s instructions.\n4. When ready to serve, stir in the yogurt and sprinkle lightly with dill.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Swedish Meatballs', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'swedish-meatballs-2', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=490', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(492, 3, '2010-08-24 23:27:30', '2010-08-25 06:27:30', 'Makes about 2 dozen\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup graham flour (or whole wheat)\n½ cup white flour\n2 to 4 tablespoon sugar\n1 teaspoon double-acting baking powder\n1 teaspoon baking soda\n½ teaspoon salt\n¼ teaspoon ground cinnamon\n1 egg, beaten slightly\n1 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\n1 cup milk\n2 tablespoons oil\nButter\nMaple syrup\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Sift the fry ingredients: flour, sugar, baking powder, baking soda, salt, and cinnamon.\n2. Separately beat the egg into the yogurt, milk, and oil.\n3. Combine the mixtures until just moistened, then cook about ¼ cup at a time on a preheated griddle (cast iron is best).\n4. Flip when puffed and browned on both sides, and serve with pats of butter and pure maple syrup.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>\n', 'Graham Griddlecakes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'graham-griddlecakes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=492', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(496, 5, '2010-12-07 05:00:23', '2010-12-07 12:00:23', 'Trade-off is one "Tool" of my program that merits my repeating often, especially during the holiday season when we''re more likely to overeat. Regardless of what we eat, calories count first, so let''s "trade-off"!  As we continue to eat and drink our way through this holiday season (and let''s not forget beyond, too!), let''s focus on the different kinds of trade -offs we can make to avoid weight gain, and there are many. Because there is no perfect way to eat, and we''ll always encounter days with holidays, birthdays, business dinners .... well you get my point, trading off can become an important weight management tool.\n \nThe philosophy I do like to share with my clients which I apply to myself is this, if we can find a way of eating 80% of the time that allows us to maintain our weight, enjoy eating, not feel deprived, and it doesn''t feel like a diet, then we have a win-win situation! \n \nI remember the day that I bumped into a client  as I was entering a Mexican restaurant, and her comment was "You eat this type of food"? Well, yes I drink Margaritas, eat chips, guacamole and desserts to name a few,  but just not as much as I want, or as often as I want. If I choose for instance, to start my meal escapade with a frozen drink with chips and trimmings, I trade-off either with a "Go Lean" entree (another tool), or an appetizer dish as my entree or I eat less calories at my next meal. I will also have a light eating day the next day if I feel that I need to. If I have a couple of parties in one week during holiday season, I eliminate my salad dressings at lunch during that week. I''m always thinking trade-offs! \n \nOf course, I also start my day with a healthy breakfast, my favorite Voskos Greek Yogurt with fresh blueberries and chopped walnuts, which helps me to tame my holiday and year- round appetite. Research does support starting our day with breakfast. In fact one recent study confirmed just this! It''s conclusion  "Breakfast skipping may lead to and increase of appetite, possibly leading to weight gain over time and increases of risk factors for diabetes and cardiovascular disease". In other words, when we don''t start our day with breakfast even a light one, we set ourselves up for cravings later, more hunger, weight gain and chronic diseases we work so hard to prevent.\n \nSo when we do overindulge, it''s important to not beat ourselves up, but rather let''s think of the next possible trade-off. Can we think of some of our own trade-offs?\n \nHere''s to starting our day with Voskos!\n \n<a href="http://www.junefit.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">June M. Lay M.S.</a>\n\nSource: Giovannini M, Symposium overview: Do we all eat breakfast and is it important? Crit Rev Food Sci Nutr. 2010 Feb;50(2):97-9. Retrieved from Pubmed.\n\n', 'Holiday Trade-Off!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'holiday-trade-off', '', '', '2010-12-07 05:00:23', '2010-12-07 12:00:23', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=496', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(500, 3, '2010-08-25 23:38:31', '2010-08-26 06:38:31', 'Makes 1 pound\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 tablespoons butter\n1 pound chicken liver, cut into ½-inch pieces\n2 tablespoons chopped shallots or scallions (use only the white parts of the scallions)\n3 tablespoons Cognac or Madeira\n½ cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek yogurt\n1/8 teaspoon ground allspice\n1/8 teaspoon crushed dried thyme\n½ teaspoon salt\n1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper\n4 tablespoons butter, melted\nParsley sprigs\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a heavy skillet melt the 2 tablespoons butter over moderate heat.\n2. Add the chicken livers and sauté about 3 minutes or until lightly browned outside but still pink inside.\n3. Remove from the heat and pour the contents of the skillet into the container of an electric blender.\n4. Add the shallots or scallions, Cognac or Madeira, yogurt, allspice, thyme, salt, and pepper.\n5. Blend at medium speed until a smooth paste is formed.\n6. Add the melted butter and blend a few seconds more.\n7. Taste and adjust the seasoning.\n8. Pack the liver mousse into an attractive serving bowl. \n9. Cover with aluminum foil and chill thoroughly.\n10. Garnish with the parsley and serve, accompanied with crackers.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Chicken Liver Mousse', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chicken-liver-mousse', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=500', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(502, 3, '2010-08-26 23:42:33', '2010-08-27 06:42:33', 'Serves 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n6 medium-size sole fillets, skinned and boned\nFresh juice of 2 lemons, strained and divided in half\n1 bunch fresh herbs (thyme, marjoram, mint, chives), minced\n¼ cup Voskos Greek Yogurt, drained\nSalt\nExtra virgin olive oil\n½ cup semolina flour\nFor optional garnish: Herb bouquets\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Place the sole in a bowl with half of the lemon juice, a pinch of the minced herbs, Voskos Greek Yogurt, salt, and a drizzle of oil.\n2. Cover with plastic wrap and place in the refrigerator for approximately 3 hours.\n3. Retrieve the sole fillets from the marinade and arrange them on parchment paper.\n4. Sprinkle each individual fillet with additional minced herbs and salt and roll, piercing with toothpicks or short skewers to secure.\n5. Heat a pan with some olive oil, sprinkle the sole skewers with semolina flour, and fry. \n6. When cooked, sprinkle with the remaining lemon juice.\n7. Serve on dinner plates with herb bouquets.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Sole Skewers', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'sole-skewers', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=502', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(503, 6, '2010-11-23 05:00:26', '2010-11-23 12:00:26', 'Thanksgiving dinner is one of highest calorie meals of the year.  Traditional recipes are loaded with love, but most often do not skimp on calories and fat.  Lara Field, pediatric dietitian, breaks down a  typical Thanksgiving dinner to reveal the actual calories consumed:\n\n6 oz turkey (breast – meat and skin)\n1 cup mashed potatoes\n1 cup stuffing\n4 oz gravy (made from drippings)\n½ cup cranberry sauce\n½ cup green bean casserole\n1 dinner roll\n1 TBSP butter\n2 glasses (8 ounces) red wine\n1 slice pumpkin pie\n\nThis provides a grand total of approximately 2000 calories, 76 g fat, 195 g carbohydrates, and 70 g protein, in just one meal!  That is more than recommended for most women, and active kids for an entire day.\n\nTake charge of your portions this Thanksgiving, and make a note to reduce calories consumed.  Or even better, this season, incorporate Voskos Greek Yogurt into your recipes for a dose of protein, calcium, and probiotics. Using Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a> instead of buttermilk, sour cream, or even cream soup will reduce your total calories significantly. Try the recipes below for delicious alternatives to your holiday fare.\n<h3>Yogurt Pumpkin Pie</h3>\n3 eggs, beaten\n2 cups 100% pure pumpkin puree\n1 ½ cups plain, non-fat Voskos Greek Yogurt\n¾ cup pure maple syrup\n2 TBSP dark rum\n1 tsp pumpkin pie spice\n½ tsp pure vanilla extract\npinch of salt\n1 pie crust\n\nDirections:\nIn a medium mixing bowl, add wet ingredients and mix until fully combined. Pour filling into a 8 inch pie crust.  Bake at 425 degrees for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees and bake until custard sets (approximately 1 hour).  Cool and enjoy!\n<h3>Cornbread</h3>\n1 cup whole wheat flour\n1 cup cornmeal\n1 tablespoon Sun Crystals\n1 teaspoon baking soda\n1 teaspoon of salt\n1 cup plain, non-fat Voskos Greek yogurt\n2 egg whites\n1 whole egg\n1 cup canned corn\n\nDirections:\nPreheat oven to 400 degrees F. Coat 13" x 9" baking pan with a nonfat cooking spray.\n\nIn a large bowl, mix flour, cornmeal, sun crystals, baking soda and salt. Stir in plain, non-fat Voskos Greek yogurt and beaten eggs. Stir until blended. Add canned corn. Pour batter into greased pan and bake in preheated oven for 20 to 25 minutes.\n\nThis recipe uses plain, non-fat Voskos Greek yogurt, which is a delicious, low fat, high in protein and calcium, as a substitute for butter. Instead of sugar, Sun Crystals are used, which is a sugar substitute that has half the calories of regular sugar. This recipe saves 175 calories from the traditional recipe, which usually consists of a large amount of sugar and butter.\n<h3>Mocked Potatoes</h3>\n4 cups cauliflower\n1 cup plain, non-fat Voskos Greek yogurt\n2 TBSP light butter\nsalt and pepper to taste\n\nDirections\nCut and wash cauliflower, remove stem.  Place in medium pot with approximately 1 inch water.  Cover and cook for approximately 5-8 minutes until tender.  Pour cooked cauliflower and cooking liquid in blender or food processor.  Blend until smooth – texture should resemble mashed potatoes; add in yogurt, butter, and seasonings.  Serve immediately.\n\nRemember to enjoy this holiday season while watching your calorie intake.  Wishing you and yours a very Happy Thanksgiving!\n\nPhoto Credit: <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/preppybyday/4998120527/" target="_blank">The Culinary Geek</a>', 'Cut Calories in your Thanksgiving Recipes!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-thanksgiving-recipes', '', '', '2010-11-23 05:00:26', '2010-11-23 12:00:26', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=503', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(504, 3, '2010-08-28 23:46:38', '2010-08-29 06:46:38', 'Makes 1 ½ cups\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 whole canned anchovies (or 4 fillets), drained and chopped\n1 tablespoon anchovy paste\n1 onion, chopped\n1 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\n¼ cup mayonnaise\n¼ teaspoon Worcestershire sauce\nWheat crackers\nCapers\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Mix together the anchovies, anchovy paste, onion, yogurt, mayonnaise, and Worcestershire sauce.\n2. Spoon on individual thin wheat crackers and top each one with a caper.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Anchovy Appetizer', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'anchovy-appetizer', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=504', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(506, 3, '2010-08-29 23:49:49', '2010-08-30 06:49:49', 'Makes 2 cups\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n4 cups Voskos Greek Yogurt (plain)\n½ teaspoon salt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Sprinkle the salt onto the yogurt.\n2. Put several layers of cheesecloth in a colander, pour in the yogurt, and cover with a paper towel.\n3. Refrigerate and let drain for 24 hours.\n4. Put the yogurt cheese into a container and refrigerate until ready to serve.\n5. Covered and refrigerated, it will keep up to 4 weeks.\n6. “Lebanie” can be served plain or combined with jams or herbs and served with fruit or on Arabic bread.\n\n<a title="Upload A Photo of Your Recipe" href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/contact-us" target="_self"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-595" title="submityourrecipe" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/submityourrecipe.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="135" /></a>', 'Lebanese Yogurt Cheese', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'lebanese-yogurt-cheese', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=506', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(515, 3, '2010-12-30 05:00:52', '2010-12-30 12:00:52', 'New Year resolutions are tricky. We remember reading somewhere that the vast majority of these resolutions are eventually broken, and we suspect we know why: We tend to make them too vague, and too difficult!\n\nFor example, a resolution that says, "I will lose weight in 2011" is doomed to fail! It''s simply too vague. It would make more sense to set small, specific goals such as "In 2011 I will lose 2 pounds, on average, each month."\n\nAnother problematic New Year resolution: "In 2011 I will lose 60 pounds!" That''s, on average, 5 pounds per month which could prove to be difficult to do. It''s much better to decide on a very attainable goal such as 2-3 pounds per month, and be pleasantly surprised if you lose more. \n\nKeeping the above in mind, here are three New Year resolutions that will make a big difference in your health, and that you should be able to keep:\n\n<h3>1. Limit Soda to 1 Per Day</h3>\n\nWhether it''s sugary, calorie-laden soda or chemical-filled diet soda, both are very bad for you and should be limited. The good news: Soda consumption is just a habit. Once you kick off the habit, you won''t even miss it! But to make this goal attainable, allow yourself one can, or 12oz of soda per day. \n\n<h3>2. No More Elevators</h3>\n\nThis is a very specific goal and a very healthy one. Unless you need to climb 20 floors, always taking the stairs will make a big difference in your health and fitness levels, especially if you work in an office building and use the elevator every day. \n\n<h3>3. No Food After 8pm</h3>\n\nAgain, this is a very specific goal so it''s easier to keep. It will help you cut junk calories, because when we eat at night, we usually reach for junk. Just like drinking soda, snacking on junk in front of the TV is just a habit, one that if you manage to kick off (and it takes about 2 weeks of consistency to kick off a bad habit), you won''t even miss. To help you achieve this goal, it would be helpful if you stop keeping junk food in the house. \n\nWhatever your goals are for the New Year, remember to keep them simple and attainable. \n\nWe wish you a happy and healthy New Year!', 'Three New Year Resolutions You Can Keep!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'three-new-year-resolutions-you-can-keep', '', '', '2010-12-30 05:00:52', '2010-12-30 12:00:52', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=515', 0, 'post', '', 0),
