(549, 9, '2010-12-14 11:58:18', '2010-12-14 18:58:18', 'I am so excited for the opportunity to partner with a company like VOSKOS. I have been such a fan for a long time. Not always the “clean eater”, I am now, and VOSKOS has certainly helped me in my journey to living a healthier lifestyle.\n\nMy name is Jenny Grothe, and I’m guessing the majority of you have never heard of me.\n\nBut, I’m also guessing once you hear my story, it is one that will sound familiar on too many levels.\n\n<strong>Three years ago I was 170 pounds</strong>. That was September 2007 – really not that long ago. Now thinking back I can’t believe how much has changed in such a short period of time. I am a completely different person now. I was always the same “me” on the inside, but I’m now the “happier”, more “confident”, “driven”, “courageous”, “energetic” me that I was when I was younger. Much younger.\n\nMy teenage years weren’t out of the ordinary. I was “slim” by teenager standards. I never worked out. I didn’t have to. I was athletic, participated in school sports, and I ate pretty much anything and everything I wanted. Remember those days? I didn’t know a carb from a protein. I just ate.\n\nBut, being a young lady, I wasn’t completely oblivious to my figure.\n\nAs a senior I remember going to the doctor for a physical. I don’t remember much about my visits to the doctor as a youth, but I do remember that one in particular. <strong>My doctor mentioned I had “great birthing hips.” </strong>“Uh, thanks. What’s that supposed to mean? Great birthing hips? You mean my hips are wide? What?” That was the first time I’d had someone else – especially someone of a respectable authority even hint to me that I had a weight problem. Again, looking back and now knowing what I know, I didn’t, but at the time I was crushed and felt insecure.\n\nI was 118 pounds. I wore a size 3, and I had ‘great birthing hips.’\n\nTime passed.\n\nAnother incident happened when I was in college. My best friend Cami and I took a modeling class. I never felt like a model, but we both thought it would be a fun after-school activity, and why not “pretend”?\n\nThe class really was pretty fun. We got to dress up, learn proper etiquette, learn how to do our hair and make up (granted it was the 80s so in order to do our hair, we simply had to tease it “higher”), and practice our walks for the runway.\n\nThen there were our one on one meetings with our teacher.\n\n“<strong>Jenny, your thighs touch. We can’t be having that.”</strong> What? My thighs touch? All of a sudden I was aware that my (skinny) little thighs actually rubbed when I walked. I’d never even noticed that before. I evaluated the star pupil of the class – the teachers pet. Her thighs didn’t touch. But mine did. Every. Single. Step.\n\nI was 121 pounds. I still wore a junior size 3, but my thighs touched.\n\n<strong>That was just the beginning. I share this because as women we are surrounded by unfair expectations. Basically we are told our bodies are not good enough when they actually, they are. Based on society, we are supposed to be taller, thinner, and lighter, and look a certain way. It starts early. And in like my case, I was a size 3, but those expectations to be skinnier were still there.</strong>\n\nMoving on to my adult years – when my body really did start to change.\n\nMy 20s were pretty non eventful body image wise.\n\nGreg and I marred in 1991. We move to Utah. We earned $5 an hour. We both worked at the same company – I worked early mornings; he worked afternoons and evenings. We rarely saw each other. When we weren’t working we went to school. We live in an apartment across the street from Walmart. We ate what we could afford, and that wasn’t much.\n\nWe stocked up on Lynn Wilson burritos, shoestring French fries, store brand chicken pot pies, and soda. Our dinners out included frequent visits to Taco Bell an their .59 cent menus. As newlyweds we had no one hanging over our shoulders telling us what we could and could not do. I’d never lived outside my mom and dad’s house until I was married. I’d had to prior college experience to prep me. I went straight from my parents to married life – which meant I had a newfound freedom that made me think I could now do things I couldn’t do before. A lot of that freedom came in the form of food. We’d fill up our big jugs before work with fully loaded caffeinated sugary drinks. We’d chug them all day long.\n\nFor our dates out, we loved going to the drive-in to see double features. I had a small pickup truck at the time which I’d had as a teenager. We loved nothing more than to pack our pillows and sleeping bags in the back and head to a double feature. But we’d first stock up on all the goodies – bags of chips, cheese dip, salsa, a box of raspberry filled donuts, boxed candies, and our big 64 oz. containers of soda. It was ridiculous. Yet at the time we were young, our bodies were still burning through those calories like crazy, and we had freedom. It was okay. We were only accountable to each other, and we were having a great time. As long as we weren’t getting “fat”, who cared? We didn’t even think twice about our diets. Ever.\n\nIt didn’t catch up to us for a long time.\n\n--\nStay tuned for part 2 of Jenny''s story. It will be posted here tomorrow!', 'My Journey to a Healthier Lifestyle', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'journey-to-healthier-lifestyle', '', '', '2010-12-14 11:58:18', '2010-12-14 18:58:18', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=549', 0, 'post', '', 5),
(559, 9, '2010-12-15 05:00:14', '2010-12-15 12:00:14', 'Click here to read the first part of Jenny''s amazing <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/journey-to-healthier-lifestyle">journey to health and fitness</a>.\n\nOur 20s came and went quickly. Though I never saw a huge change on the scale, we had changed. Our habits had changed. Our lifestyles had changed. <strong>We spent our 20s building bad habits</strong>. We ate all the time or not at all. We ‘pigged out’ by hitting cheap breakfast buffets. We didn’t exercise. We didn’t read labels. We didn’t think about healthy options. We ate out of convenience and limited our options to what we liked out of what we could afford.\n\nThen came our 30s. I remember so many people telling me, “it will catch up to you in your 30s.” Yeah, right. Old wives tale. What was so magical about my 30s?\n\n<strong>By the time I entered my 30s my metabolism had slowed</strong>. After years and years of consuming unhealthy foods with very limited physical activity, my body didn’t respond the way it had when I was younger. By this time Greg and I very rarely did anything active. We didn’t take walks. We didn’t go for jogs (not that we ever had done that before), and we didn’t hike. Neither one of us competed in city or church sports. We just continued with our same poor habits and our inactive lifestyles, watching our bodies slowly deteriorate, not knowing really what to do, but also not really wanting to change anything.\n\n<strong>I was around 150 pounds.</strong>\n\nMy 30s is when I first looked at dieting seriously. There were so many options out there. Too many. Atkins. The Zone Diet. Weight Watchers. Jenny Craig. Low-carb this and high-protein that.\n\nIt feels like I tried them all:\n\nI read the Zone Diet\nI tried the Atkins Diet\nThen Weight Watchers\nAnd Jenny Craig\nAnd finally Body for Life\n\nAll of them had different rules, different disciplines, offered different advice, and made different promises…all with one goal…to lose weight.\n\nI was slightly successful with some, not at all with others. <strong>My weight yo-yoed up and down</strong>. The problem was, none of them stuck. None of them were a livable lifestyle for me. So, after losing a few pounds (or in the case of Body for Life 20 pounds), I’d slowly retreat to old habits, and I’d gain it all back.\n\n<strong>By the summer of 2007 I was wearing a size 14 and weighed 170  pounds.</strong>\n\nI was physically at my worst. By most peoples’ standards, I was borderline ‘fat’. I hate to use that word, but I was. At the time I never really felt that way. I still tried to wear cute clothes, I paid every detail to putting on m make up just right, highlighting my hair, and styling it just the way I wanted. I knew I needed to lose weight. I wasn’t oblivious to the scale, but I didn’t realize just how much.\n\nI remember at the time watching TV, reading celeb magazines, and even seeing VS commercials thinking to myself, that will NEVER be me. Secretly I’d always wanted to be one of them as a teenager. But by the time I reached 170 pounds in my early 30s<strong> I felt like my best years were behind me.</strong> I’d never never “be” one of them, and I’d definitely never “look” like one of them. And the thought of me wearing a sexy swimsuit like the VS models? Laughable.\n\nThen a series of events started to unfold, and they crept under my skin.\n\nIn our mid 30s we moved into a new neighborhood. We were within a couple of miles of where Greg went to school. We were back in his stomping grounds. We’ve always been active members of our church, but this neighborhood took “active” to an entirely new level. We were wooed into doing things with our church and neighbors several times a week.\n\nWe became quick friends with a few families in our neighborhood. They were amazing. Friendly, loving, charitable, service-oriented, and extremely out-going. We learned quickly that they would do anything for us, and that their friendships were genuine. Not an ounce of fakeness. We grew to love them, and they are some of our best friends to date.\n\nBut…all of the wives in our new circle were tiny. One was a size 0 (yes, that number does exist), one was a size 2, another a size 4, and the other a size 6. Then there was me. Jenny. Size 14. My size was more than the sum of all theirs. Why did they want to be friends with me?\n\nThey did though. Just like me wonderful husband, they loved me unconditionally.\n\nBeing a part of this active group meant I was now attempting to do things I hadn’t done for years. They enjoyed camping, hiking, swimming, playing with the kids outdoors. They helped me remember how fun it was to be youthful again.\n\nDuring one our get-togethers we were playing “tag” in the back yard. We laid out several blankets on the grass. Everyone had to choose a blanket to stand on. There was one “shark” who’s job was to catch one of us as we scurried from one blanket to another – not wanting to be “caught”. It was a fun game, and I remember my heart skipped a beat because being chased had always scared me as a kid. But it wasn’t that that really made my heart stop. One of the husbands, a good friend of ours, mentioned under his breath, but just loud enough for me to overhear, “Are you sure Jenny will be able to do this?” It took me back to the day when I was told I had great “birthing hips’ or the time when I was told my “thighs touched.” Up to that point I’d felt like my weight problem was just me. It was at that moment I realized OTHER people noticed how big I was too.\n\nThen there was another time. We moms decided it would be fun to take the kiddos to St. George for a quick getaway. One of our adventures would be hiking through the Small Narrows – a narrow opening (crevice) between two sides of the mountain. I was a little hesitant but excited at the same time. The kids practically ran through it – facing forward – no problems whatsoever. The moms had to inch through on their sides. I let them all go ahead of me. I would follow behind. I started through the narrow path at first with no problem. There were a couple of patches where it was pretty tight, but I was able to suck in and push through – fully knowing I was probably tearing up my clothes.\n\nThen came an obstacle. I had to step-up while on my side in a very narrow section of the path. I couldn’t do it. I was stuck. I stayed there literally for minutes, sweat beading up on my face. I was embarrassed, scared, and was afraid they’d have to get help. This is NO exaggeration. At this point the other moms were still moving along through the narrows – they had no idea was left behind struggling. I thought for sure I’d have to call out to them. I didn’t want to. It was at that moment I realized again how big I was. Somehow I managed to get my leg up and carefully pull myself up, but it wasn’t easy. It was extremely difficult. When everyone opted to go through again, I opted out. I’d had enough.\n\nSo many experiences like that happened during the summer of 2007. I''m guessing they’d been happening all along but by that summer I’d had enough. Each and every bad experience got under my skin like fingernails on a chalk board. <strong></strong>\n\n<strong>I was tired of being the "big" friend. I was tired of people worrying whether I could complete things, participate in things, fit into things. I was tired of being embarrassed about my body. I was tired of hiding from the camera. I was tired of being the friend who took all the pictures but never wanted to be in them. I was tired of trying to overcompensate by having great hair, makeup, and jewelry in order to feel better about myself. I was tired of feeling older than I was. I was tired. Period.</strong>\n\nAnd I was done.\n\n--\nThe third and final part of Jenny''s story will be published tomorrow. Stay tuned!', 'A Journey to a Healthier Lifestyle: Part 2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'jenny-grothe-journey-healthier-lifestyle', '', '', '2010-12-15 05:00:14', '2010-12-15 12:00:14', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=559', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(566, 9, '2010-12-16 05:00:40', '2010-12-16 12:00:40', 'The first part of Jenny''s amazing story appears <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/journey-to-healthier-lifestyle">here</a>. You can find the second part <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/jenny-grothe-journey-healthier-lifestyle">here</a>.\n\nI think it was then that I had my breaking point. Everything came to a head. I was 37. I was ashamed I’d let most of my 30s go and that my body had gotten out of hand. 40 was right around the corner, and I wanted to do something about it.\n\nSo when I ran into my friend at the craft store and she told me her husband could get me a great deal on a gym pass, I snagged it. It was one of those times when you act first and ask for permission later. I didn’t want to talk with my husband first. I knew what he would say. I’d had gym memberships in the past only to never follow through. Two of them in fact. I’d do at first but then stop. I’d find an excuse. I knew he wouldn’t approve of me making the same mistake a third time. <strong>But somehow deep inside I knew this time would be different. It had to be</strong>. I felt it. I was compelled to change my body. So, I wrote her a check and did it. I was signed up. I later told my husband, and he shook his head in disbelief, like, “Yeah, right. What a waste. Will you ever learn?” But it was too late.\n\nI just knew this time I’d follow through.\n\nThe day I dropped my oldest boy off for 1st grade I hit the gym. It was his first day, and it was my first day. The first several weeks I spent most of my time on the bike or walking on the treadmill. I’d been to the gym with my mom as a teenager, so I knew a bit about weight training, but not much. So, I spent my time doing cardio but observing what others were doing on the weight machines. I was a very good observer. When I was done with cardio, I’d dink around on the machines. I didn’t know anything about form. I didn’t know how heavy to go, how many sets, or how many reps. I didn’t know which machines worked which body part. I didn’t have a clue. But I toyed around on them just the same. I had every entitlement that everyone else there did. I pretended to know what I was doing. And when trainers (some of them being real salespeople with salesman-like attitudes) approached me to help (for a fee of course) I declined.\n\nI did this for a couple of months. Cardio and machines. I made a habit of taking books with me to the gym to read. I read the entire Twilight series on the bike. I could get lost  in my books while doing cardio. When I wasn’t reading, I was watching trainers…train. I had a few favorites. But there was one female trainer in particular I was impressed with. She was extremely athletic looking and had the best arms. Her shoulders popped. She was cut. I wanted to look like her. There were other trainers too that looked like they knew what they were doing, but I wanted her to train me. I didn’t want a guy. I wanted a girl who could relate to me, my body type, and the fun womanly issues we deal with. So, one morning I approached her.<strong> I simply told her I wanted her arms and that she needed to train me. She was a busy trainer. She had many many clients. She sized me up, and said, “okay." </strong>\n\nAnd that was the beginning.\n\nShe was a figure competitor. When I approached her she had been cutting up for a show. She was lean. Of course then I didn’t even know what a figure competitor was.\n\n<strong>Hiring a trainer when I first started (or close to it) was one of the best things I could do</strong>. She took me around to several of the machines. She taught me about proper form. She taught me about drop sets. She gave me structure, a plan, and confidence. With her help I felt strong. I was well on my way.\n\nBy December I’d dropped 20 pounds. I was now roughly 150 pounds. I was back into a size 10, and I felt on top of the world. <strong>For the first time in years I felt attractive. I felt pretty</strong>. I loved that I had to go shopping to get SMALLER clothes. I loved giving away all my BIGGER clothes. I was happy to shop for trendy clothes and accessories. It almost felt like I was discovering a long, lost, and forgotten me. It felt GREAT!\n\nAround that same time my trainer asked me if I’d had any interest in competing. It was then that I learned about figure. She showed me her pics and she told me I should try it. She’d realized that I was a hard worker and that every workout she’d given me I’d followed through with and then some. I could see some changes in my body without a doubt, but I’d never thought about competing. I still had so much further to go. Apparently she saw something in me that I didn’t see yet myself.\n\nOne thing I should share…at the same time I made a commitment to take my body back I also made a promise to myself to try everything. I started a bucket list and was adding goals to it daily. I no longer wanted my life to live me, I wanted to live my life. I wanted to take charge. I wanted to try new things. I wanted to have adventures. I wanted to grow old and have no regrets.\n\nSo…when she asked me about competing, I figured “why not?” What could it hurt? At the very worst I might not be stage ready by the time the competition came around but I’d be so much further along than if I didn’t have a goal. So, I went for it on complete faith. I nowhere looked the part, and a part of me was so embarrassed to tell people I knew what I was doing. What if I failed? What if I changed my mind? What if leaned out and didn’t have any muscle? What if I was the laughing stock of the competition? What would people think? All these thoughts ran through my mind. I was scared. But I was excited too. What if I looked great? I decided to focus on the latter.\n\n<strong>One year after the first day I stepped foot in the gym, I competed in my first competition. I took 2nd in my first show. I couldn’t have been more proud. </strong>\n\nThat year was eventful.\n\nMy bucket list continued to grow, and I made a point to compete in whatever I could.\n\nSeptember 2007 I was 170 pounds with my self-esteem at its lowest. Its also when I started back to the gym.\n\nThat next March I ran my first 5k with several more to follow.\n\nMay 2008 I competed in my first sprint triathlon with a second one in June.\n\nJuly 2008 I ran my first 10k with a second one later in the month.\n\nSeptember 2008 I stepped on stage for my first figure competition with a second one in October.\n\nNovember 2008 I ran my first half marathon.\n\nAll of that within a year of owning a “Make it Count,” “Never say never,” “Giving up is not an option” attitude. It felt great.\n\nSince then I’ve gone on to compete in 7 shows, bringing home 5 trophies in the process.  I’ve lead my team two years in a row for the Wasatch Back Ragnar Relay. I’ve ran four half marathons, and two full marathons. Most recently I qualified for the Boston Marathon which I’ll be running during the Spring of 2011.\n\n<strong>I’ve learned that even at 40, you can lose weight. You can reshape your body. You can increase your endurance. You can eat yummy foods. You don’t have to starve yourself. You can actually eat all day long, and as long as it is good, clean, substantial food, it will actually help you lose or maintain your weight. Food doesn’t have to be the enemy. My body doesn’t have to be the enemy. I am more energized than ever. And I am almost 40.</strong>\n\nWhat I’ve learned is it''s never too late. We ALL can improve. We ALL have it in us. It starts with perception, drive, and will-power. You have to want it bad enough. You have to make a series of right choices, and when you do fail, you need to get back up and push forward. Don’t give up. Don’t give in. Don’t let bad habits and old lifestyles win. I can say this with confidence because I fought those demons too.\n\nAnd while I realize that there are so many incredible women out there who have lost oodles more weight than I have, this was my own personal battle.\n\nLooking forward I can’t wait to celebrate my 40th birthday. It’s coming up quickly – just a little over a month.\n\nThe biggest difference other than my weight loss between before and now? Now I know when I say I’ll do something…there’s a really good chance I’ll actually do it, and if not, I’ll fail trying my hardest.\n\nPhoto credit: Camille Funk', 'My Journey to a Healthier Me: Part 3', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'journey-to-a-healthier-me', '', '', '2010-12-16 05:00:40', '2010-12-16 12:00:40', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=566', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(574, 3, '2010-11-02 11:20:28', '2010-11-02 18:20:28', 'Makes 8 cupcakes\n\nRecipe courtesy of Stef from the <a href="http://www.cupcakeproject.com/2010/09/yogurt-and-honey-cupcakes-taste-of.html" target="_blank">Cupcake Project</a> and was adapted from a honey cake recipe by <a href="http://zspecialtyfood.com/" target="_blank">Z Specialty Foods</a>. \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1/2 C honey (plus extra for topping)\n1/3 C unsalted butter, melted\n2 eggs\n1/4 C Voskos Greek yogurt\n1 tsp vanilla\n1 1/2 C all-purpose flour\n1 tsp baking powder\n1/2 tsp baking soda\n1/2 tsp salt \nVoskos Greek yogurt for topping\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a medium-sized mixing bowl, mix honey and melted butter together. \n2. Beat in eggs, one at a time. \n3. Stir in vanilla and Greek yogurt.\n4. In another medium-sized bowl, whisk together flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt.\n5. Slowly mix the flour mixture into the honey mixture until smooth.\n6. Fill cupcake liners 3/4 full.\n7. Bake at 350 F for 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out dry.\n8. Allow cupcakes to cool.\n9. Just before serving, top with Greek yogurt and drizzle with honey.\n\n<b>Nutrition</b>\nPer one cupcake, excluding topping\nCalories 237\nTotal Fat 9g\nCholesterol 66mg\nSodium 226mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 35g\nDietary Fiber 1\nSugars 17g\nProtein 2g\n', 'Greek Yogurt Honey Cupcakes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'yogurt-honey-cupcakes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=574', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(583, 9, '2010-12-20 05:00:45', '2010-12-20 12:00:45', 'I eat clean 95% of the time.\n\nOver the last few years I’ve chosen a lifestyle without many of my old “favorites” – Pizza, Ice cream, Cheesecake, Mexican Food, Hamburgers, you name it. The old me? I didn’t think about food. I simply ate what I wanted when I wanted it. Now? I “schedule” my “cheats” (as I like to call them). I still allow the occasional indulgence, but I choose not to make them a part of my day to day diet.\n\nInstead I eat “clean” – meaning less fatty, non-processed foods. The greener and the the more natural the better. I moderate my calories, carbs, fats, and sodium. I’m selectively cautious.\n\nLast Saturday night? Not even close to cautious. As a matter of fact, I threw ALL caution to the wind. It was date night, and it was going to  be a scheduled “cheat.”\n\nSince I’m the picky one when it comes to eating out 9 times out of 10, I thought it was only fair I let my sweet husband pick this time.\n\nHe picked Pizza Pie Cafe. Here''s the premise...they serve a buffet of different pizzas...savory and sweet. Here are a few of their tempting offerings:\n\nBuffalo Wing Thing Pizza\nChicken Ranch Pizza\nBarbecue Chicken Pizza\nSpud-o-licious Pizza\nChocolate Chip Cookie Dough Pizza\nOreo Pizza\nPeach Cobbler Pizza\n\nAnd there were many more.\n\nThose are just the ones I tried. I hadn’t had pizza since April, so yes, I overdid it. I overate. I cleaned my plate, and I went back for more.  I enjoyed every single bite…\n\nIt wasn''t more than 20 minutes after my last bite that my stomach started to fight back.\n\nI felt absolutely stuffed. I was bloated, and my stomach was now grumbling, and NOT in a good way.\n\nI used to eat like that all the time which is what’s surprising to me. I now remembered that uncomfortable feeling after large meals.\n\nI''m NOT going to say that I didn''t enjoy my pizza, because honestly? I did. I loved it. I was giddy with excitement. I felt like a kid in a candy store.\n\nBut<strong> it was the aftermath that reminded me one of the key reasons I choose to eat clean. It''s how I feel when I eat clean. I feel good, comfortably full, clean on the inside and clean on the outside. I don''t feel bloated. I don''t feel sick. I don''t feel guilty.</strong> I don''t feel like I''m going to toss my cookies at any second. I feel like I am actually nourishing my body rather than destroying it. Clean eating makes me feel good, mentally AND physically.\n\nEating "crap" (for lack of a better term) gives me a short-term rush of excitement but afterward I''m left feeling sick.\n\nSaturday''s date night was a good reminder for me. I am ALL for cheat meals. That won''t be my last one. I believe in allowing treats every now and again, and I''m not dumb enough to say I''ll never do the same thing twice. I''ll probably even at some point go back.\n\nBut it was a good reminder that eating clean has so many benefits - some of which we forget when we do it so regularly. After Saturday, I am thankful for the reminder.', 'Why I Choose to Eat Clean', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'why-i-choose-to-eat-clean', '', '', '2010-12-20 05:00:45', '2010-12-20 12:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=583', 0, 'post', '', 4),
(584, 3, '2010-11-03 05:00:09', '2010-11-03 12:00:09', 'These simple muffins are delicate and moist. They are great with coffee (for the grownups) or with milk (for the kids).\n\nMakes 12 muffins\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1.5 cups flour\n1 teaspoon baking soda\n1 cup sugar\n0.5 cup softened butter\n3 eggs\n0.5 cup plain original VOSKOS\n3 TBS whole milk\n1 TBS vanilla extract\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 350\n2. Whisk butter and sugar together, then add egg mixture\n3. Add VOSKOS, milk and vanilla\n4. Mix flour with baking soda and gradually add to liquid mixture, incorporating well.\n5. Fill muffin tin cups almost full.\n6. Bake 20 minutes, or until golden brown and a toothpick inserted in center comes out clean.\n7. Dust with powdered sugar and ENJOY!', 'Vanilla Greek Yogurt Muffins', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'vanilla-greek-yogurt-muffins', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=584', 0, 'post', '', 4),
(591, 3, '2011-01-11 05:00:11', '2011-01-11 12:00:11', '"American society has become ''obesogenic,'' characterized by an environment that promotes  increased food intake, non-healthful foods, and physical inactivity", <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/index.html" target="_blank">says</a> the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.\n\nWe agree.  Something has happened to us as a society over the past few decades - essentially since the end of the Great Depression. We have grown lazy. We have surrounded ourselves with appliances and gadgets that basically enable us to move very little. Washers and dryers, dishwashers, escalators, elevators, cars - the average American moves very little, especially if she works in an office.\n\nThe saddest thing is, our children move very little too. Children are supposed to be active, to play outside, to explore. But kids today spend most of their time sitting, being entertained by electronics and media. As schools keep making budget cuts, our children exercise very little while at school.\n\nThen there''s the food. Portions are out of control, junk is everywhere, and as you browse through the supermarket shelves, unless you''re very careful to stick with the perimeter isles and stay away from the inside isles, you''re exposed to unimaginable amounts of temptations, including frozen pizzas, ice cream, snacks and candy, frozen meals, all laden with sodium, fat and sugar, not to mention added colorants, artificial flavors and preservatives.\n\nIt''s an environment that makes it very difficult for people to make healthy choices, because our brains and our bodies are still hardwired to conserve energy, and to eat as much as we can while food is available - in case it becomes scarce later.\n\nThe fact that the junk food industry does whatever it takes to make a profit, even if it means pushing unhealthy options, attractively packaging them and even targeting children in commercials, in an attempt to get them hooked at an early age, does not help of course.\n\nSo, is it a lost cause? Are we doomed to become an obese society, suffering from the many diseases and conditions that obesity brings with it?\n\nWe think not. Read the second part of this post, to be published tomorrow, for ways to fight back.', 'Thoughts on the Obesity Epidemic', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'obesity-epidemic', '', '', '2011-01-11 05:00:11', '2011-01-11 12:00:11', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=591', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(599, 3, '2011-01-12 05:00:06', '2011-01-12 12:00:06', 'How do we, as a society, fight the obesity epidemic and go back to being a leaner, more active, healthier society? \n\n"Policy and environmental change initiatives that make healthy choices in nutrition and physical activity available, affordable, and easy will likely prove most effective in combating obesity," says the <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/obesity/index.html">CDC</a>, and we couldn''t agree more.\n\nAfter years of "partying," it is time to accept that we''re paying a heavy (no pun intended!) price for leading a sedentary lifestyle and making bad food choices. As much as change is difficult, it can be done, on the government level through policies, on the corporate level through food manufacturers adopting a more responsible behavior, and of course on the individual level through people''s choices. \n\nOn the government level, we''ve applauded the Healthy Hunger-Free Kids Act of 2010, that was <a href="http://www.parenting.com/new/blogs/show-and-tell/alina-parentingcom/obama-signs-child-nutrition-bill?cid=rss" target="_blank">signed</a> by President Obama in December and gives the government more authority to regulate nutritional standards for all food sold in schools, including cafeteria meals and vending machine options.\n\nOn a corporate level, Voskos is doing its best to not just create a wonderful, healthy, wholesome line of products, but to also give back to the community through our empowering contests and promotions, and through <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/videos/empower-yourself-with-voskos">supporting important causes</a>. \n\nAnd on the individual level? It''s difficult to change bad habits. Extremely difficult! But it can be done, and it''s never too late to start. As our very own Jenny Grothe <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/journey-to-a-healthier-me">says</a>, "I’ve learned that even at 40, you can lose weight. You can reshape your body. You can increase your endurance. You can eat yummy foods. You don’t have to starve yourself. You can actually eat all day long, and as long as it is good, clean, substantial food, it will actually help you lose or maintain your weight. Food doesn’t have to be the enemy. My body doesn’t have to be the enemy."\n\nTogether, we can do it. We can fight back and win. Let''s go back to being a healthy, active America!\n', 'The Obesity Epidemic: Yes, We Can Fight Back', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'fight-obesity-epidemic', '', '', '2011-01-12 05:00:06', '2011-01-12 12:00:06', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=599', 0, 'post', '', 0),
