(615, 9, '2010-12-22 05:00:01', '2010-12-22 12:00:01', 'I''m a creature of habit. I think to some extent we all are. We like to know what to expect. We like to follow a system. We like structure. That goes for everything, and training and diet are no exception.\n\nBut what happens when things don''t go exactly as planned?\n\nI had such an experience just the other day, so I thought I would share that experience with you.\n\nI hadn''t run outside since my marathon in September. Last Friday was to be the day.\n\nAs I mentioned, I am a person of habit, and one of my habits is listening to my iPod when I run. Garmin. Gum. iPod. I''m accustomed to having all three when I run. They are mandatory - not optional.\n\nMy run started off GREAT. It was very cold. My legs felt like ice cubes, and I could see my breath, but surprisingly, it felt great.\n\nAfter one song my iPod died. I hadn''t charged it. There was no warning. I had no indication the day before at the gym that it was dying, so I hadn''t bothered to plug it in through the night. I was barely into my run.\n\nWhat would I do?\n\n<strong>I had two choices. Keep running or go home. I kept running.\n</strong>\nIt made me think though...every day we are faced with so many temptations, opportunities for excuses, reasons to give up, or not even try.\n\nThe words that kept coming back to me were, "What would you do?"\n\nI remember at a very young age my mom and dad teaching me to play different situations out in my head. Pretend I was up against a temptation. Play it out. "What would you do?" Make that decision right now. Sure, it''s not really happening, but what if? They told me that by knowing my answer in advance for any given situation, I''d be more inclined to resist whatever temptation came my way.\n\nNow, I wasn''t always the best at resisting. I gave my mom and dad a run for their money at times, and I certainly exhausted their patience - especially as a teenager. But, in a lot of cases, that advice was truly sound and very important.\n\nAnd it still applies today.\n\nWhat would you do?\n\nEspecially for those of us on our fitness journey. Americans spend billions (not a typo) on weight-loss products, weight loss diets, weight loss quick fixes. We are all striving to look and feel healthier. We all have an image of what we want to look like.\n\n<strong>Yet day after day most people give in. Give up. Throw in the towel. Decide to start over. Wait for another day. Each one of those people were at some point given a choice, "What would you do?" And each one of them sadly, chose to give up. Not everyone does, but there are many that do.</strong>\n\nTake a few moments and think about it.\n\n"What would you do?"\n\n- If you wake up only to find all your gym clothes are dirty\n\n- Your gym partner cancels on you the morning you''re supposed to meet?\n\n-Your gym partner doesn''t show up at all - with no advance warning?\n\n-You have an itch in your throat?\n\n- You didn''t get enough sleep?\n\n-You''ve had a stressful day at home or the office and simply don''t feel like exercising?\n\n-Your car''s batter is dead? (you laugh, but this really did happen to me one morning, and I kid you not, I woke my hubby up at 5 in the morning and made him jump my car)\n\n-You are running errands and it takes longer than you expected, and you have no "clean" meal options with you?\n\n-You didn''t prep enough of your meals ahead of time and find yourself craving a certain snack?\n\n-You are at a get together and are faced by endless unhealthy food options?\n\n-You go out to dinner with a group of friends and are craving something that doesn''t fit within your meal plan?\n\nKeep going...you know what obstacles tend to stand in your way. For each of us they''re different, but you know what YOUR challenges are.\n\n"What would you do?"\n\nI can tell you right now that many of those obstacles I''ve listed above HAVE happened to me at one time or another. Almost every single one of them. And they still do.\n\nRight now we are a week away from Christmas. Family functions. Work parties. Neighborhood gifts and treats. Friend get-togethers. Too much to do in too little time. Too many temptations that are difficult to resist.\n\n<strong>I remind myself three years ago I made a commitment. I vowed that "giving up wouldn''t be an option". No more excuses. I was done starting over. I was done throwing in the towel. I was done making excuses for all the times I didn''t follow through. I''d promised myself I was stronger than any temptation that came my way. And I am.</strong>\n\n<strong>And so are you.</strong>\n\nMy challenge for each of us is to take that little piece of advice my mom and dad shared with me so long ago. "Jenny, what would you do if..." You fill in the blank. Choose now what your answer will be later. That way, if and when those temptations or obstacles come up, you''ll already know your answer.', 'What Would You Do?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-would-you-do', '', '', '2010-12-22 05:00:01', '2010-12-22 12:00:01', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=615', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(622, 3, '2011-02-01 05:00:09', '2011-02-01 12:00:09', 'We asked our <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a> and <a href="http://twitter.com/GoVoskos" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Twitter</a> fans how they usually enjoy their Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a>. Here are some of the yummy, creative responses we’ve received:\n\n1. Voskos blended Greek Honey Yogurt with some peanut butter swirled in is awesomely smooth and tasty plus a quick high protein snack.\n\n2. I like my Voskos savory - with onions, cucumbers and garlic!\n\n3. Purchased Plain Non-fat Voskos at Safeway in Seattle. So Good! Mix it with cinnamon and it is wonderful. Keep it up!\n\n4. Plain, mixed with a little cocoa powder and a touch of sweetener.\n\n5. Honey Honey Honey! So good on its own, and super good as a dip for strawberries.\n\n6. Voskos plain nonfat, a handful dried fruit blend, a handful date pieces, some shredded coconut and a sliced banana, all drizzled with honey.\n\n7. I prefer the plain non-fat yogurt because I add 1 or 2 tablespoons of protein powder for a delicious pudding!\n\n8. My favorite is Voskos yogurt, plain nonfat on top of blueberries, 1 tablespoon of chopped walnuts and a tablespoon of part skim ricotta. Layered, it''s my blueberry cheesecake!\n\n9. If you''re ever in the mood to INDULGE, mix 8oz plain Voskos (non fat, low fat or full fat if you want to REALLY spoil yourself!) with 2 TBS chocolate syrup (the organic varieties are cleaner), then sprinkle some granola on top for some crunch. An incredible dessert with the added bonus of protein, calcium and probiotic cultures!\n\n10. Plain, always with a Local honey added and berries (of any variety) or Ground Flax.\n\n11. Plain yogurt....straw/blueberries....Barlean''s lemon flavored omega oil....shredded coconut....and a dash of stevia....HOWEVER...if I''m EXTRA hungry...I''ll throw in some granola.\n\n12. Ground flax seed and honey!\n\n13. Plain non-fat Voskos with a little Grade B maple syrup, ground flax seeds, walnuts and berries - once a day!\n\n14. Yogurt parfait, made with layers of Voskos plain low fat, fresh grapes, trail mix, and granola sprinkled on top!\n\n15. Last night I mixed some Sun Crystals sweetener, vanilla, walnuts, and banana''s into a cup of FF plain. Let me tell you it was amazing!\n\n16. I stir in blueberries, lemon zest and ginger for breakfast\n\n17. Yesterday for lunch - used in place of mayo for tuna salad.\n\n18. Dinner used in place of sour cream with grilled chicken fajitas and mixed some spicy salsa in for a great dip.\n\n19. Dessert - stir in one tablespoon dark cocoa powder &amp; a packet of Stevia and freeze for a sugar free - almost fat free - frozen chocolate yogurt.\n\n20. FF + flavored oatmeal packets!!!\n\n21. I love to mix in homemade granola and fresh blueberries.\n\n22. Lowfat Voskos, sliced banana, trail mix, coffee!\n\n23. To lighten muffin recipes, pump up the protein and reduce the calories and fat by using fat-free milk and Greek yogurt to replace the regular milk and butter.\n\n24. I Love Voskos Plain Yogurt! One of the ways I enjoy it is for dessert with a spray of whipping cream and a dash of sugar sprinkles (for cupcakes). It''s delicious. The tart yogurt with the sweetest of the whipped cream &amp; sugar sprinkles. It''s a nice little dessert.\n\n25. I don’t use sour cream anymore! Each recipe that calls for sour cream is automatically “healthified” by substituting Voskos  low fat or non fat for the sour cream.\n\n26. Chocolate chip energy bar, crushed and mixed with Greek yogurt the night before, then topped with mashed banana = cheesecake-esque breakfast. Love.\n\n27. Voskos Greek yogurt + medjool dates + wee dab of honey + grape nuts = WIN!\n\n28. 1/2 cup of plain Voskos, 1/4 cup of Udi''s Gluten Free Granola, 1 tablespoon of unsweetened shredded coconut, sprinkled with a dash of Stevia. This one is from our wonderful Facebook fan, <a href="http://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=790102093" target="blank" rel="nofollow">Tracy Lynn</a>.\n\n29. Mix cooked hot bananas, cinnamon and walnuts into Voskos plain yogurt - super delicious and nutritious! \nThis is from our Twitter follower, <a href="http://twitter.com/ExerciseSpace" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">ExerciseSpace</a>. \n\n30. Dipping honey crisp apple slices into Voskos non-fat greek yogurt swirled with cinnamon. So good. This is from our Twitter follower <a href="http://twitter.com/xraphiex" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">xraphiex</a>. Follow us on <a href="http://twitter.com/GoVoskos" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Twitter</a> too! \n\nHow do YOU like your Voskos?', 'One Voskos, 30 Ways', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-eat-greek-yogurt', '', '', '2011-02-01 05:00:09', '2011-02-01 12:00:09', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=622', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(628, 3, '2011-02-08 05:00:59', '2011-02-08 12:00:59', 'Do your kids get back home from school STARVING? Mine sure do, and I used to give in to their requests for "Goldfish" or other types of salty, white-flour-based snacks. But then it dawned on me: they''re so hungry when they get back home, it''s actually the perfect opportunity to introduce wholesome, healthy snacks! I still serve crackers and chips on occasion, but for the most part, my kids'' afternoon snacks consist of the following items - and they eat them very willingly:\n\n1. <strong>Whole wheat pita chips</strong>. Cut whole wheat pita into triangles, brush with a little olive oil, sprinkle a little salt and bake until crispy. Serve with hummus and veggies.\n\n2. <strong>Fruit</strong>. Fruit are so good! You can serve them with dips or freeze them (frozen grapes, bananas) to make then more enticing, but really, most fruit are delicious just the way they are.\n\n3. <strong>Veggies with dips</strong>. Vegetables require a little bit of help to make them more palatable for kids. Kids enjoy dipping, so serve veggies with a low fat dip made with Voskos Low fat yogurt mixed with an onion mix.\n\n4. <strong>Yogurt parfait</strong>. My kids love it when I layer sliced fruit and plain low fat Voskos Greek yogurt, sprinkle with granola and drizzle with honey.\n\n5. <strong>Warm milk with honey and cinnamon</strong>. Milk, especially whole milk, is rich in calories, so I consider milk as liquid food rather than a drink to serve alongside a meal. When it''s cold outside, I warm milk in a saucepan, whisking it with honey and adding some cinnamon. It smells so good and my kids absolutely love it.\n\n6. <strong>Air-popped popcorn</strong>. While movie theater popcorn is typically high is fat and in sodium, we like to make air popped popcorn which is filling, low in calories and high in fiber. I sprinkle it with Parmesan and serve with a piece of fruit for a kid-friendly, balanced mini-meal.\n\n7.<strong> Fruit and cheese kabobs.</strong> It''s the same boring cheddar cheese and fruit, but when it''s cubed or sliced and placed on a skewer, the kids can''t get enough of it!\n\nCan you add anything to this list? What do you like to serve as an after-school snack?', '7 Healthy After School Snacks ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-snacks-for-kids', '', '', '2011-02-08 05:00:59', '2011-02-08 12:00:59', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=628', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(635, 3, '2011-02-17 05:00:45', '2011-02-17 12:00:45', 'We often think about winter as a time to indulge. Hidden underneath layers and sweaters, shedding pounds really doesn''t seem to be a huge priority. But winter is actually a great time to lose weight, and to do so gradually and sensibly. Here''s why:\n\n1.<strong> You have time</strong>. Winter is the perfect time to start a diet, because you''re not under pressure to lose weight fast, so won''t be tempted to go on an unhealthy crash diet. You can take your time and lose weight slowly, and see great results when it''s time to switch to lighter clothes.\n\n2. <strong>Soup is perfect for weight loss!</strong> Soups are an ideal winter food, and they are an ideal diet food too. As long as they are broth-or-vegetable-based, and don''t contain cream or milk, they are tasty, filling, low in calories, and an excellent way to get in several servings of vegetables.\n\n3. <strong>Ice cream is not as tempting.</strong> Sure, there are plenty of winter comfort foods, but let''s face it - in summer, it''s not all about fresh fruit! Most of us have to face an almost daily temptation to consume ice cream during the summer. In the winter, the pressure is off.\n\n4. <strong>Snow sports are so much fun!</strong> If you ski, or engage in other snow sports such as snowshoeing, winter is a great time to get in exercise that is fun, exhilarating AND burns large amounts of calories. But even if you''re not into winter sports, you can still go to the gym, swim in a heated indoor pool or go for brisk walks a few days each week.\n\nWinter or summer, you should never go on an extreme diet. Extreme dieting may weaken your immune system, and in winter that means making you more susceptible to colds and the flu. Eat healthy foods in moderation, drink plenty of fluids, warm up before you exercise, and take your time! 1-2 pounds a week is the ideal rate for a healthy, sustainable weight loss.', 'Why Winter Is The Perfect Time to Lose Weight', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'winter-diet', '', '', '2011-02-17 05:00:45', '2011-02-17 12:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=635', 0, 'post', '', 0);
