(657, 9, '2010-12-27 11:14:24', '2010-12-27 18:14:24', 'I can hardly believe Christmas has come and gone. This season was a complete blur. My mom and grandma used to tell me that as I grew older the holidays would fly by faster and faster. I didn’t understand what they meant until this year. This was the first year I really couldn’t get a grip on everything. Too many activities. Too many commitments. Too many places we had to be. Too much shopping. Too much cooking, baking, preparation, and baking some more. I’m not one to complain because I am the furthest thing from a scrooge, but this year the holidays simply got the best of me. I’m drained.\n\nBut yesterday as we all sat down around the Christmas tree, my entire family, those I hold most dear and love more than anything, I was finally overcome with the Christmas spirit. My heart was full. As I looked at my sweet husband and watched him watch our two energetic kids. As I exchanged looks with my all-too-knowing mom and chuckled at my dad who was always thinking of the next dry comment to make. As I looked over at my sister. Everyone was there. My family. And for the most part we were all healthy.\n\nIt was then I was reminded how blessed I am for all that I have.\n\nSure, I didn’t have as much time as I’d wanted, I didn’t follow through on every single advent activity with my kids as I’d hoped, and I didn’t get to watch as many Christmas movies this year as I had in the past. This year we cut back, so we didn’t have as many gifts under the tree. I could have easily gotten wrapped up in the “have nots” and the “I didn’t dos”.\n\nYesterday morning that all seemed to fade away as we sat together, somewhat still, with only the chaos of the kids opening presents. It was then that I remembered I have more than most.\n\n♦ I have a wonderful husband who I’ve known for 22 years and have been married to for nearly 20.\n♦ I have two beautiful, healthy, active little boys – one who’s approaching his pre-teen years and the other still in diapers.\n♦ I have my mom who’s also my best friend who I can call and talk to any time I want.\n♦ I have a dad who loves me, supports me, and still gives me advice as I need it.\n♦ I have a warm home that keeps my family and me safe.\n♦ I have food on my table and <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">healthy food</a> at that!\n♦ I have a healthy body that allows me to do everything I need and want to.\n♦ I have courage and confidence to try new things.\n♦ I have talents that are unique to me that can develop over time.\n♦ I have the ability to laugh at myself.\n♦ I have and know what love and joy feels like.\n♦ I have so much that I often take for granted.\n\nIt’s easy to focus on the “have nots.” We are surrounded by material wants and desires. I’m sure I’ll find myself there again. But this Christmas, I realized again how lucky I am and tried to focus on all “I have” in my life.', 'Focusing More on the “Haves” and less on the “Have Nots”', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'focusing-on-the-haves', '', '', '2010-12-27 11:14:24', '2010-12-27 18:14:24', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=657', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(661, 3, '2010-11-08 05:00:42', '2010-11-08 12:00:42', 'Light, moist, and not too sweet. Recipe courtesy of <a href="http://www.familyfriendlyfood.com/2010/11/orange-yogurt-cake-and-too-much-sugar/" target="_blank">Family Friendly Food</a>.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour\n2 teaspoons baking powder\n1/2 teaspoon salt\n1 cup Plain Voskos\n3/4 cup sugar\n3 extra-large eggs, room temperature\n2 small oranges, juiced and zested\n1/2 teaspoon pure vanilla extract\n1/2 cup canola oil\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Grease an 8 1/2 by 4 1/4 inch loaf pan. Line the bottom with parchment paper. Grease and flour the pan.\n2. Sift together the flour, baking powder, and salt into one bowl.\n3. In another bowl, whisk together the yogurt, sugar, eggs, zest, and vanilla.\n4. Slowly whisk the dry ingredients into the wet ingredients. Whisk the oil into the batter, until it’s all incorporated.\n5. Pour the batter into the prepared pan and bake for about 50-60 minutes, or until a cake tester placed in the center of the loaf comes out clean.\n6. When the cake is done, allow it to cool in the pan for 10 minutes. While the cake is still warm, pour the orange juice over the cake and allow it to soak in. Let cool before removing from pan and slicing.', 'Orange Greek Yogurt Cake', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-cake', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=661', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(662, 9, '2011-01-05 05:00:34', '2011-01-05 12:00:34', 'Lately a lot of people have been telling me how lucky I am.\n\nI’m not going to argue that I am lucky. I know I am. I am very blessed. I remind myself of that every day. Some days I physically “pinch” myself. I love my life at this very moment.\n\nBut it’s not all luck, and it didn’t just happen. Luck didn’t just happen to fall into my lap. It rarely does. I created it.\n\nI recently heard a quote I really enjoyed, "When people say to me: "How do you do so many things?" I often answer them without meaning to be cruel: "How do you do so little?" It seems to me that people have vast potential. Most people can do extraordinary things if they have the confidence or take the risks. Yet most people sit in front of the TV and treat life as if it goes on forever." -- Phillip Adams﻿\n\nIt’s so true. Some people look at me with glazed eyes, like “Why would she want to have such a full plate? Why does she want to do so much?” Others look at me wondering, “Why her and not me?” While others ask me, “How did I get so lucky?”\n\nThe easy answer is I create my own luck, I follow my heart, and I look for opportunities.\n\nMy dad taught me how to be disciplined from a very young age. I’ve always known the meaning of working hard for something I wanted. I also knew that if I wanted something, it was up to me to make it happen. If I wanted it, I needed to go after it. If it was something out of my reach, outside of my skillset, then I made sure I learned the skills required to have it.\n\nIt’s exactly what I am doing now. Everything I do is with meaning, with purpose, and is exactly what my heart tells me to do. I absolutely love working with women. I love feeling healthy. I love my weight-loss journey and the learnings I’ve gained as a result. I love networking with women and men. I love cooking. I love food. I love social media. Everything I am involved in now is so “me.” It feels right.\n\nIf you would have asked me a year ago if I thought by the end of 2010 I’d come out with a cookbook, I would have told you no. If you would have asked me if I thought I’d be sponsored by a great nutrition supplement company like TopForm, again I would have said no. If you would have asked me if I thought I’d work with Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a>, I would have said no.\n\nBut even not knowing a year ago, I followed my heart. Layer upon layer I laid the groundwork. I committed my whole self – not knowing what the future would hold. By following my passion and doing what I loved with real intent, doors started opening.\n\nAs those doors opened, I put myself out there.\n\n<strong>It’s about being proactive. Knowing what you want and pursuing it. This goes for anything. Relationships, weight loss, new hobbies, exercise, whatever it might be. You have to make a decision for yourself and follow through. You can create your own opportunities, just like I’ve done. </strong>\n\nWhat is it you most want? What skills do you need to have in order to get it? Are you ready now? How can you be working towards your goal? Break it down in to smaller steps. Have a plan. Be courageous. Put yourself out there. Have faith. Be okay with rejection. You’ll never know unless you try.\n\n“Fall seven times, stand up eight.” -Japanese Proverb\n\nIt’s not about luck. It’s about unleashing our infinite potential. It’s about being open, thinking big, while laying the groundwork by doing the small things first.\n\nThink big. Unleash YOUR vast potential. Create YOUR opportunities.', 'It’s About Creating Opportunities, Not About Luck', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'creating-opportunites', '', '', '2011-01-05 05:00:34', '2011-01-05 12:00:34', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=662', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(665, 3, '2010-11-09 13:46:29', '2010-11-09 20:46:29', 'This recipe, courtesy of <a href="http://www.drwardbond.blogspot.com/">Dr. Ward Bond</a>, makes 12-14 cupcakes. This recipe yields 28 grams of protein, or 2 grams of protein per each cupcake. 16 grams come from the two brown organic eggs and 12 grams come from the half cup of Voskos Greek Yogurt Original, which was used in place of a half cup of oil.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 - 	Arrowhead Mills Brownie Mix (contains chocolate chips)\n2 -   	Eggs\n¼ cup - water\n½ cup - Voskos Greek Yogurt Plain Original\n10-12oz - Heath Bar English Toffee Bits\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit. Line cupcake pan with cupcake liners.\n2. Mix eggs, water, yogurt in a bowl with the brownie mix. Blend until smooth.\n3. Fill each cupcake liner halfway. Bake 18-20 minutes. Use a toothpick to check brownie cupcakes in the center. When the toothpick is pulled out clean, they’re done!\n4. Immediately put pan on wire rack. Take Heath Bar bits and place on top of each cupcake. Wrap foil around and over the pan and let them cool completely. The heat allows the bits to adhere to the brownie.\n5. After cooling, share with family and friends!', 'Chocolate Chip Cupcakes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'chocolate-chip-brownie-cupcakes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '2013-08-05 21:01:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=665', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(666, 3, '2011-03-02 05:00:55', '2011-03-02 12:00:55', 'Some weight loss experts will tell you that "a calorie is a calorie," and that the only thing that really matters for weight loss - or maintenance - is not eating more calories than you burn.\n\nWhile this is true to some extent, we have found from personal experience that not all calories are equal. Of course, in terms of health, consuming a 300-calorie donut is not the same as consuming 300 calories in eggs, <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">nonfat Greek yogurt</a>, veggies and whole wheat bread.\n\n"Not all calories are equal" is also true when it comes to how you feel when you eat certain foods. We here at Voskos believe in the "80/20 rule" - if you make healthy choices 80% of the time, it''s OK to indulge in less-healthy options the rest of the time. This is a great way to make sure you stay healthy while not depriving yourself. It allows you more freedom on weekends, holidays and special occasions while making sure you don''t go overboard (after all, most of the time you should make good choices).\n\nWhen we eat well - balanced meals, whole grains, colorful fruit and veggies and lots of protein to keep us satiated, we feel amazing. We hardly ever experience those annoying dips in blood sugar that make us feel lethargic and cause cravings. We can eat a lot of food and remain slim.\n\nBut when we stray (hey, we''re human after all) and instead of 80/20 we do 20/80 for a day or two, we feel horrible! We experience powerful cravings, headaches, we feel hungry all the time, and we even suffer mood swings as our blood sugar fluctuates.\n\nThat''s why we believe in making each calorie count. We each have an allotted amount of daily calories that we can use. It depends on our gender, age, and level of activity. Using these calories wisely - eating good, wholesome foods at least 80% of the time - is the best way to feel good, maintain our blood sugar levels, feel satiated, and stick with our weight loss - or weight maintenance - goals.', 'Make Each Calorie Count', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'make-each-calorie-count', '', '', '2011-03-02 05:00:55', '2011-03-02 12:00:55', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=666', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(670, 3, '2010-11-10 05:00:24', '2010-11-10 12:00:24', 'Recipe courtesy of <a href="http://38milesfrommanhattan.com/" target="_blank">Olivia Saez</a>. \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1.25 cups unbleached all-purpose flour\n1/2 tsp baking powder\n1/4 tsp baking soda\n1/4 tsp salt\n2 eggs\n1 cup sugar\n1/2 cup canola oil\n2 tsp vanilla extract\n1 tsp fresh orange zest\n1/2 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt (non-fat plain is the best for this recipe)\n1/2 cup dried currants\n1/4 cup sliced almonds\n\nGlaze: 1.5 cups Voskos Greek Yogurt (non-fat plain is best, but you can use vanilla), one shot of Cointreau, one cup confectioners’ sugar. Combine all ingredients in a bowl and mix with a hand mixer on high until the mixture thickens slightly. The glaze will still be thin, but creamy.\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Line a baking tin with paper liners; I used the minis here, but you can choose larger cakes, if desired.\n2. Sift the flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt into a medium bowl and set aside. \n3. In a large bowl, beat the eggs and sugar until light and fluffy (about 1 minute or so). \n4. Mix in the oil, orange zest, and vanilla until blended. \n5. Mix in the yogurt until combined. \n6. Blend the flour mixture until completely incorporated and the batter is smooth. \n7. Add the currants and almonds.\n8. Add about 2 tablespoons of the batter to each lined mini-cup. The batter should come to about 1/8 of an inch from the top for the cakes to fluff up. \n9. Bake for about 13-16 minutes (depending on your oven!)\n10. Remove the paper liners before serving and coat the cakes with the glaze. Garnish with any leftover orange zest.\n\n\n\n', 'Currant Almond Cupcakes ', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'currant-almond-cupcakes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=670', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(671, 3, '2011-03-09 05:00:40', '2011-03-09 12:00:40', 'When we go on a diet, we often think about it in terms of something that has a beginning and an end. You start on a certain date, weighing a certain amount of pounds, and you - hopefully - finish a few weeks or months later, when you have arrived at your goal.\n\nWe dislike diets.\n\nThere are many things that cause diets to fail. One of them is the very fact that people see them as something temporary. If a diet is a temporary ordeal that you have to go through in order to get to your goal weight, then once you arrive at your goal, there''s nothing to prevent you from feeling an immense relief (FINALLY I can EAT!), reverting back to your old habits and piling up the pounds.\n\n<strong>Instead of viewing your weight loss journey as something that has a beginning and an end, view it as your new life. </strong>This is how you''re going to eat from now on - and there''s no end to this, so it better be good!\n\nCAN it be good? Of course it can. Good, healthy, wholesome food can be delicious and very satisfying. Just take a look at some of the awesome, <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/">healthy recipes</a> on our recipe blog. As nutritionist Christine Avanti <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/media/video-skinny-chicks-dont-eat-salad">says</a>, “You can eat carbs and protein in each meal, speed up your metabolism  and lose weight. The only way to lose weight is to eat real food,  stabilize your blood sugar and speed up your metabolism.”\n\nThe key is to make a decision that from now on you will eat better. That you will get rid of the junk and focus on good, tasty, wholesome foods. Once you get rid of the junk, and learn to appreciate the subtler tastes and textures of real food, you won''t even crave the salty, fatty stuff anymore. Chances are, it will seem repulsive!\n\nWelcome to your new life, a life of better choices, a life of enjoying delicious, filling foods that are good for you. <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a>, whole wheat bread, fruits, veggies, eggs, legumes, lean meats, fish. Welcome to a new life where you will feel so much more energized, where you <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/make-each-calorie-count">make each calorie count</a> and take great care of this one body you have, the body that needs to serve you for 80+ years.\n\nThis does not have a beginning and an end. This is your new life. Welcome and enjoy!', 'Welcome to Your New Life', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'welcome-to-your-new-life', '', '', '2011-03-09 05:00:40', '2011-03-09 12:00:40', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=671', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(680, 3, '2011-03-16 05:00:08', '2011-03-16 12:00:08', 'Many of us associate "diet" with "hunger."\n\nWe don''t.\n\nFirst of all, we don''t view eating well as a "diet." We view it as <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/welcome-to-your-new-life">a new way of life</a>.\n\nAnd when you make this change and start on this new way of life, we absolutely don''t think that you should be experiencing hunger. On the contrary - once you stop eating sugary junk and start eating wholesome, real foods with lots of protein, your blood sugar level will stabilize, you will stop having wild cravings, and if anything, you will feel more satiated for longer than when you were eating a white-flour-white-sugar-low-fiber diet.\n\nWe couldn''t agree more with <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/media/video-skinny-chicks-dont-eat-salad">Christine Avanti</a>, who says, "You can eat carbs and protein in each meal, speed up your metabolism and lose weight... It’s all about getting away from the idea of starving yourself and putting yourself on a diet. It needs to be a lifestyle change."\n\nWe also agree with <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/journey-to-a-healthier-me">Jenny Grothe</a>, who wrote here a short while ago, "You can eat yummy foods. You don’t have to starve yourself. You can actually eat all day long, and as long as it is good, clean, substantial food, it will actually help you lose or maintain your weight."\n\nThe message that both these great women are sending is loud and clear: being lean and fit does NOT mean that you have to starve yourself to get there. On the contrary. Take a look at what actor and model <a href="http://www.facebook.com/stefan.pinto#!/album.php?aid=242829&amp;id=691474019" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Stefan Pinto</a> eats on a daily basis - some of these meals are HUGE! But they are wholesome and healthy. Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a>, eggs, tuna, garbanzo beans, raw nuts, cottage cheese, oats, Ezekiel bread, and lots and lots of veggies, to name a few of his food choices. \n\nSo what''s the secret of people like Stefan, Jenny and Christine? They eat real food, avoid processed foods and junk food, and fill their plates - and their tummies - with food that gives them endless energy and keeps them satiated for a long time after they have finished eating. It''s the exact opposite of eating foods that digest fast, causing wild blood sugar fluctuations and sending you into a spiral of uncontrollable cravings. \n\nChoosing to eat better does NOT mean being hungry. On the contrary - you will be fuller, more satiated, and more energized, than ever before. ', 'You Don''t Need to be Hungry!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'you-dont-need-to-be-hungry', '', '', '2011-03-16 05:00:08', '2011-03-16 12:00:08', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=680', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(687, 3, '2010-12-02 05:00:13', '2010-12-02 12:00:13', 'Dense, chewy and slightly sweet, this bread is perfect for breakfast or brunch, served with peanut butter, honey, jam or butter. It yields 12 thick slices. Each slice contains about 200 calories, 5 grams of protein and 3 grams of fiber.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup all purpose flour\n2 cups whole wheat flour\n½ cup packed brown sugar\n1 teaspoon salt\n1 teaspoon baking soda\n1 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt, plain low fat\n½ cup reduced fat (2%) milk\n½ cup honey\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 325°F.\n2. Sift the flour with the sugar and salt into a large bowl.\n3. Dissolve the baking soda in a mixture of the yogurt and milk, then add the honey and mix well.\n4. Add liquid ingredients to dry ingredients and stir until a dough is formed.\n4. Pour into a greased 9 x 5 inch loaf pan, leaving the dry crumbly bits in the bowl, and bake until the bread tests done, about 1 ½ hours, loosely covering with foil after the first hour.\n5. Allow to cool in pan for about 10 minutes, then transfer to a wire rack and allow to cool about 20 more minutes. Serve warm, or at room temperature.\n6. Slice and freeze any remaining leftovers. Toasted and buttered, this bread is absolutely delicious!', 'Greek Yogurt Health Bread', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-health-bread', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=687', 0, 'post', '', 6),
(692, 5, '2011-01-06 05:00:29', '2011-01-06 12:00:29', 'It''s a new year, so let''s start early with "A Voskos Greek Yogurt a Day", because not only is it easily digested, but also it just might keep the doctor away!\n\n"Start early" is one of my most important program tools, and since mounting scientific evidence supports yogurt''s health benefits, it makes perfect sense to start our day with one! Yogurt is a food that I eat every day, and in fact, it is how I start my day. \n\nHere are some of the reasons I love one of nature''s perfect foods.\n\n1. Low-fat yogurt Is a nutrient dense food, high in nutrients and low in calories (the non-fat and low-fat kind of course).\n2. Low-fat yogurt is one of the highest sources of bioavailable calcium (usually at least\n300mg) behind milk.\n3. Low-fat yogurt is high in quality protein (6 oz. serving gives us an equivalent to 1 oz. of steak). Voskos Greek yogurt actually gives us twice the amount of protein as other yogurts.\n4. Low-fat yogurt has phosphorus, which is important for our bones, and B12 (the B vitamin found only in animal products) most commonly known for its role in energy production.\n5. Low-fat yogurt has different bacterial cultures that enhance our absorption of nutrients and help maintain our own gut flora. The cultures that a yogurt contains do depend upon the brand, and even different brand yogurts that contain the same bacteria may contain a different strain of it, or a different blend of different bacteria. With Voskos Greek yogurt we get the major strains in the amount of cells that  scientific evidence supports having these beneficial health effects.\n\nYogurt is made by curdling milk with purified cultures of bacteria (the good kind that live in our gastrointestinal tract). In fact, many of us are not even aware that we have at least 500 different species of bacteria that live in our gut! The type and number of the good gut bacteria is directly related to our health. And because yogurt is cultured, many of us who have a lactose intolerance (problems digesting milk products) can enjoy the benefit of this milk product without the side effects.\n\n<strong>Now that it''s flu and cold season, the health promoting bacteria in yogurt can be particularly helpful during those times we need to take antibiotics (don''t take at the same time though), replenishing the good bugs in our gut.</strong> Yogurt itself is known as a probiotic (literally means " for life”), and probiotics are also referred to as "Living Drugs". Probiotics can also help our G.I. tract fight the bacteria that we ingest which would cause us to get sick (food poisoning for example, but will not prevent it). Some studies have also shown that yogurt is linked to an improved resistance to infection in general and other studies point to yogurt as having anti-cancer properties. Let''s not forget that enhanced absorption of nutrients can aid our immune system and health in general!\n\nWhat else can we ask for in a food? Good for our bones, good for our stomach, good for our immune system. Voskos Greek yogurt supplies double the protein, and it supplies an important vitamin necessary for energy and our nervous system. Lastly, it can be a convenient easy meal (we can buy it and carry it almost everywhere), and it is low in calories. Now in addition, research has been ongoing to establish a link between calcium, dairy foods and weight management. Here is a direct quote from one study (let''s remember, this is a quote from just one study and not conclusive!)\n\n"Dietary calcium appears to play a pivotal role in the regulation of energy metabolism and obesity risk. High calcium diets attenuate body fat accumulation and weight gain during periods of over-consumption of an energy-dense diet and to increase fat breakdown and preserve metabolism during caloric restriction, thereby markedly accelerating weight and fat loss".\n\nI have my Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a> everyday on the run. On weekends, I add my favorite cut fruit, or if I''m in the mood for something crunchy I eat the new YoGreek - <a href="http://www.yogreekyogurt.com/">Greek Yogurt with low fat granola</a> ready to pour in one cup! \n\nRecently I''ve started to eat what I call my "Blueberry Cheese Cake" breakfast made with blueberries, 1% fat cottage cheese or Ricotta, topped with my creamy Voskos Greek yogurt. I always feel so healthy after I''ve eaten my yogurt and I strongly believe all of us can benefit from starting our day with "A Yogurt a Day." It''s a great light meal an hour before a workout or a midmorning/afternoon snack too.\n\nSo, have we had our Voskos Greek yogurt today? Let''s Start Early to fuel our tank!\n<a href="www.junefit.com Some Active Live Cu" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">June M. Lay M.S.</a>', 'A Yogurt A Day Keeps The Doctor Away', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'yogurt-a-day', '', '', '2011-01-06 05:00:29', '2011-01-06 12:00:29', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=692', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(694, 3, '2010-11-26 05:00:55', '2010-11-26 12:00:55', 'It''s my favorite time of year - football season! Time for wings, chips and dips. But have you seen how many calories there are in those dips you''ve been eating? Instead, try something delicious AND healthy: Greek Yogurt Dip.  \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 clove garlic, minced\nDash of salt\n1/2 tsp dried mint leaves\n8oz container of Voskos Greek Yogurt, Plain\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nTransfer the yogurt into a bowl, add the other ingredients, mix well, and voila - you''ve got a great, healthy dip for those wings and chips! Enjoy!\n\n<object width="640" height="385"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/DjszvH6JM-A?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0&amp;color1=0x3a3a3a&amp;color2=0x999999"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/DjszvH6JM-A?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0&amp;color1=0x3a3a3a&amp;color2=0x999999" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="640" height="385"></embed></object>', 'VIDEO: Voskos Touch-Down Dip', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-dip', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=694', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(700, 9, '2011-01-07 05:00:06', '2011-01-07 12:00:06', 'When I first started competing in Figure, I completely underestimated how much time I''d spend in the kitchen. Having to eat every 2-3 hours (no less than 90 minutes and no more than 3 1/2 hours in between meals) it felt like I was always back in the kitchen cooking my next meal. What was fun at first became a chore.\n\nI’m all about sharing “best practices.” If you have a better way of doing something, I’ll be the first in line to know what you’re doing. Why reinvent the wheel?\n\nOne of the best practices I learned early on was to prepare as many of my foods at once. That might mean you find yourself in the kitchen for 3 hours at a time...but the payoff is without a doubt on the back end. What you plan, prep, cook, and store NOW you won''t have to plan, prep, cook and store LATER. It really is worth it.\n\nWhat works for me…\n\nI’ll set aside a couple of hours on Friday and schedule my menu for the upcoming week. I’ll break down recipes and categorize meats, veggies, fruits, dairy, snacks, jugs of water, everything. I want to have everything in my house for the upcoming week if possible. That way I don’t have to make mindless additional trips back to the store. \n\nSaturday morning I’ll hit Costco first. That’s where I know I’ll find the best pricing for things I go through quickly and need a lot of – oatmeal, flank, fish, chicken, eggs, romaine, spinach, etc. Then I’ll finish my shopping at my favorite grocery store. That’s where I’ll stock up on my favorite fruits, specialty items, almond milk, and Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a>. \n\nOne tip with the Greek Yogurt. I like to buy the individual serving cups. I hate nothing more than having to level out my yogurt in a measuring cup and then try transferring it over to a bowl. I can never get it all out, and I’m not one who likes to waste. Ask my closest friends. They will agree. Single-serving size cups make it easier. There’s still just enough room to add honey, agave, sweetener, berries, or my PB2 (peanut butter powder), so it works perfectly for my needs. Not to mention they are portable, and I can take them with me in my cooler if I’m going to be gone for any length of time. \n\nSunday is my day of preparation. That’s when I cut, dice, cube, bake (sweet potatoes), broil (flank) and grill (chicken) my meals. I store everything in individual sealed containers, so that they aren’t contaminated by the odors from the other foods. \n\nIf it’s a recipe that will keep, I’ll throw it together and store it. If not, I’ll prep the ingredients only, so that I can access them quickly when it’s time for a meal. \n\nThere is a balance though. Last year I tried to do too much at once. I''d prepare so much that by the time I got to the bottom of the container I had to throw it out or chance it being spoiled. \n\nSo this is what I would suggest. <strong>Prepare enough food to last you for about 3-4 days</strong>. Prepare your chicken plainly - nothing on it. That way when you need cooked chicken for a recipe (such as the healthy recipes I post on my Facebook Fan Page <a href="http://www.facebook.com/RecipesforGals" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Recipes for Gals in Figure and Bodybuilding</a> and on the <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/">Voskos Recipe Blog</a>) you''ll be able to add the spices, sauces, and marinades needed at that moment. I do this ALL the time. Works great. I prepare my veggies and flank the same way. \n\nIF I use seasoning when I prep foods in advance, I''ll lightly dust it with any one of my plethora of Mrs. Dash spices (sodium and MSG free).\n\nWhen I started my weight-loss journey three years ago, so many people in my neighborhood asked me how I did it. I''m thinking of one neighbor in particular who would say, "Jenny, some day I just need to come over to your house and see what you have in your fridge." It''s so funny now thinking back on her comment. What’s even funnier is she did come over and investigate my fridge. For her it wasn''t a matter of "hearing" it; she needed to "see" it. She wanted to see what I ate, how I cooked it, and how I stored it. \n\n<strong>If you’d like to know more about how I prep my food, just ask</strong>. It''s basic, but I know when I first started eating clean I didn’t have a clue where to start. There was such a steep learning curve. I''m happy to share my “best practices” with you. Don’t be a stranger. Ask. \n\nJust like on my Facebook Fan Page, I’m your GALfriend. I want to be someone you can feel comfortable asking anything of. We’re all in this together.\n\nHappy food prepping and clean eating!', 'How I Pack My Fridge', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-i-pack-my-fridge', '', '', '2011-01-07 05:00:06', '2011-01-07 12:00:06', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=700', 0, 'post', '', 12),
(705, 9, '2011-02-03 05:00:57', '2011-02-03 12:00:57', 'In college I hated running. I’d skip my fitness class when we had to run the mile. I couldn’t run a mile without being completely out of breath. Now I’m running 26.2 of them. \n\nNot to mention I’m preparing for one of the most prestigious marathons – the Boston Marathon. \n\nAs I’ve mentioned before, I like to <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/diet-and-nutrition/why-i-choose-to-eat-clean">eat clean</a>. I strive to eat clean at least 95% of the time. I’m all about moderation and indulgences though. I look forward to date nights, and if I’m tempted with one of my favorite desserts – I will most likely partake. \n\nBut for the most part I like to eat clean. \n\nThere’s so much more to it though. It’s not just a matter of eating clean anymore. It’s a matter of fueling my body the best I can for whatever event I’m prepping for. \n\nI love to run, and I love to compete in figure competitions (a slighter form of bodybuilding). The dietary needs for each couldn’t be more different. \n\nWhen I am trying to add muscle, my caloric, carb, and protein intake goes up. Actually, everything does – even fats. When I am within the 12-week contest prep window and trying to lean out, everything except for protein drastically goes down. It’s a matter of fine-tuning and adjusting those numbers to give me the results I want. It’s like an equation. Small little tweaks result in predictable changes.\n\nWith running, it’s so different. I might have a moderate amount of carbs nine months out of the year, but when I am prepping for a marathon, my body requires more carbs. It craves them. It’s hard to explain, but I feel a physical hunger for carbs when I’m running long distances – not just before but during and after as well. So I’ll increase my carb intake within that three month window by another 50%. \n\nSome do more. I’ve read that some recommend having one protein to every seven carbs when training for a marathon. For me that’s not realistic. I’d either need to have next to no protein (which simply is not going to happen), or my carb count would be through the roof. Instead, since I like to maintain as much lean muscle as I can, I keep my protein intake high, and I increase my carbs from moderate to moderately “higher”. \n\nWhat do I eat? \n\nI focus on eating more of the same. Nothing special. I eat what my body craves and is used to eating. Some people make the mistake of introducing new foods, and oftentimes that backfires. Their bodies aren’t used to the new foods and reject them – sometimes during their training runs – and believe me, that’s not a pleasant experience.\n\nSo I stick to what my body likes – what it''s used to. When I increase carbs I tend to eat more sweet potatoes, oatmeal, brown rice, and other complex carbs. I’ll even occasionally include white rice and russet potatoes. Carbs are a runner’s best friend. They give me the added energy I need for those brutal 16, 18, and 20 mile runs. \n\n<strong>Protein is equally as important though. Not only does protein help maintain your lean muscle, it also helps transport the carbs (your energy and fuel source) throughout your system. </strong>\n\nSo the next couple of months carbs will be crucial for my training. As my runs become more frequent and longer, I can guarantee you I’ll be adding in more healthy carb-loaded snacks between my regular meals. \n\nBut I won’t be skimping on my protein. One of my goals is to add to the muscle I already have, and I’ll be darned if I am going to run it all off. Thankfully there are easy treats like VOSKOS Greek yogurt to help make it easier. \n\nRun on!', 'My Diet While Training for the Boston Marathon ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'diet-training-for-the-boston-marathon', '', '', '2011-02-03 05:00:57', '2011-02-03 12:00:57', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=705', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(709, 3, '2011-01-18 09:22:24', '2011-01-18 16:22:24', '<strong>VOSKOS'' 2X PROTEIN GREEK YOGURT IS NOW AVAILABLE AT PUBLIX STORES</strong>\nVoskos Debuts at the 2011 Publix A1A Ft. Lauderdale Marathon To Promote Good Health and Good Diets \n\nSun Valley, CA, January 18, 2011 - Sun Valley Dairy, makers of award-winning Voskos Greek Yogurt, famous for its higher protein content ounce per ounce over other Greek yogurt brands expands it distribution, adding Publix as a new retailer partner this February.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt will roll out in over 1,000 <a href="http://publix.com/">Publix</a> grocery stores located in Florida and Georgia with five unique non-fat flavors including Greek Honey; Exotic Fig; Honey-Vanilla Bean; Wild Blueberry; and Wild Strawberry.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt debuts the partnership with an aggressive campaign, sponsoring the <a href="http://www.a1amarathon.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Publix Fort Lauderdale A1A Marathon</a> to introduce the cleaner and healthier Greek yogurt to more than 40,000 health and fitness-oriented consumers this February 20, 2011. Additionally, consumers can try Voskos Greek Yogurt via in-store demos, get coupons dispensed from Smart Source coupon machines, in-store coupon pads and in local Sunday papers.\n\nAs the first ever <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a> brand produced and distributed in the US, Voskos continues its pioneering and leadership position, leveraging a dynamic online and social media platform and partnering with CouponsInc, the world’s largest online coupon distributor, to offer digital Voskos coupon programs to shoppers on Publix.com, <a href="http://www.coupons.com/couponweb/Offers.aspx?pid=13306&zid=iq37&nid=10&bid=alk0118080143bb474f72f23214" rel="nofollow">Coupons.com</a>, Voskos.com, and the Voskos facebook fan page.\n\n“We believe in a strong and dynamic retailer support of our partners and their customers and are excited to be a part of local events and online communities that promote good health and good diets. Educating consumers on understanding the benefits of Greek yogurt is key, as anyone who tries Voskos Greek Yogurt quickly falls in love with its thick and rich taste while benefiting from the live and active probiotics that boost the digestive and immune system,” states Vanessa Nielsen, director of marketing. “Consumers agree, and it’s also great validation when national health editors name Voskos the #1 Greek yogurt for taste and nutrition in foodie contests,” adds Nielsen.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt is winner of Fitness, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, and Cooking Light magazine contests. It is also a triple gold winner of the LA International Dairy Competition this past summer.\n\n“Publix is a popular retailer coveted for its superior service and quality offerings and we’re excited to partner with this chain. Quality is our number one product and with Voskos being all-natural and gluten-free, Publix’s decision to introduce Voskos Greek Yogurt in the new year to encourage healthy diets shows their dedication to bringing new and innovative products to their health-conscious community,” says Rick Hoefner, national sales manager for Voskos Greek Yogurt.\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt</strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, and gluten-free and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields 2x more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos is the only brand to offer an organic Greek yogurt line in addition to its all-natural plain and blended flavors and never has “fruit on the bottom”. Available nationwide. Now available at Publix stores. Retails for $1.59 for 5.3 oz varieties. For store locations, healthy Greek yogurt and to download a coupon, visit voskos.com today. ', 'Voskos Now Available at Publix ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-now-available-at-publix', '', '', '2011-01-18 09:22:24', '2011-01-18 16:22:24', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=709', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(713, 3, '2010-12-08 14:28:21', '2010-12-08 21:28:21', 'This fabulous recipe is from <a href="http://anacheyer.blogspot.com/2010/11/my-big-greek-french-toast.html" target="_blank">Fit, Fun and Delish</a> - a wonderful blog dedicated to a healthy lifestyle. Thank you Ana!\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 slices of apple cinnamon bread \n1 egg\nCooking spray\n8 oz Voskos Greek Yogurt (24 grams of protein per serving!)\nCinnamon\n1 packet of Stevia or your favorite sweetener\n1/2 banana\n1/2 tbsp chia seeds\n3 tbsp of sugar free maple syrup\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Heat griddle or pan to medium high heat and spray with PAM. Scramble egg and dip bread into batter coating both sides. Place on griddle and cook each side until golden brown. \n2. While the bread is toasting, mix the yogurt with cinnamon to taste and the packet of stevia.\n3. Arrange a slice of toast, add some yogurt, chia seeds & banana slices. Add the other slice and repeat the layers. Add the syrup and Kalí óreksi! (that''s Bon Appetit in Greek :)\n\n405 Calories, 8g fat, 54g carbs, 8g fiber & 40g protein.', 'A Big Greek French Toast!', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-big-greek-french-toast', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=713', 0, 'post', '', 3),
(723, 3, '2011-01-20 13:51:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'We were deeply touched by this email we''ve received from a Voskos fan:\n\n"You were the first Greek yogurt I tried. I thought all would taste the same, but boy was I wrong. I now demand my yogurt to be Voskos only! I eat at least one every day since December, and have lost 15 lbs. so far! \n\n<strong>I''m a college student and I was pretty heavy set at 5 feet tall and 220 pounds, but now I weigh about 205 lbs. and still losing. The only change I''ve made to my diet was adding Voskos! </strong>If I didn’t have time for breakfast, I would eat some Voskos to get my metabolism going in the morning. In the past, I would usually eat nothing until noon. That way, once I would come back from my morning class, I wouldn''t want to chow down like I normally would if I hadn''t eaten anything. \n\nI also eat Voskos between lunch and dinner, so when dinnertime comes, the hunger monster is not there and I can feel satisfied with eating a regular sized meal.\n\nThe only thing that sucks is the fact that I can''t find you on campus! The only thing they sell with lots of protein are protein bars but they contain only 4 g of protein and a gazillion calories, while your  products contain 4 times the protein and 1/3 of the calories."\n\n--\nSuch an inspiring story, and we absolutely love that the only change she has made was eating Voskos twice a day, for breakfast and as an afternoon snack. \n\n<strong>We would love to hear similar stories from other Voskos enthusiasts! We are happy to offer each of our fans that makes a "How I''m Losing Weight with Voskos" video and posts it on Youtube the following prize</strong>: A three-month supply of Voskos, in the form of coupons, a Voskos tee, a Voskos travel mug, a reusable tote, and a baseball cap. Post the links to the videos here in the comments section, or on our <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt">Facebook Wall</a>. \n', 'Lose Weight with Voskos and WIN a 3-Month Supply!', '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', 'lose-weight-voskos', '', '', '2011-01-20 13:51:35', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=723', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(735, 3, '2011-01-03 05:00:35', '2011-01-03 12:00:35', 'Recipe adapted from a recipe by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.jen-fit.com/" target="_blank">Jenny Grothe</a>.\nMakes 9 pancakes\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 egg\n1/2 tablespoon olive oil\n1 ripe banana, mashed\n1 cup (a 8oz container) Voskos nonfat plain Greek yogurt\n1 tablespoon honey\n1 cup all purpose flour\n2 teaspoons baking powder\n1/2 teaspoon baking soda\n1/4 teaspoon cinnamon\nDash salt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1.Combine eggs, oil, banana, yogurt and honey in a bowl and mix well using a hand whisk.\n\n2.Whisk together flour, baking powder, baking soda, cinnamon, and salt.\n\n3. Add yogurt mixture to dry ingredients and stir just until combined, allowing batter to remain lumpy.\n\n4.Heat 2 12-inch skillets over medium heat for about 4 minutes. Coat with cooking spray. Cook 4-5 pancakes on each skillet, about 4 minutes on the first side (or until golden brown) and then about 2 more minutes on the second side.\n\n5. The result is yummy, fluffy pancakes with a hint of sweetness, banana and cinnamon. If you''re in the mood to indulge, serve them with a little maple syrup, but they are excellent just as they are with no toppings at all. And healthier than regular pancakes!\n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Banana-Pancakes-2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-740" title="Banana Pancakes 2" src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Banana-Pancakes-2.jpg" alt="banana pancakes" width="589" height="350" /></a>\n\n<strong>Nutrition per Pancake</strong>\nCalories 103\nTotal Fat 2 g\nSaturated Fat 0.7 g\nCholesterol 22 mg\nSodium 212 mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 17 g\nDietary Fiber 0.7 g\nSugars 	4.6 g\nProtein 5 g ', 'Greek Yogurt Banana Pancakes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-banana-pancakes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=735', 0, 'post', '', 9),
(746, 3, '2011-02-01 05:00:58', '2011-02-01 12:00:58', 'Recipe by <a href="http://www.jen-fit.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>. \nServings: 12\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 can rinsed and drained garbanzo beans\n1/3 cup fat-free Voskos Greek yogurt\n1/4 cup chopped onion\n1 cup chopped cucumber\n1/4 cup Tahini paste/sauce\n1 tbs lemon juice\n4 cloves minced garlic\n1/4 tsp smoked paprika\nSalt and pepper to taste\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nCombine all ingredients in a blender. Pour into bowl. Sprinkle with additional smoked paprika. Chill until served.\n\n<strong>Nutrition per serving</strong>\nCalories 47\nCalories from Fat 15.0\nTotal Fat 1.67g 2% \nSodium 169.08mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 7.17g\nDietary Fiber 1.78g\nSugars 1g  \nProtein 3.31g', 'Smoked Cucumber Hummus', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'smoked-cucumber-hummus', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=746', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(751, 3, '2011-03-01 05:00:40', '2011-03-01 12:00:40', 'Recipe by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.jen-fit.com/" target="_blank">Jenny Grothe</a>.\nMakes 4 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 cups romaine lettuce, shredded\n1 cup cooked and chopped chicken breast\n1/4 cup VOSKOS nonfat Greek Yogurt\n1/3 diced cucumber\n1/4 chopped red onion\n1/4 cup fat-free feta cheese\n2 tbs freshly squeezed lemon\n1/4 tsp sea salt\n1/4 tsp freshly ground black pepper\n2 tbs chopped kalamata olives\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a small bowl mix yogurt, lemon, salt, pepper, and cheese.\n2. Stir in cucumber, onion, olives, and chicken. Toss with lettuce.\n3. Stuff in Pitas, on Ezekiel or Whole Wheat Bread, or eat alone.\n\n<strong>Nutrition per serving (for salad only)</strong>\nCalories 96\nCalories from Fat 9.4\nTotal Fat 1.04g 1%\nSodium 316.19mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 3.73g\nDietary Fiber 0.84g\nSugars 1.15g\nProtein 18.88g', 'Greek Chicken Salad ', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-chicken-salad', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=751', 0, 'post', '', 4);
