(772, 10, '2011-02-07 11:41:19', '2011-02-07 18:41:19', 'In today’s society where the average person is moving at a faster pace, texting with one hand, a laptop in another and one eye on the road. Sound like you? Many people today will admit they don’t eat right and will always grab junk food or choose the convenient drive thru. What we do is fuel our bodies with unnecessary carbohydrates and fats. We may be moving faster through our day, but our body is getting heavier, our energy is getting lower and simple sugars and caffeine are not the cure. \n\nNow grab a spoon. Yogurt is what I call my go-to-food. My colleagues and friends tell me I never stop working or moving and I have to admit, it’s true, but good health is always a top priority for me. When I’m in the film studio or on location, I bring yogurt with me, but not just any yogurt. One day I came across a yogurt called Voskos Non-fat Greek Yogurt. The non-fat caught my attention, but I’m also a label reader. What I saw was over 20 grams of protein, non-fat and hardly any sugar (naturally occurring of course or from the healthy fruit inside). This appealed to me because I have a problem of going too long without eating and that doesn’t work very well when you have low blood sugar from time to time. \n\nA cup of yogurt may not seem as filling as a cheeseburger or a large salad, but it packs more nutrition your body needs in today’s modern world. Greek Yogurt is like dynamite, it maybe small but it packs a healthier punch! You need protein to improve your immune function, normalize your blood sugar, needed for repair and maintenance of muscle and when we do that, we have a better chance of losing weight too. Protein enhances your brain function, it’s made up of 22 amino acids as some of them will be converted into brain neurotransmitters, which keep your brain sharp and helps you avoid that tired afternoon feeling. \n\nAnother aspect of eating a cup of yogurt every day is your body’s intestinal tract has to be healthy enough to fight off all the bacteria we come in contact with on a daily basis. When your gastrointestinal tract is healthy, the rest of your body is healthy! Probiotic bacteria, the friendly bacteria are destroyed by birth control pills, antibiotics and secondhand antibiotics found in our food supply. Are you getting the picture? Your life may seem like a circus, but for your body to keep up with your daily schedule, give it the best you can and that begins with a healthy cup of yogurt. Again, my only choice is Voskos Greek Yogurt. \n\nWhat more could you ask for? You demand to be the best during your work day, isn’t it time to demand the best for your body? ', 'Feeding Your Body When Your Life is a Juggling Act', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'feeding-your-body-when-your-life-is-a-juggling-act', '', '', '2011-02-07 11:41:19', '2011-02-07 18:41:19', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=772', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(776, 3, '2010-12-30 05:00:11', '2010-12-30 12:00:11', 'Recipe by <a href="http://www.jen-fit.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>. \nMakes 2 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1/4 cup VOSKOS nonfat Greek Yogurt\n4 egg whites\nFreshly ground sea salt\nFreshly ground pepper\n1 slice Ezekiel 4:9 bread\n2 whole eggs\n1 reduced fat slice provolone cheese\n6 slices (50g) deli turkey ham\ncooking spray\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Whisk together 4 egg whites, freshly ground sea salt to taste, freshly ground pepper to taste, 1/8 tsp vindaloo seasoning, and 1/4 cup VOSKOS nonfat Greek Yogurt. Set aside.\n2. Spray two (2-cup) ramekin bowls with cooking spray. Cut one piece of Ezekiel bread in half. Place one half of bread in each ramekin. Pour egg mixture over bread. Layer meat on top of bread (evenly). Break remaining two eggs into each bowl. Cut provolone slice in half and place on top for eggs. Sprinkle with sea salt and pepper if desired.\n3. Fill a 9x13 casserole dish with 2" of water. Place ramekins in water bath and bake in a 375 oven for 15-20 minutes or until eggs are cooked through and firm to touch. Enjoy!\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 216\nTotal Fat 7.57g\nSaturated Fat 2.75g\nCholesterol 239.52mg\nSodium 593.63mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 9.63g\nDietary Fiber 1.5g\nSugars 1g\nProtein 25.03g', 'Baked Eggs with Ham', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'baked-eggs-with-ham', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=776', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(781, 4, '2011-02-15 05:00:54', '2011-02-15 12:00:54', 'It has been over a month since you’re made those New Year''s Resolutions-maybe they were the same as the last several years-it is time to move onward and upward-time to take yourself and your health seriously.  \n\nYou know that the extra weight can lead to health issues-type 2 diabetes is one of those health issues.  The excess weight is the root of many disease states.\n\n<strong>I am not a fan of setting poundage loss goals or rigid meal plans</strong>.  I am all about moving more and eating better but also knowing what foods trigger your loss of control and what food types satisfy.  When you can identify if what you’re doing is either sabotaging or supporting your efforts, it will be easier to meet your goals or you’ll be able to set new resolutions next year.\n\nWhen you are successful at meeting your weight loss or improved health goals, it can have an impact on lowering glucose levels to giving you more energy or improving relationships.  What are you waiting for?  This is your year to make the changes necessary to improve your health and quality of life-don’t let anything hold you back. \n\nYou realize that the extra weight you carry did not happen overnight so we can’t expect it to go away overnight.  Set small-reachable goals-learn from the mistakes/set-backs and keep moving forward.  Even a modest weight loss of 5-7 percent, shows a marked improvement in blood glucose and your confidence.\n\nBe patient-determine your readiness to change.  Even if you don’t lose weight, preventing further weight gain is a plus.  If you have set-backs, treat them as a small slip-don’t let that small slip destroy what you’ve already accomplished.  Seek help from a health professional-someone who can assist you to meet your goals-make this the first time you succeed and the last time you set this goal.\n', 'How Are Those Resolutions Treating You Now?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-year-resolutions', '', '', '2011-02-15 05:00:54', '2011-02-15 12:00:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=781', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(783, 3, '2011-01-06 05:00:40', '2011-01-06 12:00:40', 'Recipe by <a href="http://www.jen-fit.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>. \nMakes 4 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n4 cups thinly sliced red cabbage\n1/4 cup unsweetened dried cranberries\n1/4 cup lite rice vinegar\n3 tbs agave nectar\n1 tbs white wine vinegar\n1/4 cup nonfat VOSKOS Greek yogurt\n1/4 tsp freshly ground black pepper\n1 cup diced apple\n3 tbs chopped pecans, toasted\n9 oz shredded or cubed cooked chicken\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nCube cooked chicken and slice red cabbage. Toss chicken, cabbage, apples, and cranberries in a medium-sized bowl. Mix remaining ingredients (excluding pecans). Coat chicken mixture with dressing. Chill until served. Before serving add toasted chopped pecans.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 237\nTotal Fat 4.97g\nCholesterol 34.69mg\nSodium 521.5mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 33.35g\nDietary Fiber 5.17g\nSugars 25.68g\nProtein 16.56g\n', 'Cranberry Red Cabbage Chicken Salad', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'cranberry-red-cabbage-chicken-salad', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=783', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(790, 9, '2011-02-22 05:00:08', '2011-02-22 12:00:08', 'Two months from now I’ll be running another 26.2 miles. I’ll be surrounded by nearly 500,000 onlookers. There will be crowds for miles, rolling hills, incredible scenery, extreme cold temperatures from the start, and moderately high temperatures toward the end. \n\nBoston. I’m right in the thick of training for my first Boston marathon. Me! It wasn’t even a year ago I was training for the Top of Utah marathon. I felt one marathon a year was plenty. For me it takes a lot of training mentally and physically to prepare for running a race of that distance. By the end of training I’m more than ready to be done with training and with running all together…at least for a while.\n\nBut last Fall when I ran Top of Utah, I had not one goal but two…to finish the race with a respectable time and if at all possible to qualify for Boston. Which I did. So here I am. Training again. Not even six months later.\n\nWhen people talk about training for endurance programs, most people emphasize the importance of getting miles in and increasing carb intake. While both are extremely important, <strong>one very important resource is often overlooked. Protein. </strong>\n\nI have found through my own mistakes that my body requires a well-rounded meal prior to hitting the roads. Slow digesting carbs help sustain my energy for longer periods of time. Simple sugars from fruits give me the quick energy I need right away, but it’s the protein that feeds my muscles, feeds my body, and gives me the ongoing strength that I need for my runs. Protein is just a much a factor as anything else. Unfortunately it’s often overlooked.\n\nAnd that goes not only before a race but in my weeks of training leading up to it. It’s a well-known fact that excessive running burns off muscle. As a weight-trainer, that is something I’m trying desperately to avoid. I’m hoping to sustain as much muscle as I possibly can. Muscle also helps you power through your harder runs. Strong quads, calves, and hamstrings help you muscle up hills. A strong core and quads helps you absorb the pounding when you are running freely down hills. Muscle is key and in my opinion under appreciated in running. \n\n<strong>So before every run, without fail, I included some form of protein in my meal. </strong> Since most of my runs occur before the sun even rises, not all foods sound equally as good. I remember having a trainer that required I have chicken and a veggie as my first meal of the day. At 6 a.m. chicken doesn’t sound appealing – at least not to me. \n\nNot to mention not all foods have the same effect on my stomach. Some “sit” better than others. You’ll discover fairly quickly if a food “sits” right with you or not during a long run. I don’t think I need to explain further. :)\n\n<strong>For me, my favorite pre-run meal is old-fashioned oats, berries, and <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a>. I never grow tired of it. I’ve never had a problem with my stomach being unsettled as a result, and I know I have all the bases covered with this simple yet complete meal. </strong>\n\nRunning is hard enough even with a full stomach and energy to spare. I can’t imagine running on empty. Training for any race is key. Proper fueling is essential. ', 'Proper Fueling ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'proper-fueling', '', '', '2011-02-22 05:00:08', '2011-02-22 12:00:08', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=790', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(792, 3, '2011-01-11 05:00:36', '2011-01-11 12:00:36', 'Recipe by <a href="http://www.jen-fit.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>\nMakes 5 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n5 slices lean turkey bacon\n¼ cup VOSKOS nonfat Greek yogurt\n4 whole eggs\n4 egg whites\nFreshly ground pepper\n1 tsp Mrs. Dash Tomato Basil Garlic seasoning blend\n5 tsp low-fat ricotta cheese\n1 roma tomato, thinly sliced\n¾ cup (approximately) baby spinach leaves\n5 pieces Sara Lee 100% whole wheat bread (45 cal each)\n4 additional tbs VOSKOS nonfat Greek yogurt\n \n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Cook bacon in preheated pan until nearly done. Set aside. \n2. Using a round cookie cutter, cut 5 circles out of bread. \n3. Coat muffin pan with cooking spray. Lay cut out bread circle in 5 muffin tins. \n4. Wrap bacon around outside of each muffin tins. \n5. Combine eggs, seasonings, and 1/4 cup of Greek yogurt. \n6. Layer each muffin tin with the following: 1 tsp ricotta cheese, small handful baby spinach leaves, and 1 slice roma tomato. \n7. Divide egg mixture evenly among all 5 cups. \n8. Bake in a preheated 350 degree oven for 20-25 minutes or until eggs are firm to touch. \n9. Serve with fresh sliced tomato and a dollop of VOSKOS Greek yogurt.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 149\nTotal Fat 4.88g\nCholesterol 185.17mg\nSodium 326.29mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 9.18g\nDietary Fiber 0.97g\nSugars 2.55g\nProtein 15.95g\n', 'Baked Egg and Bacon Muffins', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'baked-egg-and-bacon-muffins', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=792', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(798, 3, '2011-01-13 05:00:57', '2011-01-13 12:00:57', 'Recipe by <a href="http://www.jen-fit.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>\nMakes 8 slices\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n8 slices lean turkey bacon\n4 whole eggs\n4 egg whites\n1 tsp McCormick Italian Seasoning \n1/4 cup nonfat Voskos Greek Yogurt\n1/3 cup thinly sliced yellow onion\n3 small russet potatoes\n1/2 tsp ground sea salt\n1/4 tsp ground black pepper\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Prick and microwave potatoes for 5 minutes or until done.\n2. Cook bacon in large pan until crispy. Once removed blot bacon with paper towels to remove excess grease.\n3. Grill onions in bacon grease until browned. Peel potatoes, slice, and add to pan with onions.\n4. Cut turkey bacon into thin slices and add to pan.\n5. Whisk remaining ingredients in a bowl. Pour over turkey, potatoes, and onions. Reduce heat to medium-low and cover. Let set for up to 10 minutes.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 107\nTotal Fat 2.75g\nSaturated Fat 0.75g\nCholesterol 117.97mg\nSodium 310.52mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 11.11g\nDietary Fiber 1.25g\nSugars 1.75g \nProtein 10.33g\n', 'Greek Yogurt Breakfast Quiche', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'breakfast-quiche', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=798', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(800, 10, '2011-02-23 05:00:05', '2011-02-23 12:00:05', 'How many of you have been fighting hunger in the evening? \n\nI bet most of you are sitting in front of the television or possibly your computer. Many of us lead a fast paced life during the day and we either don’t take time to eat or we just keep going because the hunger pangs haven’t alerted us to eat. During day we need energy, but we need fuel for that energy. If we don’t eat, we set ourselves up to overeat in the evening, the worst time for a big meal or unhealthy snack. Ever wonder why you gain weight and you tell yourself, ‘I don’t eat that much during the day, why am I getting fat?’\n\nEvenings are for winding down and preparing for rest. <strong>One of my worst past habits is not eating all day and then coming home and eating dinner, then sitting in front of the television and snacking until it was time for bed.</strong> Do that for awhile and you’ll see 30lbs of weight appear very shortly. After my middle widened too much and I started feeling slow and sluggish, it was time to do something about it. \n\nDuring the day, I focus on fruit. Eating fruit, not drinking it. Take an apple, high fiber, high energy food that will help improve your metabolism. I eat at least 2 apples a day, one at mid-morning and one at mid-afternoon. This helps control blood sugar. At lunch, for those who are fast paced, a cup of Voskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a> will feed your body high-quality, usable protein. I use the non-fat as I like to keep my weight down. I do use the other forms of Voskos for various reasons, but that’s for another article. \n\nThe Voskos Greek Yogurt will fill you up without slowing you down. The fruit varieties of Voskos are great as well. A fruit is a complex carbohydrate which will give you more energy and antioxidants. Kill two birds with one stone and improve your health! It doesn’t get any better than that!\n\nIn the evening, I have a trick. I like to eat my dinner around 5-6pm, not after 7pm if I can help it. You need at least three hours from your last meal before you decide to go to bed. When you make wise, healthy choices, you won’t gain weight and you’ll be satisfied. \n\n<strong>So what do you do if you want to snack? I use a few different ways to kill the munchies and not grab a bag of chips or cookies. </strong>\n\nExample Number 1: A bowl of berries. Blueberries, Strawberries and Raspberries make a great snack. Sprinkle some xylitol sweetener on top and eat. Xylitol is a natural sweetener safe for diabetics and reduces cravings for sweets over time. \n\nExample Number 2: A cup of Voskos Non Fat Greek Yogurt with or without fruit. A secret I learned from bodybuilders. High-quality protein will improve metabolism while you sleep. If you suffer low blood sugar or exercise in the evening, this is the perfect solution. \n\nExample Number 3: Make a smoothie using Voskos Greek Yogurt. I take 8oz of water with half a cup of Voskos and blend in frozen berries. Berries are low in sugar, high in antioxidants! Blueberries control blood sugar. A smoothie makes a great breakfast, dessert or post-workout recovery drink. \n\nFuel your body the right way!\n\n<a href="www.drwardbond.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Ward W. Bond, Ph.D.</a>\n\n', 'Eat Right and Fight the Munchies at Night', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'munchies-at-night', '', '', '2011-02-23 05:00:05', '2011-02-23 12:00:05', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=800', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(808, 3, '2011-01-18 05:00:18', '2011-01-18 12:00:18', 'Recipe by <a href="http://jen-fit-training.blogspot.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>. Makes 6 patties. \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 (7 oz.) cans Kirkland salmon\n2 tbs VOSKOS nonfat Greek Yogurt\n¼ cup liquid egg whites\n1/8 tsp dill weed\n¼ tsp crushed garlic\n¼ cup chopped celery\n¼ cup chopped onion\n3 tbs dry oats\n1 tsp Worcestershire Sauce\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nCombine everything in a bowl. Coat pan with cooking spray and cook over medium heat 3-4 minutes each side until browned. \n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 131\nTotal Fat 4.09g\nCholesterol 11.98mg\nSodium 214.36mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 5.57g\nDietary Fiber 0.84g\nSugars 0.76g \nProtein 16.4g', 'Salmon Patties', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'salmon-patties', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=808', 0, 'post', '', 1),
