(814, 3, '2011-01-20 05:00:26', '2011-01-20 12:00:26', 'Recipe courtesy of <a href="http://anacheyer.blogspot.com/2011/01/wheat-crepes-filled-with-greek-yogurt.html" target="_blank">Fit, Fun and Delish</a>. Recipe makes 7 crepes.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n3/4 cups whole wheat flour\n2 packets Stevia\n1/4 teaspoon baking soda\n1/4 teaspoon salt\n1 cup almond milk\n1 egg\n1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract\nButter-flavored cooking spray\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Mix dry ingredients in large bowl.\n2. Stir in wet ingredients and mix until smooth.\n3. Preheat pan on medium heat on stove.\n4. For each crepe, lightly spray pan and pour 1/4 cup of batter into pan. Rotate pan so that crepe is thin and even. Flip once crepe is golden brown and cook other side until golden brown. About a minute for each side.\n5. Mix Voskos Non Fat Greek Yogurt with cinnamon and a packet of no-calorie sweetener.  Add any kind of fruit you want: blueberries, bananas, strawberries, etc.\n6. Fill crepes with yogurt and fold.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nFor one crepe:\nCalories 114\nFat 1.5 grams\nCholesterol 35mg\nSodium 145mg\nCarbs 15.8 grams\nFiber 2.4 grams\nProtein 9.7 grams\nSugars 4.8 grams', 'Whole Wheat Crepes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-whole-wheat-crepes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=814', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(820, 3, '2011-03-17 11:38:47', '2011-03-17 18:38:47', 'Press Media Wire (Press Release) - Feb 25,2011 - A recent <a href="http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/33/12/2552.abstract?sid=6e7b0fe4-6374-4886-95f8-2c7b57fc1a50">study</a> published in Diabetes Care, the journal of the American Diabetes Association, reveals that a high-protein pre-breakfast yogurt snack helps reduce after-breakfast blood sugar elevation in the Type 2 diabetics studied by up to 40%.\n\n"The beauty of Voskos Plain Greek Yogurt is that it''s naturally high in protein and lower in carbohydrates, similar to the snack used in the study," says Vanessa Nielsen, Marketing Director of Sun Valley Dairy, makers of Voskos Greek Yogurt. A 150-gram (5.3 ounce) serving of Plain Nonfat Organic Voskos Greek Yogurt contains 15 grams of protein, and only 7 grams of carbohydrates.\n\nStudy participants ate a high-protein yogurt snack approximately two hours before breakfast. The study builds on previous studies that have shown a substantial reduction in elevated blood sugar levels after the second meal of the day, provided that breakfast had been eaten.\n\n"This is just the latest scientific study that helps to demonstrate the health benefits of a diet that includes Greek yogurt," adds Nielsen. "The active probiotic cultures in Voskos Greek Yogurt may help those with certain gastrointestinal complaints such as lactose intolerance, colon cancer, inflammatory bowel disease, diarrhea and constipation, according to some studies."\n\n"But of course, the best thing about Voskos Greek Yogurt is that it''s delicious. And substituting Plain Voskos Greek Yogurt for mayonnaise or sour cream is a simple way to boost protein in almost any recipe," says Nielsen.\n\nVoskos Plain Non-Fat and Low-Fat Greek Yogurt is made with just two ingredients: milk and live yogurt cultures. Voskos Plain Greek Yogurt does not contain any added sugars or sweeteners, making it a healthful option for the diabetic lifestyle.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, and Cooking Light magazine. It is also a triple gold winner of the 2010 Los Angeles International Dairy Competition.\n\nAbout Voskos Greek Yogurt\n\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, and gluten-free and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos is the only brand to offer an organic Greek yogurt line in addition to its all-natural plain and blended flavors and never has “fruit on the bottom.” Available nationwide in such stores as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts. For store locations, and to download a coupon, visit voskos.com today. ', 'High Protein Yogurt and Diabetes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'type-2-diabetes-protein', '', '', '2011-03-17 11:38:47', '2011-03-17 18:38:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=820', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(824, 3, '2011-02-09 05:00:21', '2011-02-09 12:00:21', 'Recipe by <a href="http://jen-fit-training.blogspot.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>. Makes 1 serving.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup VOSKOS nonfat Greek Yogurt\n1 tbs PB2 powder\n3 large strawberries (100g)\n1 stevia packet\n1/2 tsp vanilla sugar-free fat-free pudding mix (to thicken)\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nMash strawberries. Add other ingredients and mix well. Let set for a couple of minutes before serving. Enjoy!\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 202\nTotal Fat 0.75g\nCholesterol 15.01mg\nSodium 226.1mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 20.92g\nDietary Fiber 4.08g\nSugars 13.36g\nProtein 27.19g\n', 'PB&J Greek Yogurt', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'pbj-greek-yogurt', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=824', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(829, 3, '2011-02-16 05:00:52', '2011-02-16 12:00:52', 'Recipe by <a href="http://jen-fit-training.blogspot.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>. \nMakes 6 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n¾ cup VOSKOS nonfat <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a>\n1 can (15 oz.) 50% less sodium white beans (thoroughly rinsed and drained)\n1 can (15 oz.) black beans (thoroughly rinsed and drained)\n1 small can (4 oz.) diced green chilis\n1 can (15 oz.) diced tomatoes\n1 cup reduced-sodium chicken broth\n1 cup frozen or fresh corn\n1 ½ lbs shredded cooked chicken breast\n2 tbs lime juice\n1 minced clove\n½ tsp onion powder\n1 tsp dried oregano\n½ tsp smoked paprika\n1 tsp chili powder\n1 tsp cumin\n1 tbs dried cilantro\n2 tsp Mrs. Dash Fiesta Lime Seasoning Blend\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nPlace 1/2 cup broth and drained/rinsed white beans in a blender and puree. Add yogurt and blend again. Pour into crockpot. Add all other ingredients and stir well. \nNote: Be sure to rinse and drain black beans and chicken well before adding to crockpot. \nCook over low for 2 hours. Then serve! \n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 275\nTotal Fat 1.91g\nCholesterol 46.88mg\nSodium 892.99mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 36.09g\nDietary Fiber 10.67g\nSugars 7.06g \nProtein 31.83g\n\n', 'Creamy Taco Soup', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'creamy-taco-soup', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=829', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(831, 3, '2011-03-23 13:39:20', '2011-03-23 20:39:20', 'Mar 23, 2011 -\n<b>Could Greek Yogurt be the best new way to lose belly fat?</b>\n\nWomen and men alike hate belly fat—it ruins the look of slinky knits, and makes slacks hard to fit. But belly fat isn''t just unattractive; it''s hazardous to your health. Abdominal fat dramatically <a href="http://www.webmd.com/diet/news/20081112/belly-fat-doubles-death-risk">increases</a> risks of premature death, according to studies published in the New England Journal of Medicine and Circulation. Other studies link belly fat to diabetes, osteoporosis, <a href="http://www.healthfinder.gov/news/newsstory.aspx?docID=647547">breast cancer</a>, and <a href="http://www.webmd.com/migraines-headaches/news/20090213/belly-fat-linked-to-risk-of-migraines">migraines</a> in women.\n\n"Luckily, there''s a delicious way to help blast away belly fat—Greek yogurt," says Jenny Grothe, who, prior to becoming a professional figure builder, was an average 37 year old who went from a size 14 to a 4 in one year and has kept it off since. "Voskos Greek Yogurt makes it easy for both men and women to include more high-protein, high-calcium dairy foods in their diet," says Grothe, "and these are the kinds of foods that have been linked to belly fat reduction."\n\nWhy Greek yogurt?  "The body actually burns more calories digesting protein than carbohydrates," says Grothe. "And protein takes longer to digest, so it helps you feel satiated longer. Greek yogurt has about twice as much protein per serving than regular yogurt, and that helps make Greek yogurt a ''fat-fighting food,'' according to the popular health <a href="http://www.webmd.com/diet/slideshow-fat-fighting-foods">website</a> WebMD.com."\n\nThe best news for fighting belly fat?  Grothe offers, "A study published in the International Journal of Obesity showed that dieters on a high-calcium yogurt lost 81% more belly fat than dieters on a low-calcium diet. That''s about three servings of yogurt per day.\n\n"There is a growing body of research that points to the health benefits of a diet that includes Greek yogurt," adds Grothe. "And with Voskos Greek Yogurt—available in organic, low-fat, non-fat and regular varieties, in flavors like Exotic Fig, Honey, Blueberry, and Vanilla Bean—you can eat healthy without feeling deprived."  A 227 gram (8 ounce) serving of Plain Non-Fat Voskos Greek Yogurt contains 24 grams of protein, and only 9 grams of carbohydrates, which is also important for those who are counting carbs in an effort to lose weight.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, and Cooking Light magazine. It is also a triple gold winner of the 2010 Los Angeles International Dairy Competition.\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt</strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos is the only brand to offer an organic Greek yogurt line in addition to its all-natural plain and blended flavors and never has “fruit on the bottom.” Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in such stores as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations, and to download a coupon, visit voskos.com or Voskos Greek Yogurt on Facebook today.\n\n<strong>About Jenny Grothe</strong>\nAfter losing 60 pounds in under a year, author of "75 Ways to Love Your Oatmeal - Great Tasting Recipes that Keep You Lean," and professional figure builder, Jenny Grothe, quickly learned the value of proper diet and exercise.  At 37, an age when most overweight women want to give up, Jenny didn’t let fate get the best of her. Since losing her weight she has competed in 7 Figure Competitions, taking home 5 trophies, completed 2 marathons, and is now training for the Boston Marathon next month.  With more than 21,000 active fans, Jenny runs the popular Facebook fan page, "Recipes for Gals in Figure & Bodybuilding" where she offers inspiration, tips, product reviews, and healthy recipes for women and men all over the world. Her book, published in December 2010, has nearly sold out its first print run.', 'Is Greek Yogurt the Best Belly Fat Blaster?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-fat-burning-food', '', '', '2011-03-23 13:39:20', '2011-03-23 20:39:20', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=831', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(834, 3, '2011-02-23 05:00:51', '2011-02-23 12:00:51', 'Recipe by <a href="http://jen-fit-training.blogspot.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Jenny Grothe</a>. Makes 1 snack.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n3/4 cup VOSKOS nonfat Greek Yogurt\n1 tsp sugar-free fat-free white chocolate pudding mix\n1 tsp SweetLeaf Lemon Drop stevia drops\n1 graham cracker square (this is included in the nutritional breakdown)\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nWhisk everything - yogurt, pudding, and stevia drops - together. You can either crumble in the graham crack in and mix with it, or have it to the side as seen in the picture.\nAnother variation would be to add poppy seed - which I wanted to do but realized I was out!\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 150\nTotal Fat 0.7g\nSaturated Fat 0.1g\nCholesterol 11.25mg\nSodium 287.4mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 15.71g\nDietary Fiber 0.2g\nSugars 8.2g\nProtein 18.5g\n', 'Lemon Graham Greek Yogurt', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'lemon-graham-greek-yogurt', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=834', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(839, 3, '2011-03-03 05:00:20', '2011-03-03 12:00:20', 'Recipe by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://jen-fit-training.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">Jenny Grothe</a>. Makes 1 snack.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup nonfat VOSKOS Greek Yogurt\n50g fresh or frozen blueberries\n1 stevia packet or to taste\n1/2 tsp pure vanilla extract\n1/2 tbs fat-free sugar-free cheesecake pudding mix\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nUsing a blender mix everything in a small bowl and serve!\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 187\nTotal Fat 0.11g\nSaturated Fat 0g\nCholesterol 15mg\nSodium 358.42mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 19.46g\nDietary Fiber 1.77g\nSugars 11.65g\nProtein 24.22g', 'Cheesecake Greek Yogurt', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'blueberry-cheesecake-greek-yogurt', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=839', 0, 'post', '', 4),
(843, 3, '2011-01-25 15:50:13', '2011-01-25 22:50:13', 'Recipe courtesy of Danielle of <a href="http://peacefulcooking.blogspot.com/2011/01/veggie-melt-on-hbin5-dilled-rye-bread.html" target="_blank" >Cooking for My Peace of Mind</a>. Makes 6 burgers.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 15 oz can black beans, drained \nSalt and Pepper as needed\nOptional: Cayenne pepper, to taste\n1/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons bulgur wheat\n1 egg\nvegetable oil as needed\n1 medium onion, chopped fine (about 1 cup)\n1 celery rib, sliced\n4 garlic cloves, chopped\n1/2 lb mushrooms, sliced \n1/4 cup Voskos Greek Yogurt, Plain\n1 cup bread crumbs or panko crumbs\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a small saucepan, bring 1 cup of salted (1/2 tsp) water to a boil. Stir in the bulgur wheat and cover immediately. Remove from heat and let stand until all the water has absorbed, about 20 minutes.\n2. In a heavy skillet, heat a couple of teaspoons of vegetable oil. Saute the onions, celery, garlic and mushrooms over medium heat until tender.\n3. In a medium sized bowl, combine the bulgur wheat, black beans, sauteed veggies and yogurt. \n4. Transfer the mixture to a food processor and pulse until coarsely chopped, about 15 - 20 times. Transfer back into the bowl and add the egg, bread crumbs and salt and pepper to taste.\n5. Divide your veggie burger mix into 6 equal sized balls and shape them.\n6. Pour a bit of oil in a skillet, and fry, turning carefully because they aren''t as sturdy as meat.\n7. Top with melted American or cheddar cheese and grilled onions.', 'Healthy Veggie Melt', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-veggie-melt', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=843', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(850, 3, '2011-03-31 11:31:44', '2011-03-31 18:31:44', 'Cars, elevators, escalators, home appliances... we''re not moving enough. Then there''s all that convenience food and junk food we''re surrounded with - and tempted by - on a daily basis. Is it any wonder obesity rates are skyrocketing?\n\nWell, it''s time we do something about it.\n\nTaking just 10 minutes, three times a day, to walk will help you live longer. In fact, studies show that just ONE hour of vigorous exercise will increase your life expectancy by TWO hours! It makes sense to walk more and eat well - to live longer.\n\nJoin The American Heart Association on April 6 for <a href="http://www.startwalkingnow.org/about_start_walking_day.jsp" target="_blank">National Start Walking Day</a>. Event will be held in downtown Los Angeles at Union Bank Plaza from 11:45 am - 1 PM. \n\nFestivities include health screenings, yummy Voskos, Subway, goodie bags, massages, t-shirts, LA Galaxy, and CPR Training for everyone. So put your sneakers on an join us - your heart will thank you. \n\nHope to see you there!', 'Join Voskos at National Start Walking Day!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'national-start-walking-day', '', '', '2011-03-31 11:31:44', '2011-03-31 18:31:44', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=850', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(855, 3, '2011-04-07 05:00:08', '2011-04-07 12:00:08', 'We can''t possibly take the credit for this post. Our <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a> fans have basically written it for us, offering awesome breakfast ideas when we had asked them, <a href="http://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10150129126657236&set=a.99562612235.89992.99560247235&comments" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">a few weeks ago</a>, to share their favorite breakfast with us. \n\nHere are their - YOUR! - fab ideas: \n\n1. Voskos Vanilla Honey yogurt, diced fresh strawberries, and grapenuts cereal, mixed all together. total YUM!  -Stephanie Hesse Colasuonno\n\n2. Voskos and bare naked vanilla granola... yummy!! -Cheryl Senay\n      \n3. Whole grain English muffin toasted, with peanut butter, sliced banana and sometimes honey on top-SO good! -Heather from <a href="www.savingmoneylivinglife.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Saving Money, Living Life</a>. \n\n4. <a href="http://anacheyer.blogspot.com/2010/08/overnight-oats.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Overnight Oats</a>! -Ana Frias \n  \n5. Voskos yogurt, a teaspoon of lectin granuals, a slice of toast with fresh marmalade and a multi-vitamin starts my day! -Renee Calhoon\n      \n6. Yogurt, fresh blueberries and a sprinkling of healthy granola or nuts. I have posted this on my fitness page before - it''s a favorite!  -Simply active sonja (Sonja Sandholm-Pound)\n \n7. Voskos honey Greek yogurt with fresh fruit, 12 grain toast with Nutella, and a banana.. wouldn''t hurt to add some green tea or Tazo Focus tea. -Elisha Marie Ickes\n      \n8. <a href="http://thebigredpot.blogspot.com/2010/08/double-berry-pancakes.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Double berry pancakes</a> or <a href="http://thebigredpot.blogspot.com/2010/08/mango-berry-smoothie.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Mango Berry Smoothie</a> -Bethany McGhehey\n\n9. We love yogurt mixed with whole grain cheerios and banana slices! Or peanut butter toast with applesauce. -Jennifer Walker Holmes  \n      \n10. I like fruit or applesauce topped with vanilla yogurt and Fruit and Nut Granola for breakfast! -Joyce Tremblay\n\n11. Honey vanilla yogurt, banana, strawberries, chia seed, and vanilla almond milk...blended! Great smoothie...breakfast on the go. -Melissa Lynn Kirkland      \n\n12. One of my favorite way to eat Voskos is: Plain Voskos Yogurt + 2 teaspoons of honey + crumble feta cheese on top and dive in! Also: Toasted crushed almonds, sprinkle over Voskos Fig Yogurt. -Rob Mikitarian  \n\n13. Any flavor Voskos with Grape Nuts sprinkled on top..filling and delicious, and good for you! -Ginny Keenan    \n\n14. 1 Vanilla Voskos greek yogurt, 3/4 - 1 cup frozen mixed berries, 1/8-1/4 cup orange juice, 1t agave nectar, blend with ice. Pour in glass, drink with straw! Yum! -Cindy Fraustro  \n      \n15. Spray a small flat bowl with nonstick spray, beat an egg in it, microwave for 45 seconds. Remove from mic. Microwave a whole grain tortilla for 10 seconds. Dice your egg. Put egg, cheese, pepper and salsa in tortilla for a filling breakfast burrito in under a minute. -Amy Hansen     \n      \n16. ‎1 Vanilla Honey Voskos, 1/2 cup frozen blueberries, 1 cup Almond Milk and 1 scoop Whey protein powder - blend in blender until smooth- Yum!! -Cathy Rawlinson Lawrence      \n\n17. Voskos honey bean yogurt with Back to Nature granola with pumpkin and sunflower see. -Nicole Addison \n\nAnd here are three more ideas from our own kitchen:\n\n18. <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/breakfast/greek-yogurt-banana-pancakes">Greek yogurt banana pancakes</a>. \n\n19. <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/breakfast/quick-healthy-breakfast">The simplest breakfast EVER</a>! Thanks <a href="http://pintofactory.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Stefan Pinto</a> for the video. \n\n20. <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/breakfast/greek-yogurt-breakfast-shake">Greek yogurt breakfast shake</a>. \n\nCan you add more healthy breakfast ideas? Share them in the comments!', '20 Yummy, Healthy Breakfast Ideas', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-breakfast-ideas', '', '', '2011-04-07 05:00:08', '2011-04-07 12:00:08', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=855', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(867, 3, '2011-04-14 05:00:12', '2011-04-14 12:00:12', 'I used to be afraid to tweak recipes. "What if the recipe is ruined if I make changes?" I thought. But over the years, I have learned that cooking - even baking - is just as much art as it is science, and that there''s absolutely no reason to be afraid to make changes. This is especially true for cooking - tweaking baked goods recipes is a bit more tricky, but as you''ll soon see, it can be done. \n\nThe need to tweak came when the doctor had ordered my husband to consume less sugar, and more fiber, in an effort to control his blood sugar. Suddenly, looking at my collection of recipes, I realized how unhealthy many of them were. So I started making changes. \n\n<strong>The main changes I tend to make are the following:</strong>\n\n1. <em>Less added sugar</em>. I find that almost all cake and muffin recipes contain way too much sugar. Cutting the sugar by a third - sometimes even by half - is almost always just fine.\n\n2. <em>More fiber</em>. I now replace between a third to a half of the flour in all bread and muffin recipes with 100% whole wheat flour. \n\n3. <em>Less saturated fat</em>. Sour cream can almost always be replaced with <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">greek yogurt</a>. Butter can often be replaced with <a href="http://www.hsph.harvard.edu/nutritionsource/what-should-you-eat/fats-full-story/index.html" target="_blank">heart-healthy canola oil</a>, or - for savory recipes - with olive oil. Sometimes you can forgo fat altogether and use applesauce, especially in muffin recipes and in quick breads. \n\nAn example? Sure! These are the ingredients for a quick cheese bread recipe. I have made the bread before. It''s amazing. It''s from The Best Recipe cookbook, which contains a large collection of foolproof recipes. \n\n<h3>Quick Cheese Bread: Original Recipe</h3>\n3 ounces Parmesan cheese\n4 ounces cheddar cheese\n3 cups all purpose flour\n1 TBS baking powder \n1/4 tsp cayenne pepper\n1 tsp salt\n1/8 tsp ground black pepper\n1 + 1/4 cup whole milk\n3 TBS unsalted butter, melted\n1 large egg\n3/4 cups sour cream\n\nA slice (1/10) of bread resulting from this recipe contains 315 calories, 15 grams total fat, 9 grams saturated fat, 57mg cholesterol, 1 gram of dietary fiber, and 12 grams protein. \n\nNow take a look at the healthier version:\n\n<h3>Quick Cheese Bread: Healthier Recipe</h3>\n3 ounces Parmesan cheese, shredded\n2 ounces cheddar cheese, shredded\n2 ounces part skim mozzarella cheese, shredded\n2 cups all purpose flour\n1 cup whole wheat flour\n1 TBS baking powder \n1/4 tsp cayenne pepper\n1 tsp salt\n1/8 tsp ground black pepper\n1 + 1/4 cup 2% milk\n2 TBS olive oil \n1 large egg\n3/4 cups low fat greek yogurt\n\nThis version contains 240 calories, 7 grams total fat, 4 grams saturated fat, 38mg cholesterol, 2 grams dietary fiber and 14 grams of protein. \n\n<strong>Now, if I told you that this was just as good as the original recipe (and I should know, since I have made both), wouldn''t you rather enjoy a healthier version?</strong>\n\nAdmittedly, recipes CAN be ruined when tweaked. But in the vast majority of cases, substituting Greek yogurt for sour cream, reducing the amount of sugar, using oil instead of butter and replacing part of the flour with whole wheat flour results in an excellent recipe. \n\nHere''s how to make this delicious bread:\n1. Heat oven to 350 degrees. Spray a 9 X 5 pan with cooking spray.\n2. In a large bowl, whisk flours, baking powder, and spices. Mix in the cheeses.  \n3. In a medium bowl, whisk together milk, oil, egg and yogurt. \n4. Gently fold wet ingredients into dry, using a rubber spatula, until just combined. Batter will be heavy and thick. Do not over-mix.\n5. Transfer to pan, spread and level with spatula. \n6. Bake about 1 hour, until golden brown and a knife inserted in center comes out clean. Cool in pan on a wire rack 5 minutes, then transfer to wire rack and cool 45 more minutes before slicing and serving. \n\n<img src="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/Cheese-Bread-589-optimized2.jpg" alt="" title="Cheese Bread 589 optimized" width="589" height="352" class="alignright size-full wp-image-878" />\n\nDo you ever tweak recipes to make them healthier? ', 'The Art of Tweaking Recipes to Make Them Healthier', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'tweaking-recipes', '', '', '2011-04-14 05:00:12', '2011-04-14 12:00:12', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=867', 0, 'post', '', 3),
(872, 3, '2011-02-09 15:05:19', '2011-02-09 22:05:19', 'Tzatziki is a traditional Greek appetizer, which I have grown up with, and LOVE. Tzatziki in itself is a healthy meal, but by using Voskos Greek yogurt you''re getting twice the protein, and you don''t have to go through the hassle of straining the yogurt. \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\nA 16oz container Voskos Plain Greek Yogurt\n2 cucumbers - peeled, seeded and diced\n2 tablespoons olive oil\n1/2 lemon, juiced\nsalt and pepper to taste\n1 tablespoon chopped fresh dill\n1 teaspoon mint\n1 clove garlic, minced \n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nSimply combine all the ingredients, chill for about an hour, and serve! It doesn''t get any easier than that. :) Serve Tzatziki as a side to grilled vegetables or meat, with warm pita bread, with chips, or - my favorite - serve it over a bowl of rice. \n\nAnd here''s a great tip from one of our <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a> fans, Melissa Aivaliklis: "After you dice your cucumber very small, lay it in a single layer on paper towels. Give it a very light sprinkle of salt. Put more paper towels on top. Let it drain for at least 10 minutes. If you skip this step, the excess water in the cucumber will make your tzatziki runny. My husband is Greek, this is the first Greek thing I learned to make. Always gets rave reviews. :)"\n\nEnjoy! And if you have any more tips, we''d love to hear about them in the comments section below, or on our Facebook page. \n\n<iframe title="YouTube video player" width="640" height="390" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/4MEv_br8xWo?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'VIDEO: Voskos Tzatziki', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-tzatziki', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=872', 0, 'post', '', 3);
