(927, 3, '2011-03-22 05:00:21', '2011-03-22 12:00:21', 'Makes 1 BIG Omelet\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup egg substitute or equivalent in egg whites (6 approx)\n1/2 tsp baking powder\n1 tsp PB2\n40g banana\n1 tbs Walden Farms Zero-Calorie Chocolate Sauce\n3 tbs nonfat cottage cheese\n1/4 cup Voskos nonfat Greek Yogurt\n1 stevia packet\ndash cinnamon\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Blend 30g banana, eggs, cottage cheese, baking powder, and PB2 in a blender. Heat pan over medium. Coat with cooking spray. Pour egg mixture in to pan. Sprinkle with cinnamon. Cover. Let cook for a few minutes until it starts to puff-up. Remove lid and continue cooking until firm to touch. Transfer to plate. Pour tbs of Walden Farms zero-calorie chocolate sauce on omelet and spread with a knife. Slice remaining banana into thin pieces and dot on omelet. Fold.\n2. Combine VOSKOS nonfat Greek Yogurt with 1 stevia packet (if needed) and spread on folded omelet. Dot with chocolate sauce and sprinkle with cinnamon and/or PB2.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 231\nCalories from Fat 2.3\nTotal Fat 0.25g\nCholesterol 6mg\nSodium 673.34mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 18.53g\nDietary Fiber 1.6g\nSugars 14.51g\nProtein 36.22g', 'Banana Chocolate Omelet', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'banana-chocolate-omelet', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=927', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(935, 3, '2011-03-15 14:38:28', '2011-03-15 21:38:28', 'Who has time to make breakfast these days? \n\nBut before you resort to some sugary cereal, or to an artery-clogging fast food breakfast, try doing the simplest thing ever: \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\nVoskos Greek Yogurt, non fat or low fat\nA handful of raisins\nA handful of almonds\nA drizzle of honey\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nMix the raisins and almonds into creamy, high-protein, low fat Voskos Greek yogurt and drizzle with honey. This easy breakfast will keep you satiated for hours! \n\nThank you <a href="http://pintofactory.com" target="_blank">Stefan Pinto</a>! Awesome. \n\n<iframe title="YouTube video player" width="560" height="349" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/8e5NuqRYTeg?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'VIDEO: A Quick, Healthy Breakfast', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'quick-healthy-breakfast', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=935', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(936, 3, '2011-05-03 17:27:58', '2011-05-04 00:27:58', 'If breakfast is truly the most important meal of the day, why do so many people casually skip it? According to recently published studies, breakfast skipping combined with fast food consumption rapidly and significantly increases weight gain in adults and teens.\n\nBreak the fast of your overnight slumber and kick-start your day with these easy-to-prepare meals that are not only hassle-free, but high in energy. Most of these breakfasts contain added protein in the form of powders. \n\n<strong>1. Goji Protein Oatmeal</strong>\nYou will need: Protein powder, goji berries and oatmeal. \nHow to enjoy: Using 2 cups of oatmeal, pour in just enough water to cover the oatmeal. Microwave for two minutes. Mix in 2 scoops of protein powder (ok to add more water for consistency). Add goji berries. \nI recommend: Vega Whole Food Optimizer (protein), Navatis Naturals Organic Raw Goji Berries, organic old fashioned oats (generic is fine)\n\n<strong>2. Two Banana Black Coffee with Hemp</strong>\nYou will need: Bananas (buy one week’s worth and separate from stem), coffee, hemp milk.\n INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(967, 9, '2011-06-06 16:49:44', '2011-06-06 23:49:44', 'I’ve been running now for three years and half years. \n\nAt times its hard to believe its been that long. It doesn’t seem like that long ago I hated running. I loathed it. I remember track in high school. Anything longer than the 800, and I’d “ditch”. Long distance wasn’t my thing. Even with the 800 I experienced exercise induced asthma, but back then I didn’t even know that’s what it was called. I simply experienced it – gasping for air, wheezing, shortness of breath – all signs. \n\nNow that I run regularly, I often experience some level of it, but its always been manageable. It’s the worst after my long runs – especially if I’ve been running in the cold morning weather. Within a few minutes I’m fine. My chest might be a little tight, but it passes within an hour. \n\nThree and ½ years later, I have run various terrains, in all types of weather conditions, and at varying altitudes. I’ve run at 8,800’ and at sea level. I’ve run steep mountains and cascaded down declines. I’ve never experienced anything I couldn’t handle, physically. \n\nUntil last weekend. \n\nLast weekend I ran the Moab Red Rock Relay with five other girlfriends. Our team name was Gym Bums, and I was their captain. I’d previously run the Vegas Ragnar (once) and the Wasatch Back Ragnar Relay (twice). I’d run three marathons – two of which started high in the mountains. No trouble, whatsoever. \n\nLast weekend was different. \n\nLeading up to my first leg, I felt fine. My stomach felt okay. I had a decent amount of energy, and I thought I’d done everything I could to mentally and physically prepare for the challenge. Why would this time be any different from the others? I’d run with less sleep. I’d run hungrier. In relay situations I’d practically run on fumes. Relays are unlike any other race. At the beginning of your 1st leg you feel great, but by the 2nd and 3rd legs when you’ve had little to no sleep, have been snacking on junk food or whatever’s convenient in the car, you are exhausted, famished, and a little “silly”. \n\nThis time was different. \n\nI’d barely started my first leg which was a steep incline starting at what I’m guessing was around 7,500’, and I was sick to my stomach. Sour stomach sick. Within minutes I was wheezing, and it took everything in me to suck air in to my lungs. My throat filled with gunk, and I constantly had to clear it to keep oxygen flowing. It was a very difficult run and the start of what I call a “bad running day”. \n\nIt ate at me the rest of the day and in to the next morning. I thought I’d prepared. I was disappointed, mad, and angry with myself. \n\nIt wasn’t until I stumbled across an article on Altitude Sickness that I realized what had happened. \n\nThe first thing I learned was that altitude sickness can happen to any one at any time in the higher elevations. Just because you’re fit doesn’t mean you are immune. Another thing I learned was that just because you haven’t experienced it before doesn’t mean you won’t experience it in the future. None of that mattered. That explained my situation. \n\nThis happened to me, and I live in a higher elevation. \n\nThis happened to me, and I’d just run Boston less than a month ago. \n\nAltitude Sickness does not discriminate. \n\n I have another relay in less than four weeks, and I am going to make absolutely sure I do everything I can to prevent a repeat of what happened in Moab. \n\nAfter reading a number of articles, I’ve narrowed it down to six preventative measures:\n\n1. It’s important to train physically before the trip. Training helps strengthen your lungs which in turn can help your lung’s capacity to cope with the challenging higher altitudes. \n2. Stay hydrated before and during the race. Try to get in at least 2 liters of water the day before and drink throughout the day of. \n3. Eat a balanced meal but focus primarily on carbohydrates. Pre-run I always have yogurt with some dried oats. In the future, I’m planning to carb-up my VOSKOS Greek Yogurt with big chunks of fruit and spoonfuls of granola and dried oats. \n4. Acclimate to the altitude you’ll be running in when possible. Arrive a day early, give your body a chance to acclimate and become comfortable with the higher elevation.\n5. Try not to compete against those around you if at all possible. Everyone acclimates at different rates. The harder you push your body at higher altitudes the more likely you’ll suffer the consequences of Altitude Sickness. \n6. If you are susceptible to Altitude Sickness, talk to your doctor about taking dexamethasone, an anti-inflammatory, which can help open up the passageways, increasing oxygen flow. \n\nI plan on enjoying my next relay. I don’t want another surprise. I’ve run the Wasatch Back twice before, and both times I loved it. I had a great time. I don’t want to experience another “bad running day”, and I can guarantee you I’ll be doing everything I can to prevent it. \n', 'Fitness: Dealing with Altitude Sickness ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'altitude-sickness', '', '', '2011-06-06 16:49:44', '2011-06-06 23:49:44', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=967', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(972, 3, '2011-07-12 05:00:28', '2011-07-12 12:00:28', 'I used to assume that "a calorie is a calorie" and that it didn''t really matter what I ate, as long as I kept portions under control. But recent changes my husband and I have made to our diets have shown us that we can actually eat more, feel satiated, and lose or maintain our weight. \n\nThe secret? Avoiding refined, processed foods that are rapidly broken down into sugar, absorbed into the blood, causing a spike in blood sugar and leaving us hungry just a couple of hours later. Our diet is now rich in veggies and fruit, lean protein and whole grains. We eat a ton of food, we''re never hungry, and yet we''re losing weight! \n\nThis is very exciting for us, and we were so happy to read that our personal findings are backed by scientific evidence. A recent <a href="http://www.npr.org/2011/06/23/137376133/trying-to-lose-weight-study-says-avoid-potatoes" target="_blank">Harvard study</a> says that not all calories are created equal. Highly refined foods, including white bread, white rice and potatoes, are related to increased weight gain, while fruits, vegetables, whole grains, nuts and yogurt are related to lower weight gain.\n\nYogurt helps with weight loss, or with avoiding weight gain, because the types of bacteria in our colon influence our state of inflammation and weight gain. The healthy bacteria in the yogurt are helping change the mix of bacteria in the colon and positively influencing weight. \n\nNuts are good because, despite being high-fat, they contain good fats. Nuts are essentially a package of fat, fiber and important micronutrients that are not rapidly absorbed into the body, and so we stay satiated for longer. \n\nAnother interesting observation made by the Harvard scientists is that "just because a food has fat doesn''t mean that it''s going to be fattening." This is important, because we''ve all been trying to avoid fat for so long now, but fat is actually crucial to our bodies, especially good fats such as those found in olive oil. According to the study, this is also true for fat from dairy, such as cheese and yogurt. This is possibly because fat helps keep us satiated, so we end up consuming fewer calories. \n\nTrying to lose weight? Forget about counting calories. Instead, focus on a diet that will keep you satiated, replacing refined carbs with high protein, high fiber foods, including fruit, vegetables, nuts and yogurt.   \n ', 'Trying to Lose Weight? Eat Some Yogurt!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'trying-to-lose-weight-eat-some-yogurt', '', '', '2011-07-12 05:00:28', '2011-07-12 12:00:28', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=972', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(974, 3, '2011-03-29 17:08:54', '2011-03-30 00:08:54', 'This yummy shake takes just minutes to make. It''s good for you, perfect on the go, and the extra protein will keep you fuller for longer. \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1.5 cups fresh orange juice\n2 TBS heaping vanilla protein powder\n1 sliced banana\n1/4 cup Voskos organic vanilla bean Greek yogurt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nSimply blend all ingredients in a blender. Enjoy!\n\n<iframe title="YouTube video player" width="560" height="349" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/R5OZE-Vjc7o?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'VIDEO: Greek Yogurt Breakfast Shake', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-breakfast-shake', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=974', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(983, 3, '2011-07-08 08:00:51', '2011-07-08 15:00:51', 'The secret to avoiding unwanted weight gain in college: focusing on quick and easy, yet nutritious meals.\n\nSun Valley, CA -July 8, 2011- Mary was determined not to gain any extra weight during her first year in college. Instead of hopping on the “junk food and alcohol” train, she started <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/users?uid=45">Mary’s Kitchen</a>, where she develops quick, easy and nutritious meals for anyone who’s too busy for elaborate cooking and for recipes with 25 ingredients. \n\nFreshman Fifteen, the notorious average weight gain during many students’ first year of college, is a real problem, because more often than not, it does not go away after the first year. Once you pack on the pounds, it’s very difficult to take the weight off, so it’s crucial to avoid this weight gain in the first place. \n\nWith the obesity epidemic one of the major problems facing the US, and with Mrs. Obama’s commendable efforts to put a stop to this worrying phenomenon, it is up to college students to take care of themselves and avoid becoming the next overweight generation. \n\n“I knew I wanted to stay healthy and eat well, even on a limited budget and with very little free time,” says Mary. “I know too many college freshmen who forgot all about healthy eating, and started consuming so much junk that they gained more than fifteen pounds in just one year! I didn’t want this to happen to me, so I started Mary’s Kitchen, as a way to make myself accountable and get in the habit of regularly coming up with quick, nutritious meals and snacks” adds Mary. \n\nMary focuses on recipes that require no cooking or minimal cooking. She uses Voskos Greek Yogurt in most of her recipes, as an easy way to add protein and calcium without adding sugar and unwanted calories. \n\n“College students need healthy meals and snacks to curb hunger and minimize the urge for unhealthy snacking” says June M Lay, M.S. “Much of the typical college weight gain is caused by consuming highly processed, refined carbohydrates and high-sugar juices, sodas and alcohol. Having high-protein, high-quality real food that requires minimum preparation can give students much-needed nutrients and energy. Dairy is really important here, as the protein, natural milk carbohydrate, calcium still needed for bone growth and B12 found in milk products such as yogurt can go a long way in helping students feel satiated and avoid that notorious weight gain during the first year of college” adds Lay. \n\nOne of Mary''s favorite recipes is her <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/breakfast/video-voskos-breakfast-spread">Voskos Breakfast Spread</a>. With this spread in your fridge, there are truly no more excuses! Even if your mornings are super hectic, all you need to do is spread this delicious, protein-packed spread on warm toast, and you’re good to go. Or you can just eat it with a spoon – it’s so creamy and delicious. \n\nFreshman Fifteen doesn’t have to happen to you. Join Mary, and say NO to college weight gain!\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt</strong>\nAward winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, and gluten-free. Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method offers 2x more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos offers a full line of products: organic and all-natural, along with plain and blended flavors (never “fruit on the bottom”). Available nationwide. For store locations and more information, visit www.voskos.com today. \n \n<strong>About June Lay, M.S. </strong>\nAuthor of “It’s Not a Diet, It’s Creative Eating” and lifestyle columnist at healthnewsdigest.com. Her website, <a href="http://www.junefit.com/" target="_blank">JuneFit</a> is included in Google''s top ranked women''s health.  Ms. Lay is available for media interviews. \n', 'College Student Says No to “Freshman Fifteen”', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'avoid-freshman-fifteen', '', '', '2011-07-08 08:00:51', '2011-07-08 15:00:51', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=983', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(984, 3, '2011-04-05 12:26:20', '2011-04-05 19:26:20', 'This moussaka keeps fat content in check and protein content high by using baked, rather than fried, eggplants, and a mixture of Voskos Greek Yogurt and eggs instead of traditional, butter-containing, béchamel sauce. \n\nMakes 6 servings. \n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 large eggplants, peeled \n2 TBS olive oil \n1 large onion, finely chopped \n4 medium garlic cloves, crushed\n1 pound lean ground beef \n1 can diced tomatoes, drained \n2 tablespoons finely chopped parsley \n½ teaspoon crushed dried oregano\n1 tsp salt\n¼ tsp freshly ground black pepper\n¼ tsp cinnamon \n2 eggs, beaten\n¾ cup Low Fat (or non fat) Plain Voskos Greek yogurt, at room temperature \n1/2 cup (2oz) shredded part skim Mozzarella cheese \n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Cut eggplants crosswise into ½-inch-thick round slices. Place on baking sheet over wax paper in a single layer, brush with 1 TBS olive oil, and roast in a 500 degrees F oven for 20 minutes, or until golden. \n\n2. Lower oven temperature to 375 degrees F.\n\n3. Sauté onion and garlic in 1 TBS olive oil until soft but not browned, stirring frequently.\n\n4. Add the meat and cook until lightly browned, breaking it up with a wooden spoon.\n\n5. Stir in the tomatoes, parsley, oregano, cinnamon, and salt and pepper. Cook, uncovered, about 10 minutes or until most of the liquid has evaporated.\n\n6. Arrange half the eggplant slices in the bottom of a shallow 2-quart baking dish. An 11 X 7 X 1.5 inch dish works well. Spread the meat mixture over eggplant slices. Cover with the remaining eggplant slices. \n\n7. Mix together the beaten eggs and yogurt well with a hand whisk until creamy, and pour over the top. \n\n8. Sprinkle the cheese on top. Bake, uncovered, in a preheated 375°F oven 40 minutes or until top is golden and set.\n\n<img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/Moussaka-31.jpg" alt="Moussaka " title="Moussaka 3" width="589" height="349" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-995" />\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCalories 364\nTotal Fat 24 g\nSodium 585.7 mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 16.4 g\nDietary Fiber 4.8 g\nSugars 3.2 g\nProtein 21.6 g', 'Better-For-You Moussaka', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'better-for-you-moussaka', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '2013-08-05 21:00:45', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=984', 0, 'post', '', 3),
(1003, 10, '2011-07-19 10:54:56', '2011-07-19 17:54:56', 'In my practice, most of my clientele are over the age of 65 with many health issues ranging from arthritis, fatigue, high blood pressure, diabetes and obesity. Many do not exercise and have poor eating habits. Today’s societies overlook our growing senior population and believe that when one retires, it’s just relaxing and basking in achievements of one’s past experiences. In reality, our senior population has a serious problem with malnutrition. \n\nSocial factors that affect malnutrition include, living alone, financial concerns, and restrictive diets. Living alone, especially for men, results in the decreased intake of food. Elders experiencing financial concerns, such as poverty or low-income, may not be able to buy a sufficient amount of food. Many times choices need to be made between buying food and paying for other necessities such as medications, heat, rent, etc (Visvanathan & Chapman, 2009). \n\nWhen I talk with my senior clients about nutrition, I ask them what do they eat on a daily basis? What they tell me isn’t unusual. They eat the normal American diet of processed food, barely including fruits, vegetables and quality protein. \n\nWith seniors, many know how to cook and prepare food, but when you’re the only one in the house or in poor health, why cook? I understand my clients and their needs, so I don’t push them to go cook a meal, but work with them to make sure all of their nutritional needs will be met within their budget. All of us health experts know that when one goes to the grocery store, life is found on the outer aisles of the store. Produce, meats, dairy and whole grain bread are life-giving foods. Death lives within the aisles of the store, where all of the prepackaged, processed foods are located. So what do I tell them? There are many ways to get the nutrition you need without breaking the bank and can be prepared in a short time. \n\nLet’s look at a few ways to get three healthy meals that will provide improved health for our seniors. These examples are more for those seniors who are not active or home-bound. \n\n<strong>Breakfast: </strong>\nWhey protein shake with fruit (blueberries).\n182 calories; 22 grams of protein; 1 grams of fat; 10 grams of carbs; 4 grams of fiber\n\nOr Voskos Nonfat Greek Yogurt with an whole grain English muffin with strawberry jam.\n280 calories; 20 grams of protein; 1 grams of fat; 40 grams of carbs; 1 gram of fiber\n\nOr Voskos’ YoGreek Yogurt with Granola\n140 calories; 11 grams of protein; ½ gram of fat; 22 grams of carbs; 1 gram of fiber\nHealthy grains from multi-grain cereals, toast or muffins can be added as well. Healthy fats such as flaxseed oil are also recommended for balanced breakfast. \n\n<strong>Lunch:</strong>\nCaesar Salad with Romaine lettuce (1 cup).\n170 calories; 6 grams of protein; 14 grams of fat; 6 grams of carbs; 2 grams of fiber\n\nTurkey / Cheese Sandwich \n235 Calories; 25 grams of protein; 4 grams of fat; 25 grams of carbs; 4 grams of fiber\n\nAdd Voskos Nonfat Greek Yogurt (Strawberry) for dessert\n120 Calories; 13 grams of protein; 0 grams of fat; 16 grams of carbs; 0 grams of fiber.\n\n<strong>Dinner: </strong>\n(Example of a whole Dinner)\nPan Roasted Chicken \n223 calories; 31 grams of protein; 10 grams of fat; 1 gram of carb; 0 g fiber\n\nSmall Dinner Salad with Balsamic Oil and Vinegar Dressing\nSalad – 1 cup. 50 calories; 3 grams of protein; 3 grams of carbs; 2 grams of fiber\nDressing - Per tablespoon. 90 calories; 1 g carbohydrates; 10 g fat\n\n1 cup of Steamed Broccoli\n54 calories; 4 grams of protein; 8 grams of carbs; 5 grams of fiber\n\nFor Dessert – Voskos Nonfat Greek Yogurt (Honey)\n130 calories; 13 grams of protein; 18 grams of carbs; 0 grams of fiber\n\nThe examples above are just examples. Daily calorie intake should be 1,500-2,000 calories for seniors who are not active and home bound. If exercise is part of one’s daily routine, the calorie intake will of course increase. \n\nOne last note. We should all respect our senior population for their wisdom, insight and past experiences. Help a senior today so both you will have a better tomorrow. ', 'Senior Nutrition', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'senior-nutrition', '', '', '2011-07-19 10:54:56', '2011-07-19 17:54:56', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1003', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1008, 3, '2011-05-04 05:00:39', '2011-05-04 12:00:39', '<a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.bellplantation.com/" target="_blank">PB2</a> is powdered peanut butter. It''s a great way to get that peanut butter taste, without the fat and calories. We love mixing it into Voskos plain <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a>, or using it when baking. Here''s one of our favorite recipes to make. Note that the batter is just slightly sweet, but the chocolate chips sweeten it more than enough. We adapted it from <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.bellplantation.com/recipes/pb2-chocolate-chip-muffins" target="_blank">this</a> recipe.\n\n12 Servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients </strong>\n1 cup whole wheat flour\n3/4 cup all purpose flour\n6 TBS PB2\n2 tsp baking powder\n1/2 tsp salt\n1/4 cup sugar\n\n1 large egg\n1 cup 2% milk\n1 TBS vanilla\n2 TBS vegetable oil\n1/2 cup plain, lowfat VOSKOS Greek yogurt\n1/2 cup chocolate chips\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nMix dry ingredients (first 6 listed). Mix liquid ingredients in another bowl. Pour liquid over dry and mix just until incorporated. Add chocolate chips. Spoon into muffin tin lined with liners and sprayed with baking spray. Bake at 350 degrees for approximately 20 minutes.\n\n<strong>Nutrition </strong>\nPer muffin (approximate): 180 calories, 7g total fat, 2g saturated fat, 17mg cholesterol, 24g Carbohydrates, 2g dietary fiber, 10g sugars, 5g protein.', 'PB2 Chocolate Chip Muffins', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'pb2-chocolate-chip-muffins', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:40', '2013-08-05 21:00:40', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1008', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1011, 3, '2011-07-25 10:19:54', '2011-07-25 17:19:54', 'Want to lose weight…and keep it off as you age? A new <a href="http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1014296" target="_blank">study</a> published in the New England Journal of Medicine suggests a link between yogurt and weight loss. The study, conducted by the Harvard School of Public Health, quizzed over 120,000 nurses and other health workers about their dietary habits over the course of many years. The goal was to discover what impact diet had on weight over time.\n\nConsumption of two foods—nuts and yogurt—were most closely correlated with weight loss, according to Walter Willett, one of the study''s co-authors. Interviewed on National Public Radio, Willett noted that the active probiotic cultures in yogurt may be responsible for yogurt''s weight loss powers. "There has been a lot of work in recent years on how the types of bacteria in our colon influence our state of inflammation and weight gain. So it may well be that the healthy bacteria in the yogurt are helping change the mix of bacteria in the colon and influencing weight."\n\nVoskos <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek Yogurt</a> is made with a mix of beneficial probiotic cultures, including Lactobacillus acidophilus, Bifidobacterium bifidus, and Lactobacillus casei. "In a healthy person, the population of good (healthy) bacteria in the gut outnumbers the numbers of bad (pathogenic) bacteria," says registered dietician Janet R. Mertz, MS, RD, CDE, CPT., a contributor to Voskos Greek Yogurt''s "What''s Fresh" blog. "Consuming Voskos Greek Yogurt helps support a healthy blend of bacteria in the digestive system."\n\nWillett also noted that fat content in foods did not mean that the food itself was fattening. "But eating foods that keep us satisfied is really going to be important in the long run."\n\nThat "satisfaction factor" is one reason Greek yogurt has been called a "superfood" when it comes to losing weight, says Mertz. "Greek yogurt is a great weight loss food because of its high calcium and protein levels," she says "Studies show that protein takes longer to digest, and is more satisfying, than ''empty'' carbohydrates. You feel full longer after you''ve enjoyed a serving of Greek yogurt. And that may keep you from snacking on other, higher-calorie foods."\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. It is also a triple gold winner of the 2010 Los Angeles International Dairy Competition. Visit Voskos'' Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes - breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks. \n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt</strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos is the only brand to offer an organic Greek yogurt line in addition to its all-natural plain and blended flavors and never has “fruit on the bottom.” Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in such stores as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations, and to download a coupon, visit Voskos.com or "like" Voskos Greek Yogurt on <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a> today.\n\n<strong>About Janet Mertz, Janet R. Mertz, MS, RD, CDE, CPT</strong>\nJanet Mertz is a diabetes educator, wife of a Type-1 diabetic and mother who enjoys helping educate people on nutrition and healthy lifestyle.', 'Eat Yogurt If You Want To Lose Weight, Says Harvard Study', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'yogurt-weight-loss', '', '', '2011-07-25 10:19:54', '2011-07-25 17:19:54', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1011', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1017, 3, '2011-07-28 08:30:13', '2011-07-28 15:30:13', 'Most women know that a healthy diet is vital during pregnancy. But Voskos Greek Yogurt would like to remind women that proper nutrition is just as important for new moms who are breastfeeding. In commemoration  of World Breastfeeding Week — a seven-day salute to breastfeeding that is observed in 170 countries from August 1 to August 7, 2011 — Voskos Greek Yogurt suggests adding Greek yogurt to your diet if you are breastfeeding.\n\nAccording to WomensHealth.gov, babies who are breast-fed have fewer ear infections, respiratory infections, skin rashes, and less diarrhea than formula-fed infants. Breastfeeding also lowers a baby''s risk for developing asthma, obesity, diabetes and childhood leukemia.\n\n"Breastfeeding moms need extra amounts of several nutrients that are found in Greek yogurt," says Registered Dietitian Melissa Hooper, founder of Bite-Size Nutrition. Hooper is a contributor to Voskos Greek Yogurt''s "What''s Fresh" blog.\n\n"According to the American Academy of Pediatrics," says Hooper, "nursing mothers should consume five servings of calcium-rich foods per day, totaling between 1,000 and 1,300 milligrams of calcium. It''s important to include this amount of calcium in the diet because otherwise, the body may ''steal'' calcium from the mother''s bones in order to make milk for the baby." One 8-ounce serving of Voskos Plain Nonfat Greek Yogurt contains 200 milligrams of calcium, which is 20% of the recommended allowance for breastfeeding mothers.\n\nHooper adds, "Breastfeeding moms also need to consume a diet that includes about 75 grams of protein per day, and you can accomplish that with just three 8-ounce servings of Voskos Plain Nonfat Greek Yogurt. The beauty of plain Greek yogurt is that it''s thicker and creamier than regular yogurt," says Hooper, "so you can easily substitute it for sour cream in recipes. This gives you the flexibility to incorporate Greek yogurt into any meal—not just breakfast."\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in food contests presented by Self, Fitness, Shape, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, and Cooking Light magazine. It is also a triple gold winner of the 2010 Los Angeles International Dairy Competition.\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt</strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, and gluten-free and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos is the only brand to offer an organic Greek yogurt line in addition to its all-natural plain and blended flavors and never has “fruit on the bottom.” Available nationwide. Now available at Publix stores. Retails for $1.59 for 5.3 oz varieties. For store locations, healthy Greek yogurt recipes and to download a coupon, visit voskos.com today.\n\n<strong>About World Breastfeeding Week</strong>\nWorld Breastfeeding Week 2011 takes place August 1 through 7th, and is recognized in over 170 countries worldwide. The event is promoted by the World Alliance for Breastfeeding Action (WABA), a global network of individuals and organizations concerned with the protection, promotion and support of breastfeeding worldwide.\n\n<strong>About Registered Dietitian Melissa Hooper</strong>\nA health commentator and radio host, Melissa Hooper is the founder of Bite-Size Nutrition. Her “Minute for Your Health” reports can be heard on Clear Channel’s KOST & KHHT “HOT92.3” in Los Angeles. She also hosts a weekly TV spot, "The Easy Living Segment." Melissa is also a contributing author for The Competitive Edge.\n\n<font size="1">Photo credit: <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/hodac/338724105/in/photostream/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">ODHD</a></font>', 'Voskos Greek Yogurt Salutes World Breastfeeding Week', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-greek-yogurt-salutes-world-breastfeeding-week', '', '', '2011-07-28 08:30:13', '2011-07-28 15:30:13', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1017', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1021, 3, '2011-04-28 18:14:19', '2011-04-29 01:14:19', 'Today we’re making a delicious Greek meal called Gyro.\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n½ cup Mixed baby greens\n1 chicken kebab, diced\n½ a tomato, sliced\n1/2 onion, sliced\n3 tbsp Plain non-fat Voskos Greek Yogurt\n1 Pita bread\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nEasy! Simply place all the ingredients in the pita, wrap it up, and you’re good to go. \nCompared to a cheeseburger, this takes the one for health AND taste!\n\n<iframe width="560" height="349" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/K-Eg8EYElGU?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'VIDEO: Greek Gyro', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-gyro-recipe', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1021', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1027, 3, '2011-04-28 18:23:08', '2011-04-29 01:23:08', 'Coming from a big traditional family, Easter is always HUGE at our home. But we try to take the healthy route when it comes to all those yummy foods and traditional meals. Dips can be seriously fatty – but this spinach yogurt dip is just as good. Compared to a cup of mayo, Voskos has 218 calories, while mayonnaise had 916!\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 8oz container of plain Voskos Greek Yogurt\n1/2 cup of pre-cooked spinach\n1 clove of minced garlic\nA pinch of salt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nSimply mix in a bowl, and you’re ready to go!\nYou can also chill overnight or for a few hours. \n\n<iframe width="560" height="349" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/hiDveSRLppA?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'VIDEO: Easter Spinach Dip', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'yogurt-spinach-dip', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1027', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1031, 3, '2011-08-05 05:00:16', '2011-08-05 12:00:16', 'Protein helps you stay satiated longer and avoid dips in blood sugar levels that are typical when your diet is based on simple carbs. The following high-protein snacks are quick, easy, tasty, and will help you last until the next meal, avoiding unnecessary cravings. \n\n1. Half a cup of 2% cottage cheese with 1 cup fresh fruit. This filling snack contains about 150 calories and 16 grams of protein. \n\n2. One can of tuna in water, mixed with ¼ cup Voskos Nonfat Greek Yogurt and chopped green onions, on a thin slice of whole wheat bread.  250 super satisfying calories, and about 30 grams of protein! \n\n3. A slice of whole wheat bread, spread with one tablespoon peanut butter and topped with a sliced banana. 250 calories, 5 grams protein, and the fat in the peanut butter will keep you satiated forever.  \n\n4. <img src="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/YOGREEK_STRAWBERRY.jpg" alt="" title="YOGREEK_STRAWBERRY" width="60" height="60" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1036" /><a href="http://yogreek.com/">YoGreek yogurt snack</a> is easy and delicious. It contains 140 calories and 11 grams of protein. \n\n5. 2 servings of low fat string cheese with ¼ cup dried fruit (such as raisins).  250 calories, 12 grams protein, and a winning combination of salty and sweet. \n\n6. <img src="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/PB.jpg" alt="" title="PB" width="60" height="47" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1042" /> A tablespoon of peanut butter, softened in microwave, mixed into half a cup Voskos Nonfat Greek Yogurt, and topped with a small sliced banana. About 250 calories, 17 grams protein.\n\n7. Scrambled eggs, made with 1 whole egg and 2 egg whites and scrambled in a nonstick skillet sprayed with nonstick spray, then wrapped in a low-carb, high-protein tortilla (such as those made by La Tortilla Factory) with a tablespoon of salsa. The tortilla has 8 grams protein and 80 calories, the eggs add 10 grams of protein and 105 calories, the salsa adds maybe 10 calories (and healthy lycopene!) Total for this snack: about 200 calories and 18 grams protein. \n\n8. Half a cup hummus, served with celery and carrot sticks (about 1 cup veggies).  250 calories, 10 grams protein. \n\n9. <img src="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/smoothie.jpg" alt="" title="smoothie" width="60" height="43" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1040" />The perfect summer snack: a fruit and yogurt smoothie, made with Voskos Nonfat Greek Yogurt . Our <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/breakfast/pineapple-strawberry-smoothie">Pineapple-Strawberry Dream</a> contains about 150 calories and 8 grams protein per serving. \n\n10. 2 ounces low fat ham, 1 ounce low fat cheddar and a sliced tomato, all rolled inside a low-carb tortilla. 200 calories, 25 grams protein.\n\nEnjoy!', 'Top 10 High Protein Snacks', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'high-protein-snacks', '', '', '2011-08-05 05:00:16', '2011-08-05 12:00:16', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1031', 0, 'post', '', 4),
