(1157, 3, '2011-11-09 05:00:47', '2011-11-09 12:00:47', 'Thanksgiving is a challenge! According to the Calorie Control Council, the average American consumes more than 4,500 calories and a whopping 229 grams of fat on Thanksgiving. That''s more than twice the amount of calories and three times the amount of fat most of us should consume in a day.\n\nWe at Voskos think holidays are a time to splurge, and that if you eat right most of the time, it''s OK to indulge on occasion. But since Thanksgiving starts a season of holidays and celebrations, it''s important that we learn to manage this day - and the entire season - in a way that won''t cause too much damage to our weight and to our health. \n\nWe believe that the best way to handle Thanksgiving is to allow yourself to eat more - but not to the point of stuffing yourself with so much food that you feel bloated and almost sick (sounds familiar? Been there, done that!)\n\nHere are a few tips to help you manage Thanksgiving:\n\n1. <strong>Don''t skip breakfast, but keep it light</strong>. Skipping breakfast and arriving at the Thanksgiving dinner starved will make you eat more, not less. So eat a wholesome breakfast that includes protein and fiber. \n\n2.<strong> Exercise.</strong> You should always exercise of course, but on Thanksgiving day, if you can manage 30 minutes to an hour of activity (walking counts!), the calories you burn will help offset some of the extra calories you will consume. \n\n3. <strong>Make or bring a lighter option</strong>. If you''re hosting, try to include lighter fare in your meal, including a platter of fresh-cut veggies with low fat dressing, and using Voskos Greek Yogurt instead of mayonnaise, butter or sour cream in creamy dips, mashed potatoes, and casseroles. If you''re a guest, volunteer to bring a low-calorie dish. \n\n4. <strong>Watch your portions</strong>. It''s fine to try everything on the table - as long as you take just a tablespoon of mashed potatoes or a sliver of the pies. In fact, one of the best ways to enjoy your meal, feel satisfied and keep calories in check is to fill your plate with a taste of everything you want to try, and avoid going for seconds. You should also drink lots of water with your meal, and try to limit alcohol consumption to one glass of wine. \n\n5. <strong>Take your time</strong>. Eating slowly, putting your fork down between bites, and savoring each bite are all great ways to truly enjoy your meal and feel satisfied with one plateful of food. \n\nOf course, it''s important to be realistic. This is a holiday, after all, and a big part of it is centered around food. A reasonable goal during Thanksgiving - and the holiday season - would be to maintain your weight. Trying to lose weight during this month might prove to be too difficult - and frankly, we''re not sure it''s worth it. ', 'Giving Thanks? Yes. Gaining Five Pounds? No!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'giving-thanks-yes-gaining-five-pounds-no', '', '', '2011-11-09 05:00:47', '2011-11-09 12:00:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1157', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1164, 3, '2011-11-16 05:00:14', '2011-11-16 12:00:14', 'In the spirit of the season, of giving thanks and being grateful, I thought it would be fun to compile a list of the things we love most about Thanksgiving. \n\n1. <strong>Family time</strong>, especially spending time with family members that I rarely get to see. Sure, they can be annoying at times, and the whole big-family-dynamic can get old fast... but for a few precious hours, being part of this large, noisy group, is just so much fun!\n\n2. <strong>The Thanksgiving table</strong>. Thanksgiving tables have a way of looking so festive. When I host, I love to mix different serving pieces - some from my grandmothers, and some that I have purchased over the years. I love the way all the pieces look together, and I love the memories they bring.\n\n3. <strong>Pecan pie</strong>! Any pie actually, pumpkin included, but pecan pie is a big favorite around here. \n\n4. <strong>Leftovers</strong>, enjoyed for at least a week and in so many ways - just heated up on a plate, in sandwiches, in quesadillas... mmm I just love turkey quesadillas! \n\n5. <strong>Memories</strong>: Cherishing old memories with old family members, and creating new ones for the younger generation. \n\n6. <strong>Pumpkin cheesecake</strong>, especially when lightened up with Greek yogurt (<a href="http://www.healthyfoodforliving.com/?p=14862" target="_blank">here''s</a> a great recipe). \n\n7. <strong>The official start of the holiday season</strong>. There''s something festive in the air on Thanksgiving... it''s not just the holiday itself, but the start of an entire month of festivities.  \n\n8. <strong>Thanksgiving Day NFL games</strong>. Just as much a part of Thanksgiving as turkey and pumpkin pie!\n\n9. Making tasty, fragrant <strong>turkey soup</strong> with the leftover turkey carcass.\n\n10. My own family''s Thanksgiving tradition of lighting up the fireplace and eating <strong>pumpkin pancakes for breakfast.</strong>\n\nWhat do you love most about Thanksgiving?\n\nPhoto credit: <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/49651178@N00/2078620193/in/photostream/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">museinthecity</a>\n', '10 Things We Love About Thanksgiving', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'things-we-love-about-thanksgiving', '', '', '2011-11-16 05:00:14', '2011-11-16 12:00:14', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1164', 0, 'post', '', 0),
