(1280, 3, '2011-07-03 09:19:20', '2011-07-03 16:19:20', 'It’s finally summer time and the 4th of July is just around the corner! Every year my family has a BBQ to celebrate and today I’m going to share one of our recipes that’s a firework of flavor.  \n\nWelcome back to Mary’s Kitchen! Today I’ll be showing you all how to make some mouthwatering sliders, topped with a chipotle coleslaw. Trust me, once your guests have a bite of these, it’ll have them fighting over the last one.\n\nNow, this recipe serves 12, so you can cute everything in half if you have a smaller crowd to feed. \n\n<strong>Ingredients </strong>\n1 pkg of mini burger buns\n1 lb Ground Beef\n6-7 cups of shredded red and green cabbage\n2 tbsps of canned chipotle\n1 tsp salt\n1 tbsp original molasses\n7 green onions, thinly sliced\n1 8oz container of Plain Voskos Greek Yogurt\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nWith the ground beef, you can get creative and marinate it however you like. I used 1 teaspoon season salt, ½ tsp black pepper, 1 small chopped onion, and 2 cloves of garlic.  Shape the meat into little patties that will correspond with the buns you purchased and grill them for about 5-6 minutes on each side over medium heat.  \n\nI would suggest making the slaw beforehand so you can chill it while you’re grilling. As for the coleslaw, instead of using ½ a cup of sour cream and mayonnaise, you guessed it, we’ll be using plain Voskos Greek Yogurt. Add the 2 tbsps of chipotle adobo sauce, you can add more if you like it really spicy, the salt, the molasses and stir it all together. Add the green onions to the cabbage then the Voskos mixture and stir. \n\nWhat’s great about this recipe is, since we’re using voskos instead of mayo and sour cream, which combined would be about 704 calories, you’ll be consuming only 280 with Voskos. Once you’ve finished mixing everything, top it on your sliders and let the compliments flow in! \n\n<iframe width="560" height="349" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/Vjv_979ZQj0?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', '4th of July Sliders', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', '4th-of-july-sliders', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1280', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1296, 3, '2012-02-02 17:04:34', '2012-02-03 00:04:34', 'Watching the Superbowl doesn''t have to mean overeating, or eating junk. Here are some healthy, delicious, EASY super bowl snack ideas. \n\n1. Our very own <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/appetizers/avocado-yogurt-dip-with-cumin">avocado-yogurt sip with cumin</a>. Avocado contains healthy oils, and the yogurt adds protein and reduces the number of calories in each serving. \n\n2. White bean dip made with mashed white beans, olive oil, garlic and salt. You need just a little bit of olive oil to dress the beans, and you''ll enjoy the good fats in olive oil and avoid the extra calories and saturated fats in sour-cream-based dips. \n\n3. Kale chips. You can buy them at stores such as Whole Foods, or make your own - simply toss clean, dry leaves with olive oil, sprinkle with salt and bake 20 minutes in a 400-degree oven.\n\n4. Baked onion rings. Dip the rings in flour, eggs, and breadcrumbs. Spray with olive oil spray and bake at 450 degrees for 20 minutes, turning after 10 minutes.\n\n5. <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/appetizers/greek-yogurt-dip">Voskos touchdown dip</a> is a healthy dip made with Voskos instead of sour cream or mayonnaise.\n\n6. <a href="http://healthyrecipesblogs.com/2011/12/12/baked-cocktail-meatballs/">Baked cocktail meatballs</a> will save you some fat and calories compared with deep-fried meatballs. \n\n7. When making sandwiches, use mustard instead of mayo and pile on the veggies instead of cheese. An open-face sandwich will save you calories and carbs, and will taste better, than a traditional sandwich. \n\n8. Crispy garbanzo beans make another great alternative to potato chips. Toss drained, dried garbanzo beans with olive oil and salt. Spread on a rimmed baking sheet lined with foil. Bake 30 minutes at 400 degrees F, shaking pan midway to ensure even browning. \n\n9. If you plan to order pizza, order a skinny-crust pizza with lots of veggies. \n\n10. Low-fat microwave popcorn is a great snack. For some extra flavor, sprinkle just a tablespoon of grated Parmesan on top. ', '10 Healthy Super Bowl Snacks', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-super-bowl-snacks', '', '', '2012-02-02 17:04:34', '2012-02-03 00:04:34', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1296', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1302, 12, '2012-02-08 13:54:16', '2012-02-08 20:54:16', '<em>This is a guest post by Nikko Generales B.S., EMT-B</em>\n\nIt was truly love at first site when honey first came into contact with Voskos’s Plain Greek Yogurt. It was as if all the stars became aligned and wedding bells rang in perfect harmony. This was truly a match made in heaven. \n\nYou see unbeknownst to them, honey and Voskos’s Plain Greek Yogurt actually share many of the same health benefits. This is surely what solidified their romance into a full-blown marriage that will undoubtedly last a lifetime. \n	\nTheir relationship stems from the fact that they both work to synergistically improve gastro-intestinal health. Eating Voskos’s Plain Greek Yogurt may help to increase the amount of probiotic bacteria in your stomach. Probiotics play a critical role in carbohydrate and lipid metabolism, endocrine function, and inflammation.1 By enhancing the health of your gastro-intestinal system, probiotics may work to improve “lactose intolerance, cancer, allergies, hepatic disease, Helicobacter pylori infections, urinary tract infections, and hyperlipidemia.”2 Probiotics can also help to lower serum cholesterol levels.2\n	\nFor the benefits of probiotics to be effective however, they need to be fed the proper nutrients. This is where honey shines in the relationship. Honey is largely made up of the monosaccharides (simple sugars) fructose and glucose.1 These sugars are readily broken down in the stomach and made available for absorption in the small intestine.1 Honey also contains oligosaccharides and polysaccharides, which are regarded as “pre-biotics” because they stimulate “the growth and/or activity of one or a limited number of bacteria in the colon, thus improving host health”.1 Because they are resistant to the acidic nature of the stomach, and therefore are not metabolized as quickly, oligosaccharides and polysaccharides are vital nutrients to microflora in the gut.1 Consequently, eating honey with yogurt may cooperatively help in improving the number and health of probiotic bacteria in your gut. \n	\nThe benefits of honey don’t stop there! The oligosaccharides in honey may exhibit antidiabetic effects, and help stabilize blood glucose levels.1 \n\n\nA study performed on diabetic patients demonstrated “improved lipid metabolism,” as well as a decrease in serum triglyceride and LDL-cholesterol levels.1 Furthermore, some studies have reported that oligosaccharides can increase the feeling of satiety and thus compliment a weight-loss program.1 \n	\nSo what should you do to help jumpstart your new years resolution to live a healthier lifestyle. Aim to eat 5.3oz of Voskos Organic Greek Honey Yogurt three times a week with your breakfast or in the afternoon as a power snack. For added benefit I would recommend eating a tablespoon of 100% raw buckwheat honey with this yogurt. Throw in some organic berries and almonds and you’ve got yourself one powerful breakfast. \n\nTry this out and let me know what you think! \n\n<strong>References</strong>\n1. Erejuwa O, Sulaiman S, Ab Wahab M. 2011. Oligosaccharides might contribute to the antidiabetic effect of honey: A review of the literature. Molecules 17: 248-266. \n\n2. Ejtahed H.S., Mohtadi-Nia J, Homayouni-Rad A, Niafar M, Asghari-Jafarabadi M, Mofid V, Akbarian-Moghari A. 2011. Effect of probiotic yogurt containing lactobacillus acidophilus and bifidobacterium lactis on lipid profile in individuals with type 2 diabetes mellitus. J. Dairy Sci 94: 3288-3294.\n', 'When Honey Met Voskos', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'when-honey-met-voskos', '', '', '2012-02-08 13:54:16', '2012-02-08 20:54:16', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1302', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(1307, 3, '2011-07-21 12:18:30', '2011-07-21 19:18:30', 'Before we know it the kids will be back in school. For some that''s good, for others that''s bad. It''s always a hard transition after a fun summer being home. Less time playing with friends and as a family and more time in the classroom.\n\nFor me back to school means back to our old daily routine. Up early. Struggle to get my little guy out of bed, dressed, and downstairs for breakfast. Fight him to brush his teeth and wash his face while I pack his lunch. Load the bags, and then off for school. Like clockwork - every morning.\n\nThen that same little kiddo who wanted to have nothing to do with breakfast comes home exhausted--and starving! He goes straight to the refrigerator and searches high and low to see what''s there. Then the freezer. Then the pantry. He''s looking for anything ready-made. Sweet or salty - it doesn''t matter. He just wants something fast.\n\nI''m guessing this sounds familiar.\n\nWith me being a health-food "junkie", I''m constantly looking for healthy snacks and treats that he wants. I look for things he craves and will "hopefully" choose over other less-healthy options.\nBetter yet? I look for snacks and treats that we can make together.\n\nI love this particular super easy recipe because its not only healthy, it tastes like a treat, and it''s something we can do together. My grade-schooler could make on his own if it really came down to it. Made with nutritious fruit and high protein Voskos Greek yogurt, you''re getting a balanced snack that''s fun to make and yummy to eat!\n\nHere''s the recipe, and a step by step featuring my son, Dakota:\n\n<h3>Super Easy Frozen Yogurt Pops</h3>\n\nMakes 5 small popsicles\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 cup nonfat VOSKOS nonfat Greek yogurt\n2 tbs sugar free or regular honey, agave or stevia (if using stevia you''ll need less)\n1/2 cup berries (we used 1/4 cup blueberries and 1/4 cup assorted strawberries and blackberries)\n5 small throw-away cups\n5 popsicle sticks\n5 pieces foil\n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1366.jpg"><img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1366.jpg" alt="" title="DSCN1366" width="480" height="360" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1308" /></a>\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Combine yogurt and sweetener of choice in a small bowl.\n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1370.jpg"><img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1370.jpg" alt="" title="DSCN1370" width="480" height="344" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1309" /></a>\n\n2. Mash 1/2 cup of berries using a fork. Scrape bowl and add to the yogurt mixture. Stir.\n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1375.jpg"><img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1375.jpg" alt="" title="DSCN1375" width="480" height="343" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1310" /></a>\n\n3. Spoon yogurt in to individual cups. Add blueberries and press down (roughly 3-5 each cup).\n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1377.jpg"><img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1377.jpg" alt="" title="DSCN1377" width="480" height="343" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1311" /></a>\n\n4. Cut foil in squares large enough to cover and wrap over top of each cup. Poke hole in center of each foil and add Popsicle stick.\n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1381.jpg"><img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1381.jpg" alt="" title="DSCN1381" width="480" height="343" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1312" /></a>\n\n5. Place Popsicles in freezer for 3-4 hours to harden or until ready to eat. When frozen solid, peel cup from yogurt pop.\n\n<a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1384.jpg"><img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/DSCN1384.jpg" alt="" title="DSCN1384" width="480" height="343" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1313" /></a>\n\nNote: I''ve tried to do these in regular cups and Popsicle molds, but with yogurt they don''t come out easily from hard cups if at all. The paper cups are a nice option because they peel right off. \n\nNutrition with HONEY:\nCalories 87\nTotal Fat 0.3g\nSodium 19mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 16.8g\nDietary Fiber 2.25g\nSugars 13g\nProtein 5.45g\n\nNutrition with STEVIA: \nCalories 63\nTotal Fat 0.3g\nCholesterol 3mg\nSodium 19mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 10g\nDietary Fiber 2.65g\nSugars 6.6g\nProtein 5.45g', 'Frozen Yogurt Pops', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'frozen-yogurt-pops', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1307', 0, 'post', '', 5),
(1309, 12, '2012-02-28 05:00:23', '2012-02-28 12:00:23', 'February is Heart Month—and a great time to add heart-healthy Greek yogurt to your diet.\n\n(Sun Valley, Calif.) February 21, 2012 – According to the American Heart Association, cardiovascular disease is America''s number one cause of death. Approximately 2,200 Americans die from cardiovascular disease every day. \n\nDuring February, Americans are encouraged to emphasize heart health by exercising and eating a healthier diet—and Voskos Greek Yogurt can be a part of that, says personal trainer Nikko Generales. \n\n“The first thing everyone should be doing is making an honest attempt at becoming more physically active,” says Generales. “Aim to get at least 30 minutes of physical activity in every day.”\nGenerales continues, “The second and most obvious measure for heart health is eating smarter. One of the most important things you can do is eliminate empty calories by cutting down on sodas, cakes, cookies, candies, and other sugary desserts. Removing refined carbohydrates from your diet can help you lower your cholesterol, lose weight, and thus lower your risk of heart disease.” \n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt can help with this goal in several ways. “Because it''s high in protein and calcium, Greek yogurt makes you feel full longer, to help you cut down on unhealthy snacking,” says Generales. Unlike most snacks, Voskos Greek Yogurt is nutrient rich. And finally, says Generales, “a diet that includes yogurt has been linked with weight loss in several clinical studies. And obesity is a risk factor for heart disease, so by losing weight, you also reduce your risk of heart disease.”\n\n“My favorite snack is Voskos Greek Yogurt Plus Granola,” Generales continues. It provides the perfect balance of healthy carbohydrates and protein to keep you going. The next time you feel like reaching for that candy bar, try Voskos Greek Yogurt Plus Granola. My favorite flavor is Strawberry Crunch. It really hits the spot after a tough workout or a long day at work. It has zero grams of saturated fat, zero milligrams of cholesterol, and eleven grams of protein! This is a heart-¬‐healthy option that won’t disappoint when it comes to flavor.” \nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. Visit Voskos'' Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes for low-carbohydrate breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks.\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt </strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos is the only brand to offer an organic Greek yogurt line in addition to its all-natural plain and blended flavors and never has “fruit on the bottom.” Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in such stores as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations, and to download a coupon, visit Voskos.com or Facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt today. \n', 'Greek Yogurt: Good for your Waistline & for your Heart Health', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-good-for-your-waistline-and-for-your-heart-health', '', '', '2012-02-28 05:00:23', '2012-02-28 12:00:23', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1309', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1313, 12, '2012-02-29 05:00:15', '2012-02-29 12:00:15', 'Don''t spend a fortune combatting dry winter skin! You can enjoy a softer, plumper, glowingly hydrated complexion with an inexpensive product that is already in your refrigerator.\n\n(Sun Valley, Calif.) February 28, 2012 –  Are you suffering from dry winter skin? You can get natural relief without expensive beauty products. “Relief for your dry skin may be as close as your refrigerator,” says Emily Neukircher, the marketing manager for Voskos Greek Yogurt, America''s first nationally-distributed Greek Yogurt brand.\n\n“Many expensive moisturizers and facial creams contain lactic acid, which is found naturally in Greek yogurt,” says Neukircher. “Lactic acid is a gentle exfoliant. Adding a natural moisturizer like honey helps rehydrate dry skin.” \n\nThis simple face mask recipe contains just two ingredients, and is perfect for soothing dry winter complexions. It''s easy to apply first thing in the morning, and remove in the shower.\n\n<strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt Honey Mask</strong>\n\n1 Tablespoon Plain Organic Voskos Greek Yogurt\n1 Tablespoon Organic Honey\n\nAdd honey to a small microwave-safe bowl, and microwave for just a few seconds, until it is warmed to approximately body temperature and becomes runny.\n\nRemove bowl from microwave and stir in Voskos Greek yogurt. Blend until just mixed. \n\nApply to cleansed face (avoiding eyes) and allow to sit on your skin for 15 minutes. During the last 5 minutes, you can get into the shower and allow the steam to help moisturize your skin even more.\n\nRemove mask with a warm, damp washcloth.\n\n“This natural moisturizing mask can help you combat the dull, dry skin that comes from heated indoor air this time of year,” says Neukircher. “And if you eat the rest of the yogurt, from the container, it will help you feel as good on the inside as you look on the outside!”\n\nGreek yogurt is thicker and creamier than regular yogurt, and contains a number of probiotics—naturally occurring friendly bacteria that are present in our digestive systems. Some research has linked probiotics to healthy digestion and regularity. \n\nEating Greek yogurt may be even more important during “flu season.” In a study, people who ate two cups of live-culture yogurt every day for three months produced higher levels of immunity-boosting interferon. The probiotics in yogurt have also been shown to stimulate the production of infection-fighting white blood cells.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. Visit Voskos'' Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes for low-carbohydrate breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks.\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt </strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos is the only brand to offer an organic Greek yogurt line in addition to its all-natural plain and blended flavors and never has “fruit on the bottom.” Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in such stores as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations, and to download a coupon, visit Voskos.com or Facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt today. \n', 'End Dry Skin Naturally with a Voskos Greek Yogurt Facial', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dry-skin-greek-yogurt-facial', '', '', '2012-02-29 05:00:15', '2012-02-29 12:00:15', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1313', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1317, 3, '2012-03-14 05:00:48', '2012-03-14 12:00:48', 'So yes, spring is approaching fast, but we''re not here today to recommend a new diet in anticipation of summer. You see, we don''t believe in diets. We do believe in healthful, mindful eating. We believe in making wise food choices (most of the time), avoiding excess food, eating slowly and savoring each bite. \n\nBut a diet, in the sense of restricting your calories and/or your food choices for several weeks or months until you lose an X amount of pounds? Bad idea. \n\nDieting is a bad idea for several reasons:\n1. It encourages cravings. As soon as you declare a certain food a forbidden food, you start craving it.\n2. A too-restrictive diet may cause your body to slow down its metabolism. This will make losing weight even more difficult.\n3. Frequent dieting, and especially yo-yo dieting, may mess up your metabolism for life, making it increasingly harder to shed pounds. \n4. Many diets lack in terms of nutrition, especially diets that restrict a certain food group such as carbs. \n5. Research shows that most dieters eventually fail, gaining what they had lost, and then some. \n\nThe bottom line is, our bodies do not react very well to diets. Even though we are surrounded by food, evolution has been slow to catch up, and our bodies are still hardwired to do whatever they can to hold on to food and avoid starvation. Since most diets feel like starvation to our bodies, going on a diet is like declaring a war on your body, and trust us, you don''t want to do that!\n\nIf you need to lose weight, especially if you need to do so for medical reasons, a much better bet is to make gradual changes to your lifestyle. Focus on one change each month. For example, in March, lower your soda consumption to one can per day. Weather you''re used to drinking sugared soda or diet soda, both can be bad for your weight and for your health, so this is the first thing you should aim to cut.\n\nNext, in April focus on a new goal, such as eating more servings of fruit and veggies each day, or limiting fast food visits to once a month. \n\nWhatever you do, don''t look at these changes as temporary. Your goal is to rid yourself of bad habits, and adopt healthy habits, for life. Also, don''t look at this as an all-or-nothing resolution! Even if you drink an extra can of soda one day, this is not a "failure" and not a reason to throw away your good habits for the rest of that day (or week, or month). The occasional indulgence is fine - after all, if you''re going to do this for the rest of your life, you have to be flexible. ', 'Spring is Almost Here! Time for a New Diet?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'spring-is-almost-here-time-for-a-new-diet', '', '', '2012-03-14 05:00:48', '2012-03-14 12:00:48', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1317', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1321, 3, '2011-07-25 10:32:57', '2011-07-25 17:32:57', 'This recipe is perfect if you want to lay back, relax and cool off on a hot summer day.\n\nMakes 4 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 Cups Diced Pineapple\n1/2 Cup Hulled Strawberries\n1 Cup Milk\n1 Cup Crushed Ice\n1 Cup Non-Fat Plain Voskos Greek Yogurt\n3 Tablespoons superfine sugar\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Mix together the first four ingredients in a blender, until smooth.\n2. Add the sugar and Voskos Greek yogurt and pulse some more, until well blended. \n3. Enjoy!\n\n<iframe width="560" height="349" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/PAVghJ12l9k?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'Pineapple-Strawberry Dream ', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'pineapple-strawberry-smoothie', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1321', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1325, 12, '2012-03-27 05:00:41', '2012-03-27 12:00:41', 'Blueberries and Greek yogurt have both been linked to weight loss in clinical studies. \n\n(Sun Valley, California) March 22, 2012 - For some time, researchers have known about the link between yogurt and losing weight. A 2005 study published in the International Journal of Obesity showed that dieters eating a low-calorie, high-calcium diet that included yogurt lost 81% more belly fat than dieters on a low-calcium diet. And their overall weight loss was 22% higher than the control group.\n\nThe other good news from that study? The dieters who ate yogurt burned more fat, and lost less lean muscle mass.\n\nIn 2011, a graduate student from Texas Women’s University found that the antioxidants in blueberries inhibited the development of fat cells in mouse tissues. The student, Shiwani Moghe, MS, discovered that blueberry polyphenols may actually inhibit fat gain at the molecular level. And the higher the dose of polyphenols, the greater the reduction of fat content in the tissue sample, according to the research presented at the Experimental Biology 2011 meeting. Blueberry phytochemicals have also been shown to help alleviate high blood sugar in animal studies. High blood sugar is a risk factor in cardiovascular disease and diabetes.\n\nMore advantages of blueberries, beyond their high antioxidant content? “Blueberries are relatively low in carbohydrates and high in fiber compared to other fruits,” says registered dietitian Janet R. Mertz.\n\nSo, what does this mean? “If you want to lose weight, you can’t go wrong by combining Voskos Greek Yogurt and blueberries,” says registered dietitian Janet R, Mertz. Of course, Voskos offers a pre-mixed non-fat wild Blueberry Greek yogurt flavor, and a Blueberry + Granola variety. “But you can also make your own version by combining Voskos plain Greek yogurt with frozen wild blueberries, found in the fruit section of your grocery’s freezer case,” says Mertz. Wild blueberries are highest in antioxidant capacity per serving, compared with more than 20 other fruits, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. Visit the Voskos Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes for high-protein, low-carbohydrate breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks.\n\nAbout Voskos Greek Yogurt \nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos offers an organic Greek yogurt line and all-natural line in both plain and blended flavors. Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in stores such as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations, visit Voskos.com or Facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt today. \n\nAbout Janet R. Mertz, R.D.\nJanet R. Mertz is a diabetes educator, wife of a Type-1 diabetic and mom who believes that healthy eating and health can go together.', 'Blueberries & Voskos Greek Yogurt: Partners in Weight Loss', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'blueberries-voskos-greek-yogurt-partners-in-weight-loss', '', '', '2012-03-27 05:00:41', '2012-03-27 12:00:41', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1325', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(1330, 12, '2012-04-05 05:00:29', '2012-04-05 12:00:29', 'Following the Mediterranean diet, which includes Greek Yogurt, can help weight loss and improve overall health.\n\n(Sun Valley, California) March 22, 2012 - As swimsuit season approaches, many Americans have weight loss on their minds. But what’s even more important than losing inches? Losing pounds. Losing weight can help lower risk factors for deadly conditions such as coronary heart disease (CHD), hypertension, and Type 2 Diabetes.\n\n“Greek Yogurt is one of the many healthful foods that come from the Mediterranean,” says Nikko Generales B.S., a writer for the Voskos Greek Yogurt What’s Fresh blog. “The Mediterranean diet originated in Greece and has been followed by both Athenians and island villagers for centuries. As a result, these people have lower rates of obesity — and thus lower rates of heart disease and hypertension — than those following the typical American diet.” \n\nThe Mediterranean diet includes plenty of fruits and vegetables, nuts, legumes, whole grains, seeds, olive oil, herbs and spices, plus moderate amounts of fish, eggs, and poultry, and small amounts of red meat. Of course, it also includes high-protein Greek yogurt, such as Voskos.\n\n“The benefits of this regimen are clear,” says Generales. “An evaluation of 1.5 million Americans has linked this diet to a decrease in cardiovascular related deaths, a reduction in cancer incidence and mortality rates, as well as a decrease in rates of Parkinson’s and Alzheimer’s diseases.”\n\nThe value of Greek yogurt in the Mediterranean diet seems to come from the probiotic bacteria, which have displayed cholesterol-lowering effects in clinical settings. “According to one study,” says Generales, “eating just 200 grams of yogurt containing L. acidophilus, such as that found in Voskos Greek Yogurt, can help decrease serum cholesterol levels by up to 2.9%.”  In other studies, Greek yogurt consumption has been linked to loss of belly fat. “This is the kind of metabolically active fat that is linked to heart disease,” says Generales. “So the fact that Greek yogurt helps you lose belly fat can help improve your heart health as well.”\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. Visit the Voskos Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes for high-protein, low-carbohydrate breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks.\n\nAbout Voskos Greek Yogurt \nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos offers an organic Greek yogurt line and all-natural line in both plain and blended flavors. Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in stores such as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations visit Voskos.com or Facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt today. \n\nAbout Nikko Generales\nNikko’s passion for health and fitness stems from his aspiration to become a physician. He earned his B.S. in Physiology from the University of California, Santa Barbara and is currently working on orphan drug research at the Keck Graduate Institute of Applied Life Sciences. He believes that people should be proactive in asking questions and educating themselves on how to live a healthy lifestyle.', 'Greek Yogurt & Mediterranean Diet: The Recipe for Good Health', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-mediterranean-diet-the-recipe-for-good-health', '', '', '2012-04-05 05:00:29', '2012-04-05 12:00:29', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1330', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1337, 3, '2012-04-11 05:00:57', '2012-04-11 12:00:57', 'My family has started eating healthier over the past two years. It required some adjustments, and especially a change in our old mindset that "healthy is not as tasty," but we''ve pretty much adjusted to our new lifestyle. Crusty whole-wheat breads, brown rice, whole-wheat pasta, more olive oil and less butter, lots of veggies... we love it! Who knew healthy food can taste so good? \n\nThe biggest challenge for me as a mom when making the switch was my ten-year-old daughter. She''s a notoriously picky eater, and can spot a "healthified" version of her favorite foods from a mile away.  Once she does, it''s very difficult to convince her to give it a try. But even with her, persistence has paid off. Here are some of the snacks she willingly eats these days:\n\n1. <strong>Greek yogurt with fruit</strong>. The secret here seems to be to whip the yogurt using a hand whisk until it''s light and fluffy. I put it in a pretty bowl, drizzle with a little honey and dot with berries. She loves it, and actually prefers it to the watery, overly-sweet yogurt she used to like.\n\n2. <strong>Dips</strong>. Dips are fun and interesting for kids, and it''s so easy to make homemade yogurt-based dips. For a savory dip, mix the yogurt with salt, pepper, cumin, chili powder and cilantro. For a slightly sweet dip, mix it with peanut butter and jelly, or with Nutella. Honey and cinnamon mixed with Greek yogurt also make a great dip, and your child will love dipping fruit, veggies or chips into those healthy dips.\n\n3. <strong>Part-whole-wheat baked goods</strong>. This took some time, but after a few months of gradually introducing homemade muffins made with half whole-wheat flour, and rice made with half white and half brown rice, my kids now happily eat whole-wheat baked goods, brown rice and whole-wheat pasta. Eating whole-wheat is truly a matter of habit, and in fact, many people (big and small) report that once they got used to the chewy texture and heartiness of whole-wheat, the fluffiness of white flour seemed empty and unsatisfying. \n\nOne more tip: When you make your own baked goods, it''s almost always safe to reduce the amount of sugar in the recipe. Most modern recipes contain way too much sugar. So try reducing the amount of sugar by a third, and see what happens. Chances are, no one will ever miss it!', '3 Healthy Snacks Your Kids will Love', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '3-healthy-snacks-your-kids-will-love', '', '', '2012-04-11 05:00:57', '2012-04-11 12:00:57', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1337', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1350, 3, '2012-04-22 09:00:50', '2012-04-22 16:00:50', 'Today, Earth Day, we''d like to hear from you:\n\nWhat do you do to help keep Earth clean?\n\nPlease share in the comments below. Tonight, at 7pm PDT, we will select five random winners to receive a Voskos reusable tote. \n\n*<a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/contest-rules">Voskos Contest Rules</a> apply to this promotion, as to all our promotions.\n\n--\nWe used random.org to pull the names of five winners and here they are: Jennifer L. , Kristy Boneventre, Molly Dunfee, Karrie Kleba and Val Gates. Congrats! Please email us at social (at) voskos.com with your full name, date of birth (just the year) and full mailing address. Thanks!', 'Keeping Earth Clean', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'earth-day-2012', '', '', '2012-04-22 09:00:50', '2012-04-22 16:00:50', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1350', 0, 'post', '', 47),
(1357, 3, '2012-04-20 05:00:16', '2012-04-20 12:00:16', '<em>Voskos Greek Yogurt demonstrates its commitment to sustainability by producing 100% organic, GMO-free Greek yogurt, sold in 100% recyclable packaging.</em>\n\n(Sun Valley, California) April 18, 2012 - Since the first “National day of observance of environmental problems” in 1970, Americans have gathered on Earth Day to raise awareness of issues affecting the environment. And more than thirty years later, Earth Day has truly become a global phenomenon, uniting hundreds of millions of people in over 175 countries.\n\nAs a company with an international heritage and a commitment to the environment, “Every day is Earth Day at Voskos Greek Yogurt,” says Nikko Generales B.S., a writer for the Voskos Greek Yogurt What’s Fresh blog. “Voskos Greek Yogurt offers organic flavors in plain, Greek honey, and vanilla bean. And they make all of their yogurt flavors naturally, with no artificial sweeteners, flavors, colors or preservatives,” says Generales. “Voskos products are also free of gluten, rBST, rBGH, and GMOs.” \n\nThere are several things Voskos encourages its customers to do for the environment in honor of Earth Day:\n\n1.<strong> Buy locally-grown and sustainable products whenever possible</strong>.\n“Read the labels on your produce,” says Generales. “If you live in the United States and your plums came from Peru, imagine how much fuel was burned to get that fruit into your local produce department. Shopping locally means less fuel consumption and less pollution.”\n\n2.<strong> Buy organic products whenever possible.</strong>\nWhile there are a number of different “organic” certification standards, generally “organic” produce is grown without pesticides and other chemicals. “Pesticides, of course, are meant to kill insects,” notes Generales. “So it’s no surprise that they can kill beneficial insects like honeybees and ladybugs along with unwanted pests. And many chemical pesticides contain neurotoxins that can be dangerous (or even deadly) to the people who have to handle them.”\n\n3. <strong>Buy products in recyclable packaging and recycle when finished</strong>.\n“Recycling is a crucial step you can take to help preserve the environment. That’s why all of Voskos yogurt cups are recyclable-so you can still enjoy a tasty and healthy cup of yogurt while being environmentally conscious.” \n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. Visit the Voskos Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes for high-protein, low-carbohydrate breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks.\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt </strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos offers an organic Greek yogurt line and all-natural line in both plain and blended flavors. Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in stores such as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations and other great opportunities visit Facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt today.\n\n<strong>About Nikko Generales</strong>\nNikko’s passion for health and fitness stems from his aspiration to become a physician. He earned his B.S. in Physiology from the University of California, Santa Barbara and is currently working on orphan drug research at the Keck Graduate Institute of Applied Life Sciences. He believes that people should be proactive in asking questions and educating themselves on how to live a healthy lifestyle.', 'At Voskos Greek Yogurt, Every Day is Earth Day', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-every-day-is-earth-day', '', '', '2012-04-20 05:00:16', '2012-04-20 12:00:16', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1357', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1367, 3, '2011-08-23 09:59:24', '2011-08-23 16:59:24', 'Who said coleslaw can''t be healthy?\n\nServes 8 / 30 Minutes\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n4 green onions\n1/2 head napa cabbage, sliced thinly\n1/2 head red cabbage, sliced thinly\n1/2 cup cilantro leaves\n2 limes\n1/2 cup VOSKOS nonfat Greek yogurt\n1TBS olive oil\n1 tsp. sugar\n1 tsp. kosher salt\n1 tsp. pepper\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Toss together onions, cabbages, and cilantro in a large bowl.\n2. Zest both limes and juice 1 lime.  \n3. In a bowl, mix lime zest and juice, yogurt, oil, sugar, salt, and pepper. \n4. Pour dressing over cabbage mixture; stir to combine.\n\n<strong>Nutrition </strong>\nPer 1-Cup Serving:\n45 calories\n2% (1 Cal) from Fat \n2.9 G  Protein \n0.1 G  Fat (0 G Sat) \n9.5 G  Carbs \n(2.2 G Fiber)\n286 MG  Sodium\n0 MG  Cholesterol', 'Creamy Lime Slaw', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-coleslaw', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1367', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1369, 3, '2012-04-29 07:00:59', '2012-04-29 14:00:59', 'Voskos Greek Yogurt demonstrates its commitment to fighting cancer by donating delicious Greek yogurt and tote bags to each of the 50,000 participants in <a href="http://do.eifoundation.org/site/PageNavigator/2012_runwalk_splash.html" target="_blank">The EIF Revlon Run/Walk For Women</a>.\n\n(Sun Valley, California)  April 29, 2012 - Voskos has been in the forefront of healthful eating for 5 years, “and because a number of studies have linked the probiotics in yogurt and calcium consumption to cancer prevention, it’s only natural for Voskos Greek Yogurt to support The Entertainment Industry Foundation Revlon Run/Walk For Women,” says Susan Randolph, a registered dietitian and contributor to the Voskos Greek Yogurt What’s Fresh blog. \n\nScheduled on May 12, 2012 in Los Angeles, the annual EIF Revlon Run/Walk For Women has distributed over sixty million dollars to increase awareness, education, research, and diagnostic treatment services in the fight against women''s cancers since its debut in 1994.\n\nVoskos Greek Yogurt is supporting the estimated 50,000 women and men who are taking part in the event by providing each of them with a gift of a 5.3-ounce serving of high-calcium Voskos Greek Yogurt, and a free tote bag.\n\n“As a woman, I appreciate the work the Entertainment Industry Foundation does in presenting the Revlon Run/Walk for Women,” says Randolph. “Knowing that more than 273,000 new cases of womens’ cancers will be diagnosed every year in the U.S. makes this cause that much more compelling. Voskos is honored to support the women and men who are taking part in this important event.”\n\n“Yogurt has often been referred to as a ‘superfood,’” adds Randolph. “Several studies show a correlation between calcium and probiotic intake and a reduction of cancer rates. In the Nurses’ Health Study, women who reported a high-calcium diet reduced their risk of breast cancer by an amazing 33 percent! Another preliminary study has linked consumption of digestion-friendly Acidophilus bacteria to lower cancer risk, apparently because it reduces the conversion of bile acids into carcinogens.” Acidophilus is just one of the active probiotic cultures included in every creamy spoonful of Voskos Greek Yogurt, which is also naturally high in calcium.\nVoskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. Visit the Voskos Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes for high-protein, low-carbohydrate breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks.\n\n<strong>About Voskos Greek Yogurt </strong>\nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Voskos offers an organic Greek yogurt line and all-natural line in both plain and blended flavors. Available nationwide, retailing between $1.49 - $2.99 in stores such as Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations and other great opportunities visit Facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt today.\n\n<strong>About Susan Randolph, MS, RD</strong>\nSusan Randolph is a wellness educator, registered dietitian and wife. Her passion is motivating people to use nutrition to take small, meaningful steps toward a healthier diet and lifestyle. She believes eating ought to be a joyful and delicious experience to be embraced, not dreaded.\n\n<strong>About the EIF Revlon Run/Walk</strong>\nCreated in 1994 by Lilly Tartikoff, Ronald O. Perelman and the Entertainment Industry Foundation, the EIF Revlon Run/Walks, held annually in Los Angeles and New York, have distributed over 60 million dollars in the fight against women''s cancers.\n\n<strong>Photo Credit</strong>\n<a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/72465344@N00/4590526828/in/photostream/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Sha in LA</a>', 'Voskos Supports the EIF Revlon Run/Walk for Women', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-supports-revlon-walk-run', '', '', '2012-04-29 07:00:59', '2012-04-29 14:00:59', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1369', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1375, 3, '2012-05-10 05:00:50', '2012-05-10 12:00:50', 'When we suggested Jess'' delicious, low-fat tuna cakes for Mother''s Day brunch on our <a href="https://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" rel="nofollow">Facebook page</a>, Max was not a fan of the idea. \n\n"Yes, that''s exactly what Mom wants on Mother''s Day: low-fat tuna cakes! I say, give her a pint of Ben & Jerry''s, and let her watch a Project Runway marathon while you clean the house. Now, there''s a present she can get excited about" he posted.\n\nThis got us thinking... CAN you celebrate with healthy food, or is the entire point of celebrating pigging out and forgetting about your diet for one day or for just one special meal?\n\nAn informal poll around the office yielded mixed results. Some of us feel that you can absolutely celebrate while still sticking to your healthy diet. Healthy foods can be delicious - a healthy diet is not about deprivation. So why not serve a tasty, low-cal dish for Mother''s Day brunch? \n\nOthers feel that as long as you stick with a healthy diet most of the time, the occasional splurge is absolutely fine, and in fact beneficial. Maybe not the entire pint of ice cream (you would just feel lousy after consuming so much fat and sugar), but certainly it''s acceptable, for one festive meal, to forget about low-cal, low-fat etc, and to enjoy decadent, fatty, sugary foods. \n\nWhat do you think? Do you try to prepare healthy food on holidays and celebrations, or do you believe that healthy food is for everyday, and on special occasions it''s OK to indulge? Please share in the comments. \n', 'Please Celebrate Responsibly (?)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'please-celebrate-responsibly', '', '', '2012-05-10 05:00:50', '2012-05-10 12:00:50', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1375', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1384, 3, '2012-06-26 05:00:07', '2012-06-26 12:00:07', 'It''s always interesting for us to talk with customers and hear their different points of views. It seems that    when it comes to fat, there are two opposing points of views. The first shows a strong preference towards low-fat foods, the second claiming that fat is in fact good for us and that minimizing our fat consumption should not be the goal. \n\nAs a company, we have chosen to offer a wide range of <a href="http://www.voskos.com/products.php">Greek yogurts</a>, including low fat and fat free options as well as full-fat options. A sentence that''s really caught our attention recently was this: "just because a food has fat doesn''t mean that it''s going to be fattening." This is from a <a href="http://www.npr.org/2011/06/23/137376133/trying-to-lose-weight-study-says-avoid-potatoes" target="_blank">study</a> by the Harvard School of Public Health, and it really gets you thinking. Fat in itself is not necessarily bad, certainly not healthy oils, and even not the fats found in dairy products. Trans fats are of course to be avoided, and so are fatty cuts of meat. But an extremely low-fat diet, more and more health professionals tell us, is not necessarily desirable.\n\nThe bottom line is, as in so many things in life, that moderation is key. You don''t want an extremely low-fat diet, but you also don''t want a diet high in saturated fats, and you definitely want to avoid artery-clogging trans fats. So, as a company, we decided to offer this wide range of products and allow you, the consumer, to make your own choices. Our full-fat, plain yogurt is delicious - add a little honey and it really is like eating a rich, decadent dessert. More and more consumers opt to buy the full-fat yogurt. But we''re offering low fat and fat free products as well, because many of you find that even with low-fat products, you still end up consuming fair amounts of fats per day, and you prefer to keep your fat consumption under control. \n\nWhatever we do, our number one priorities are flavor and health! So whether full fat, low fat or non fat, we make products that are delicious and healthy - products that we enjoy and serve to our own families every day. ', 'Low Fat vs. Full Fat', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'low-fat-vs-full-fat', '', '', '2012-06-26 05:00:07', '2012-06-26 12:00:07', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1384', 0, 'post', '', 4);
