(1421, 3, '2012-06-06 19:31:31', '2012-06-07 02:31:31', 'Voskos Greek Yogurt Features Its Products at the International Dairy Deli Bakery Association™ (IDDBA) Expo in New Orleans June 10-12, 2012.\n\n(Sun Valley, California) May 9, 2012 - Voskos Greek Yogurt, America’s first nationally distributed brand, will make an appearance at the International Dairy·Deli·Bakery Association™ (IDDBA) Annual Dairy·Deli·Bake Seminar and Expo in New Orleans on June 10th through 12th, 2012. Voskos will be promoting its 32-oz. size Voskos Greek yogurt—available in Plain Non-Fat, Vanilla Non-Fat, and Greek Honey flavors—at booth #3852 in the convention center. Voskos Greek Yogurt is available nationwide in over a dozen regular, low-fat, fat-free and organic flavors at retailers including Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more.\n\n“The growth trend in the Greek yogurt category is in larger sizes because consumers have discovered Greek yogurt is a great ingredient for many of their favorite foods,” says Rick Hoefner, Voskos’ National Sales Manager. “Take smoothies, for example. Smoothies are a $2.5 billion away-from-home-meal category. Consumers are beginning to realize they can make better smoothies at home with thick, creamy Voskos Greek yogurt. Knowing this, Voskos’ retail partners have an opportunity to capitalize on this exploding trend and get some of the business that has been going to smoothie shops by featuring Voskos in the large size container.”  \n\nThe annual IDDBA event attracts over 1,600 dairy, deli, and bakery exhibitors, making it a great venue for Voskos to interact with and listen to their retailers. “The show gives us an opportunity to find out more about what our customers want from us,” says Hoefner. “The IDDBA also gives Voskos Greek yogurt a great opportunity to interact with our retailers to better understand their needs.”\nGreek yogurt sales are strong in the U.S., with food industry analysts predicting that Greek yogurt sales will reach $1.5 billion in 2012, “which is remarkable, considering the product has only been on store shelves in the U.S. for about six years,” says Emily Neukircher, Voskos Marketing Manager. Voskos Greek Yogurt has been recognized in awards contests presented by Fitness magazine, Women’s Health, Vegetarian Times, Natural Solutions, Self Magazine and Cooking Light magazine. Visit the Voskos Web site for dozens of Greek yogurt recipes for high-protein, low-carbohydrate breakfasts, appetizers, entrees and snacks.\nAbout the IDDBA\n\nThe International Dairy·Deli·Bakery Association™ (IDDBA) serves its members by providing opportunities for professional dialogue, education, exchange of industry data and selling opportunities. IDDBA''s Annual Dairy·Deli·Bake Seminar and Expo attracts manufacturers, retailers, wholesalers, distributors, brokers, and many others in the dairy, deli and bakery industries, who gather to promote new products, meet new suppliers, make new contacts, connect with buyers, and learn new ideas.  \nAbout Voskos Greek Yogurt \nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. For store locations and other great opportunities visit Facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt today.\n\n# # #\n\nMedia Contact\nEmily Neukircher\nSun Valley Dairy\n818-504-1775 ext 111\nmarketing (at) voskos (dot) com\n', 'Voskos Greek Yogurt Exhibits at IDDBA Annual Dairy, Deli, Bake Expo', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-iddba-annual-dairy-deli-bake-expo', '', '', '2012-06-06 19:31:31', '2012-06-07 02:31:31', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1421', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1426, 3, '2012-07-18 05:00:49', '2012-07-18 12:00:49', 'Everyone knows that breakfast is the most important meal of the day, but how many of us manage to make it count? Busy mornings mean that too many of us skip breakfast, which makes us low on energy, slows down our metabolism and gets us to lunch ravenous, which often results in overeating. \n\nEating a healthy breakfast need not be difficult - in fact, some of our favorite breakfasts are very easy to make, while others can be made in advance, frozen and reheated. Here are a few ideas for breakfasts that will keep you full until lunch:\n\n1. <strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt mixed with fresh fruit</strong>. How easy is that? Combine the protein from the yogurt with the fiber and vitamins from the fruit, and you got yourself a super quick, tasty and healthy breakfast that will keep you full for several hours. \n\n2. <strong>Two scrambled eggs with 1/4 cup Voskos and lots of veggies.</strong> Heat a tablespoon of canola oil over medium heat; add onions, bell peppers and mushrooms and stir-fry them until tender, 5 minutes. Pour mixture of eggs, yogurt, salt and pepper on top, and scramble with a heat-proof spatula, gently pushing from side to side in the skillet until a mound forms. You can also make this into an omelet, of course. Takes 10 minutes to make and so filling.\n\n3. <strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt with your favorite cereal</strong>. Try adding your favorite cereal (ideally a low-sugar, high-fiber one) to Voskos instead of milk. It''s delicious, and you''ll get more protein and less sugar than when using milk.\n\n4. <strong>Greek yogurt oatmeal pancakes</strong>. These substantial <a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/breakfast/greek-yogurt-oatmeal-pancakes">pancakes</a> are nutritious and very filling. You can make them on the weekend, of course, but they also freeze very well - make them ahead of time, freeze individual servings in ziploc bags, and thaw in the microwave. \n\n5. <strong>Voskos Crunch</strong>. This is truly as quick and convenient as it gets - just take off the lid, pour the granola, and enjoy! You''ll get protein, fiber, and of course lots of flavor. ', 'Five Delicious, Quick, Healthy Breakfast Ideas', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'five-delicious-quick-healthy-breakfast-ideas', '', '', '2012-07-18 05:00:49', '2012-07-18 12:00:49', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1426', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1434, 3, '2012-08-15 05:00:14', '2012-08-15 12:00:14', 'A few weeks ago, we asked our <a href="https://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a> fans this question. The majority of those who had <a href="https://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt/posts/10151030936702236" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">answered</a> said they were unhappy with their current weight. Several of those added that they were working on it and making progress. Just a few said that they were happy with their weight. \n\nIt''s a sad irony of the well-fed Western world, that while in other parts of the world people starve, we have to fight back the temptation to overeat. We are constantly surrounded by food, and by a marketing industry that helps market those foods even if they''re not good for us, even if we are encouraged to consume them in too-large quantities. \n\nSomeday our biology might catch up, making it easier to resist food, maybe also making it easier to burn off extra calories. But for now, we are stuck with the biology that we have inherited from out ancestors - brains that are hardwired to eat when we have the opportunity, even if not hungry, and bodies that are very good at storing extra calories, and not so good at burning those off. It used to be about survival, and now it''s haunting us as we, as a nation, get bigger and bigger. \n\nSo what can we do? Here at Voskos Greek Yogurt, even though we''re in the business - and passion - of making delicious, healthy food, the staff is no stranger to the challenges of losing weight, or maintaining an ideal weight once you''ve reached it. The temptations are huge, and it takes a lot of dedication and effort to resist. One way that has worked for several of us is to try to think about a healthy diet in positive terms. So, instead of thinking about everything we''re giving up, we''re thinking about all the delicious foods that we ARE allowed to eat (including thick, creamy <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a> of course!), and about the many other things we gain as we lose weight, including better health, more energy, and just feeling better throughout the day. \n\nBefore we wrap this up, we would also like to encourage anyone''s who''s working to lose weight to take it very slowly, lose no more than 1-2 pounds each week; to focus on eating well and on the health benefits of losing weight instead of on looks; and to forgive themselves when they slip once in a while - this is a lifetime commitment, so the occasional indulgences will, and should, happen - as long as they remain occasional, of course.', 'Are You Happy with Your Current Weight?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'are-you-happy-with-your-current-weight', '', '', '2012-08-15 05:00:14', '2012-08-15 12:00:14', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1434', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1454, 3, '2011-08-31 16:37:32', '2011-08-31 23:37:32', 'Total prep and cook time: About 30 minutes. \n\nYield: 4 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n3 tablespoons grape seed oil\n2 small red onions, chopped\n2 tablespoon minced fresh garlic\n1 tablespoon fresh ginger\n2 tablespoons tomato paste\n1 tablespoon brown sugar\n1 teaspoon garam masala (ground spices)\n1 tablespoon curry powder\n1 teaspoon red chili flakes\n1 teaspoon salt\n1 pound chicken breasts, boneless and skinless, cut into cubes\n1/4 cup Voskos yogurt, plain\n1/2 cup water\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Heat oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add onions and cook for about 4 minutes, until golden. Add garlic and ginger and cook 2 more minutes. \n2. Add the tomato paste, brown sugar, garam masala, curry powder, chile flakes and salt and cook for 2 minutes. \n3. Add the chicken cubes and stir well to coat. Add the yogurt and water and cook, stirring frequently, until chicken is done, about 20 minutes. Serve with rice or quinoa. \n\n \n\n', 'Indian No-butter Chicken', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'indian-no-butter-chicken', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1454', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1457, 3, '2012-09-17 05:00:00', '2012-09-17 12:00:00', 'I loved my breakfast. Fluffy pancakes, a cup of steaming coffee... what''s not to like?\n\nOf course, two hours later I was famished. \n\nThat''s the problem with eating empty carbs: you might thoroughly enjoy the taste and texture while you''re eating, but you will not stay full for very long, and in fact, typical dips in blood sugar shortly after a carb-heavy meal will make you reach for more carbs. It''s a vicious cycle. \n\n<strong>The answer? Adding protein, and small amount of healthy fats, to each meal and snack.</strong> So, for breakfast, instead of a stack of white-flour pancakes with a cup of coffee, consider a whole-wheat pancake spread with peanut butter and topped with banana slices, or strawberries. And instead of a sugary cereal with milk, choose a low-sugar, high-fiber cereal and mix it and a handful of berries into a cup of rich, creamy <a href="http://www.voskos.com/">Greek yogurt</a>.\n\nWhen it comes to snacks, fresh fruit are a great choice - but you should accompany them with some protein to make them more satiating. An apple is good - apple with cheddar is better. Carrot sticks are great - carrot sticks dipped in hummus are even better. \n\nWhat about dinner? Dinner typically does contain protein, and here, the main challenge for most of us is to focus on a lean protein, and to make veggies the stars of the show rather than a small portion on our plate. So pile your plate with veggies, add a small amount of a lean protein and some whole-grain side such as brown rice, have some fresh fruit for dessert, and this just might keep you full for so long that you forego the notorious late-night snack that keeps sabotaging your efforts!\n\nAnd if you do reach for a late-night snack, forget that bag of chips! Those are empty calories. Instead, how about a cup of yummy Greek yogurt with some crunchy granola?', 'Foods that Keep you Full For Longer', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'foods-that-keep-you-full', '', '', '2012-09-17 05:00:00', '2012-09-17 12:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1457', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1464, 12, '2012-08-28 08:44:48', '2012-08-28 15:44:48', 'The obesity epidemic that currently plagues this country has now spread to children. In an attempt to help mitigate this crisis, most dieticians and parents alike turn to low fat diets for the answer. Moreover, dieticians and personal trainers claim that if you want to lose weight, you must have a caloric deficit at the end of the day. In order to achieve this you must combine diet and exercise. Right? Unfortunately, the current model fails to acknowledge the biochemical pathways of our body. \n\nThe real culprit is excessive fructose consumption. Unlike glucose, which is recognized and utilized by the brain and other parts of the body for energy, fructose is not. Because the brain does not recognize fructose, it must be metabolized exclusively by the liver in a similar fashion to that of ethanol (standard alcoholic beverage). Fructose is thus a chronic hepatotoxin! Despite the fact that fructose is a carbohydrate, it is metabolized like fat in the liver. Chronic fructose exposure leads to activation of inflammatory pathways, increased vLDL levels, type 2 diabetes, and obesity. Remember that table sugar (sucrose) contains 50% glucose and 50% fructose, so it is nearly as toxic when consumed over chronic periods.  \n\n<strong>So what can you do to help combat this epidemic? Follow these basic rules when packing your child’s next school lunch:</strong>\n\n1)	Water and milk should be the only beverages consumed. Most sucrose and fructose consumption in this country comes from sugar-flavored beverages. \n\n2)	Eat as many non-processed foods as possible. \n\n3)	Pack more raw fruits and vegetables to help increase fiber consumption. Note that fruit does contain fructose, however the ratio of fiber to fructose is high. Fiber can decrease the “rate of intestinal carbohydrate absorption,” “induce satiety,” and “inhibit absorption of some free fatty acids to the colon” (Lustig 2009). \n\n4)	Increase “good” fat consumption from Omega 3’s and 6’s. \n\nHere are some healthy school lunch snacks that will help keep brainpower elevated.\n\n1.	Plain Greek yogurt - Providing perhaps the best carbohydrate to protein ratio of any food, yogurt is a great way to not only provide you with sustainable energy but can also double as a recovery food. You will also obtain the added benefits of probiotics. I recommend Voskos’s Plain Original Greek Yogurt. You can also throw in some blueberries for added flavor. \n\n2.   Fruit – A piece of fruit, such as an apple, banana, or a handful of blueberries can provide you with healthy antioxidants and fiber.  \n\n3.   Almond butter sandwich – Spread two tablespoons of raw almond butter on whole wheat bread, and add slices of banana inside. \n\n4.   Cucumbers, carrots, and celery sticks with hummus  dip – Eating vegetables is an easy way to increase fiber and vitamin consumption. \n\n5.   Peanut butter bars – Make your own protein “bars” by mixing peanut butter, rolled oats, dates, and a protein powder of your choice (preferably whey protein isolate). You can either eat them raw or bake them in the oven. (*See recipe below)\n\n6.   Kale chips – A member of the cabbage family, kale ranks high in terms of nutritional value. Kale is rich in carotenoids, anti-oxidants, and Vitamins A, K, and C. Drizzle olive oil on kale leaves and bake them in the oven until desired texture is achieved. \n\n7.   Tortilla wrap – Take a whole wheat tortilla and wrap it around a protein source such as chicken, turkey, or even prosciutto. Add fresh mozzarella cheese, avocado, fresh basil, and cherry tomatoes.  \n\n8. Beef or turkey jerky – A great high protein alternative to cold-cuts that doesn’t require refrigeration. Whenever possible ensure that it comes from grass-fed and free-range cows and turkeys. Avoid products that are high in added sugar and preservatives. \n\n*Here is the recipe for raw peanut butter bars:\n\n4 Large and pitted dates\n1/4 cup whey protein isolate - make sure there is no added sugar\n1/4 cup raw oats \n3 TBSP organic almond or peanut butter - unsweetened and unsalted \n1 TSP vanilla, almond, or orange extract for taste - optional \n1 TSP organic maple syrup - optional, realize this will add more calories and added sugar \n\nPlace all ingredients in a food processor and mix until finely ground. Mold contents into small balls. They do not need to be baked. Enjoy! \n', 'Healthy School Lunches Fight Childhood Obesity ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'healthy-school-lunches-fight-childhood-obesity-epidemic', '', '', '2012-08-28 08:44:48', '2012-08-28 15:44:48', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1464', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(1471, 12, '2012-08-31 05:00:46', '2012-08-31 12:00:46', 'Let’s be honest, beach day food can be a real detriment to keeping your diet on track. Burgers, beer, and chips provide nothing more than a quick recipe for disaster. The next time you hit the surf, consider the quality of your nutrition while being Calorie conscious. \n\n<strong>Here is a list of ten healthy beach snacks that are under 150 Calories:</strong> \n\n1.	Water – At least 1.5 liters of water should always be in your cooler or backpack when heading to the beach.   Proper hydration is the foundation of any nutrition plan, and is necessary for maintaining most physiological functions. \n\n2.	Nuts and seeds– Rich in good fats (Omega-3s), a handful of nuts and seeds, such as almonds and chia seeds, can provide the sustainable energy necessary to stay full at the beach. Remember to choose raw, unsalted, and unsweetened options whenever possible.  \n\n3.	Fruit – A piece of fruit, such as an apple, or a handful of chopped pineapple can provide you with healthy antioxidants and fiber. This is a great low-Calorie way to grab a quick source of energy. \n\n4.	Yogurt – Providing perhaps the best carbohydrate to protein ratio of any food, yogurt is a great way to not only provide you with sustainable energy but can also double as a recovery food after a beach workout. You will also obtain the added benefits of probiotics. I prefer Voskos‘s 5.3oz strawberry yogurt, which has only 120 Calories. \n \n5.	Almond butter with celery and carrots – Spreading a couple tablespoons of almond butter on carrots or celery is a great alternative to peanut butter and is rich in omega fatty acids. \n\n6.	Protein lettuce wraps – Take large romaine lettuce leaves and wrap them around a lean protein source of your choice, such as chicken or turkey breast. For added flavor and variety add olives and cucumbers. You can also drizzle olive oil and balsamic vinegar inside.  \n\n7.	Peanut butter balls – Make your own protein “bars” by mixing peanut butter, rolled oats, dates, a protein powder of your choice (preferably whey protein isolate), and a dash of maple syrup. You can either eat them raw or bake them in the oven. \n\n8.	Popcorn – Substituting this snack for chips and dip is a great low-Calorie alternative.  \n\n9. Kale chips – A member of the cabbage family, kale ranks high in terms of nutritional value. Kale is rich in carotenoids, anti-oxidants, and Vitamins A, K, and C. Drizzle olive oil on kale leaves and bake them in the oven until desired texture is achieved. \n\n10.	Roasted chickpeas – Chickpeas, also known as garbanzo beans, are rich in zinc, protein, and fiber. Drain and rinse a 15oz can of chickpeas, then drizzle olive oil, add salt, and spices of your choice. Bake in the oven for 30 minutes at 400°F. \n', 'Labor Day Weekend Low Calorie Beach Snacks', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'low-calorie-beach-snacks', '', '', '2012-08-31 05:00:46', '2012-08-31 12:00:46', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1471', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1476, 3, '2012-09-06 09:54:07', '2012-09-06 16:54:07', 'You''re cooking or baking.. oh no! You''re out of butter!\n\nNo worries - use Voskos instead! You''ll end up with a moist, delicious cake. \n\nIn fact, in most recipes that call for mayonnaise or butter, you can replace at least half the listed amount with Voskos Greek Yogurt. Often, you can replace the entire amount of butter or mayo, with great results. \n\nVoskos... better than good! \n \n<iframe width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RmAVRJG5ddM&list=UUARxLBOKvzi7qW8ILbpyoUg&index=1&feature=plcp" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>', 'Out of Butter? Use Voskos!', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'out-of-butter-use-voskos', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1476', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1484, 3, '2011-09-27 10:07:31', '2011-09-27 17:07:31', 'Many thanks to <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Facebook</a> fan Jimmy Arcade for submitting this recipe to our recipe contest, and to his lovely wife for posing with the lassi! \n\nJimmy is the winner of the contest. He won a $50 AmEx gift card. \n\n<b>Voskos Mango Lassi</b>\n\nServes: 2-4\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 mango (peeled and chopped into cubes)\n2 5.3 oz. containers of Voskos Organic Vanilla Bean Greek Yogurt\n1 5.3 oz. container of Voskos Organic Greek Honey Greek Yogurt\n1/2 cup Coconut Milk\n1/2 tsp Lime Juice\n1/2 tsp Ginger (ground)\n1/8 tsp Nutmeg (ground)\n1/4 tsp Cardamon (ground)\nOptional: 1/2 tbsp Organic Honey \n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nEmpty all three containers of Voskos Greek Yougurt into a blender or food processor, along with coconut milk, and lime juice. Blend just until mixed. Add all of the mango cubes, honey, ginger, nutmeg, and cardamon. Blend until well mixed. Pour into 2 tall glasses or 4 medium glasses.\n\nNote: If you like your mango lassi with a bit a sweetness kick, add the optional honey.', 'Voskos Mango Lassi', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-mango-lassi', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1484', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1488, 12, '2012-09-12 05:00:15', '2012-09-12 12:00:15', 'Follow these 10 easy tips to help avoid the “freshman 15”: \n\n1.	<strong>Prepare Meals Ahead of Time\n</strong>\nCollege students are often busy studying every chance they get, finding little time to eat or sleep. As a result, they are quick to grab unhealthy fast food. Rather than scrambling for food at the last minute, prepare all of your meals on Sunday for the following week and store them in the refrigerator. Chili was my favorite meal, as it could be made in large quantities. \n\n2.	<strong>Eat Breakfast</strong>\n\nRather than waking up 10 minutes before class starts, give yourself enough time to make breakfast. Eating breakfast will help jump start your metabolism and give your brain the fuel it needs to focus during class. I highly recommend steel-cut oatmeal. \n\n3.	<strong>Eat More Protein, and Less Refined Carbohydrates </strong>\n\nSubstitute refined carbohydrates with protein rich foods such as lean meats, fish, and eggs. \n\n4.	<strong>Eat More Fiber</strong>\n\nFiber can decrease both carbohydrate and fat absorption by the body.\n\n5.	<strong>Eliminate Empty Calories and Foods with High-Fructose Corn Syrup </strong>\n\nJunk foods such as sodas, flavored waters, energy-drinks, candy, chips, and cookies can be loaded with high-fructose corn syrup. For the average individual (non-elite athlete), these empty carbohydrates will be metabolized directly into fat. Energy drinks can also be loaded with large doses of caffeine (greater than 300mg) and other stimulants that increase the stress hormone cortisol when consumed repeatedly. \n\n6.	<strong>Voskos Greek Yogurt is the Perfect Study Food </strong>\n\nYogurt makes a great study food that doesn’t require any preparation time. It also has an optimal protein to carbohydrate ratio, making it a great recovery food after hard workouts. For men and women trying to “tone-up” I recommend 5.3oz of Voskos’ Non-Fat Plain Yogurt. For those trying to gain muscle mass I recommend 8oz of Voskos’ Plain Original Greek Yogurt. \n\n7.	<strong>Keep Your Hormones in Balance </strong>\n\nUnbalanced stress hormones can lead to an increase in body fat. To counter the stress of exams get between 7-8 hours of sleep, exercise at least five days per week for at least 30 minutes, limit caffeine consumption as much as possible, and practice some form of yoga and/or meditation. \n\n8.	<strong>Minimize Partying and Alcohol Consumption </strong>\n\nAn obvious but often overlooked concept, partying late into the night can alter your circadian cycle and create hormonal imbalances leading to body fat increases. Aside from its detrimental effects on the body, alcohol is metabolized directly into fat. A shot of vodka contains 50 calories while a glass of beer ranges from 100 to nearly 300 calories.  \n\n9.	<strong>Replace the Elliptical and Treadmill for Compound Barbell Movements and High-Intensity Plyometric Exercises</strong>\n\nHeavy barbell lifts such as the squat, deadlift, bench-press, military-press, clean and jerk, and the snatch have been shown to increase testosterone levels. High-intensity plyometric exercises are great for building explosive power and increasing metabolic conditioning. Depending on effort, more calories can be burnt in a shorter amount of time when compared to a moderate jog on a treadmill or elliptical. \n\n10.	<strong> No Excuse Not to Workout</strong>\n\nIf you are low on free time, opt for a high-intensity body weight circuit in your dorm or apartment room. Complete as many rounds of 20 pushups, 30 squats, 30 sit-ups, and 20 dips in 10 minutes without rest. Then hold a plank for two minutes and complete 100 flutter kicks. \n\n￼￼￼￼', '10 Tips for Maintaining Fitness in College', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '10-tips-for-maintaining-fitness-in-college', '', '', '2012-09-12 05:00:15', '2012-09-12 12:00:15', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1488', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1492, 12, '2012-09-14 05:00:49', '2012-09-14 12:00:49', 'Breakfast is the most important meal of the day. Whether you are trying to lose weight or add muscle mass, breakfast should be part of your morning ritual. \n\n<strong>Follow these basic rules at breakfast when trying to lose weight: </strong>\n\n1.	Avoid adding sugar to your coffee, tea, or oatmeal. \n\n2.	Eat more fiber.  \n\n3.	Eat more foods packed with omega fatty acids.   \n\n4.	Drink more water. \n\n5.	Substitute refined carbohydrates for high protein foods, such as lean meats, eggs, and fish.\n\n6.	Avoid drinking fruit juice in excess.\n\n<strong>Try these power-packed breakfast recipes:</strong>\n\n1.	Weight-loss yogurt parfait \n\n     Mix 5.3oz Voskos plain nonfat yogurt with ¼ cup of fresh berries and sprinkled chopped almonds.  \n\n2.	Steel-cut oatmeal with flax seeds \n\n     For a fiber and omega-3 packed breakfast, sprinkle one tablespoon of flax seeds on ¼ cup of cooked steel-cut oats. \n\n3.	Power fruit smoothie \n\n     Start your morning off with this delicious smoothie. Mix 5.3oz of Voskos plain nonfat yogurt with frozen blueberries, 4oz full-pulp orange juice, and ice. \n\n4.	Egg whites and chicken breast \n\nFor those trying to minimize carbohydrate intake, start your day off with 2 egg whites and 5oz of chicken breast. Drizzle olive oil for taste. \n\n5.	Egg-white omelet \n\nMix two egg whites with a pinch of spinach, onions, and mushrooms. Cook in a tablespoon of olive oil. \n\n6.	Omega toast\n\n     To add some omega-3s to your morning breakfast, spread two tablespoons of almond butter and sprinkle one teaspoon of flax seeds on one slice of whole grain bread. Add ½ sliced banana on top for added taste. \n\n7.	Salmon with vegetables \n     \n     Get your morning dose of omega fatty acids and protein with 4oz of salmon or lox with sliced cucumbers and tomatoes. \n\n8.	Voskos green drink\n\n     Start your day off with this vitamin, antioxidant, and fiber packed drink. Mix 5.3oz of Voskos plain nonfat yogurt with frozen blueberries, 1 cup spinach, 1 cup kale, 1 granny smith apple, 4oz full-pulp orange juice, and ice. \n\n9.	Weight gainer protein shake\n\n     For those trying to pack on serious muscle, add this shake to your morning regiment. Mix 8oz Voskos original plain yogurt, one cup whole milk, four tablespoons of raw almond butter, one whole banana, 30g of whey protein isolate, and ice. \n', 'The Power Breakfast Prescription ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'power-breakfast', '', '', '2012-09-14 05:00:49', '2012-09-14 12:00:49', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1492', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1496, 3, '2011-10-05 05:00:52', '2011-10-05 12:00:52', 'Moist and delicious, these pumpkin muffins are perfect with hot tea.\n\nMakes 12 muffins\n\n<strong>Ingredients </strong>\nNonstick spray \n2 cups whole-wheat flour\n½ cup packed brown sugar \n1 TBS baking powder\n1 teaspoon ground cinnamon\n2 large eggs, lightly beaten\n1 cup VOSKOS Greek yogurt, plain low fat\n1 cup unsweetened pumpkin puree\n2 TBS olive oil \n1/4 cup reduced fat milk\nFor topping: 2 TBS sugar mixed with 1/4 tsp. cinnamon\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line 12 muffin cups with paper liners and generously spray with nonstick spray.\n2. In a large bowl, combine flour, sugar, baking powder and cinnamon.\n3. In a separate bowl, whisk together the eggs, yogurt, pumpkin puree, olive oil and milk. \n4. Add the liquid ingredients to the dry ingredients and mix just until incorporated. \n5. Spoon batter into muffin tin, filling each cup almost to top. Sprinkle with cinnamon sugar.\n6. Bake for 20 minutes, or until a wooden toothpick inserted in one of the muffins comes out clean. \n7. Cool 5 minutes in pan on a wire rack, then transfer to wire rack to cool some more. Serve warm or at room temperature. \n\n<img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/DSC_0008-589.jpg" alt="" title="DSC_0008 589" width="589" height="355" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1497" />\n\n<strong>Nutrition Per Muffin 	</strong>\nCalories 166.5\nTotal Fat 4.0 g\nSaturated Fat 0.9 g\nCholesterol 32.5 mg\nSodium 146.5 mg\nTotal Carbohydrate 32.0 g\nDietary Fiber 3.4 g\nSugars 16.0 g\nProtein 6.1 g\n\n', 'Greek Yogurt Pumpkin Muffins', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'greek-yogurt-pumpkin-muffins', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1496', 0, 'post', '', 16),
(1502, 3, '2012-09-17 16:06:24', '2012-09-17 23:06:24', 'On Friday, September 7th, celebs including Gwyneth Paltrow, Alicia Keys, Tom Hanks, and Sofia Vergara helped raise money for cancer research at the Stand Up to Cancer telethon in Los Angeles, a nationally televised fundraiser to accelerate groundbreaking research in the fight against cancer. Actors, musicians, and athletes came together for the fundraiser. \n\nSeveral of the participating stars shared stories of their, or their loved ones'' personal battles with cancer. It was amazing to see so many great talents joining together for this important cause. \n\nStand Up To Cancer is a program of the Entertainment Industry Foundation, a philanthropic arm of the TV and movie industries. The American Association for Cancer Research is the scientific partner of Stand Up To Cancer and conducts scientific oversight of its research projects in conjunction with the SU2C advisory committee.\n\nStand Up To Cancer <a href="http://www.standup2cancer.org/" target="_blank"><u>accepts</u></a> individual as well as corporate donations. Voskos Greek Yogurt is a proud sponsor of the charity. ', 'Stars Stand Up to Cancer ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'stars-stand-up-to-cancer', '', '', '2012-09-17 16:06:24', '2012-09-17 23:06:24', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1502', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1514, 3, '2011-10-12 05:00:16', '2011-10-12 12:00:16', 'Makes 8 cupcakes\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1/2 cup agave syrup\n1/3 cup unsalted butter, melted\n2 eggs\n1/4 cup Voskos Organic Vanilla Greek Yogurt\n1 1/2 cup all-purpose flour\n1 teaspoon baking powder\n1/2 teaspoon baking soda\n1/2 teaspoon salt\n\n \n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Line a 12-cup cupcake pan with cupcake liners.\n2. In a medium-sized bowl, blend the melted butter, cooled slightly, and the agave syrup. Carefully beat in eggs one at a time, then stir in Voskos Non-Fat Vanilla Yogurt. In another medium-sized bowl, whisk together the dry ingredients (flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt.)\n3. Slowly mix the wet ingredients into the bowl of dry ingredients and blend until smooth.\n4. Fill cupcake liners 3/4 full. (Mixture will make enough batter for approximately 8 cupcakes.)\n5. Bake in a preheated oven at 350 degrees for 20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out dry.\n6. Allow cupcakes to cool completely before icing.\n\n<strong>Frosting</strong>\n1 8-oz. package of cream cheese\n5 tablespoons butter, softened\n2 tablespoons Voskos Vanilla Organic Greek Yogurt\n1 teaspoon vanilla\n2 cups powdered sugar, sifted\n\n1. Whisk cream cheese with softened butter.\n2. Add Voskos Organic Vanilla Greek Yogurt along with vanilla.\n3. Gradually add powdered sugar to the mixture. Continue to blend until nearly smooth.\n4. Using a commercial edible glaze, add a "breast cancer awareness" ribbon to the top of each cupcake after frosting. Just before serving, top cupcakes with frosting and serve.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nCupcake:         \n212 Calories\nFat 9g\nCarbs 30g\nFiber 1g\nProtein 2g\n\nFrosting: \n152 Calories\nFat 6g\nCarbs 21g\nProtein 3g\n\n \n\n', 'Voskos Breast Cancer Awareness Cupcakes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-breast-cancer-awareness-organic-vanilla-cupcakes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1514', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1517, 3, '2012-10-03 05:00:47', '2012-10-03 12:00:47', 'Here at Voskos we support numerous causes, but breast cancer awareness is especially important to us because several of us know someone who was affected by the disease. The <a href="http://www.breastcancer.org/symptoms/understand_bc/statistics.jsp" target="_blank">statistics</a> are sobering: About 1 in 8 U.S. women will develop invasive breast cancer over the course of her lifetime. In fact, besides skin cancer, breast cancer is the most commonly diagnosed cancer among American women. \n\nThe good news: death rates have been decreasing since 1990, especially in women under 50. These decreases are thought to be the result of treatment advances, earlier detection through screening, and increased awareness.\n\nResearch tells us that half of cancer deaths are <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/09/20/half-cancer-deaths-preventable_n_971746.html" target="_blank">preventable</a>, through lifestyle changes and screenings. For breast cancer especially, if it is detected early, survival rates are <a href="http://www.cancer.org/Cancer/BreastCancer/OverviewGuide/breast-cancer-overview-survival-rates" target="_blank">very high</a>. \n\n<a href="http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/breast-cancer-prevention/WO00091" target="_blank">The Mayo Clinic</a> suggests several ways to try and prevent breast cancer, such as limiting alcohol intake, being physically active and keeping a healthy body weight. Obviously not all cases of breast cancer can be prevented, but it does make sense to try and control what one *can* control.\n\nWhen it comes to screening, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/cancer/breast/basic_info/screening.htm" target="_blank">recommends</a> having a screening mammogram every two years between the ages of 50-74, although some healthcare professionals recommend an annual mammogram starting at age 40. The center adds that breast self exams and clinical breast exams have not been shows to reduce breast caner mortality, so regular mammograms remain the main tool we have for early detection of breast cancer. \n\nThis month, Breast Cancer Awareness Month, and throughout the year, we urge each and every one of you to follow these simple guidelines. Adopt as healthy a lifestyle as you possibly can, and go get that mammogram! It could save your life. For more info, and to find a low-cost screening location near you, visit the <a href="http://www.nbcam.org/" target="_blank">website</a> of National Breast Cancer Awareness Month. ', 'Thoughts on Breast Cancer Awareness Month', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'breast-cancer-awareness-month', '', '', '2012-10-03 05:00:47', '2012-10-03 12:00:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1517', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1524, 3, '2011-10-25 05:00:58', '2011-10-25 12:00:58', 'Prep Time: 25 Minutes\nCook Time: 20-25 Minutes\nServings:   24\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n\n3 1/2 cups all-purpose flour                \n2 teaspoons baking soda\n1 teaspoon salt\n1 teaspoon baking powder\n1 1/2 teaspoons ground cinnamon\n2 cups canned pumpkin puree\n1 cup white sugar\n1/2 cup light brown sugar\n1/2 cup applesauce\n1 cup Non-Fat Voskos Vanilla Yogurt\n4 egg whites\n1 egg\n2/3 cup water\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n\n1.Preheat oven to 350 degrees F. Line two 12 cup cupcake pans with paper liners that have been sprayed with cooking spray. (*Note- there is no butter in the batter). \n\n2. In a medium bowl, mix the flour, baking soda, salt, baking powder, and cinnamon. In a large bowl, beat together the the pumpkin, white sugar, brown sugar, applesauce, yogurt, egg whites, and egg. Blend flour mixture into sugar mixture, alternating with the water, to form a smooth batter. Transfer to the prepared cupcake pan, filling 3/4 full. (*Note- using an ice-cream scooper works best).\n\n3. Bake 20 to 25 minutes, until a toothpick inserted in the center of a cupcake comes out clean. Cool on wire racks before frosting.\n\n<strong>Frosting</strong>\n\nTwo 8 ounce packages cream cheese\n1 stick butter, room temperature\n3 cups confectioners'' sugar\n2 teaspoons vanilla extract\n\nIn a stand mixer, beat the cream cheese, butter, sugar and vanilla on medium speed until fluffy, about 5 minutes. Decorate cupcakes to your liking.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\n\nCupcake: 125 calories\nFat                0.4g\nCarbs                27.1g\nFiber                1.1g\nProtein        2.9g\n\nFrosting: 149 calories\nFat                9.4g\nCarbs                15.5g\nProtein        1.5g\n', 'Halloween Pumpkin Cupcakes', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'halloween-pumpkin-cupcakes', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '2013-08-05 21:00:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1524', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1525, 12, '2012-10-12 05:00:12', '2012-10-12 12:00:12', 'If you’re like most men and women, turning 40 feels like life as you know it is accelerating to an end. People often turn to expensive cosmetic creams, botox injections, supplements, and fad diets, all in search of the fountain of youth. No matter how enticing a product box or advertisement may seem, the truth is, these are merely temporary band-aids that cover up underlying health problems. \n\nWant to look and feel young, fresh, and like you just spent a weekend in the Bahamas? Save your money and follow these quick and cheap lifestyle fixes: \n\n1) <strong>Use Sunscreen </strong>\n\n•	Problem: UV radiation from the sun is a carcinogen and was responsible for almost 60,000 skin cancer diagnoses and over 8,600 deaths in the United States in 2008 (CDC) alone. Excessive UV exposure can damage DNA and accelerate skin wrinkling and dryness.\n\n•	Solution: Reapply sunscreen throughout the day if you know you’re going to be in direct sunlight. Researchers believe between 5-30 minutes of sunlight between the hours of 10am and 3pm is all that is needed to get the proper daily dose of Vitamin D. Avoid tanning beds all together, as they can emit abnormally high doses of UV radiation. To keep your skin looking extra fresh try the <a href="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/press-releases/dry-skin-greek-yogurt-facial">Voskos Greek Yogurt face mask</a>. Greek yogurt contains lactic acid, which can help exfoliate and moisturize the skin. \n\n\n2) <strong>Minimize Stress </strong>\n\n•	Problem: In my opinion, stress is one of the major causes of aging and most diseases. Chronic stress can wreak havoc on the endocrine system and create hormonal imbalances. Chronic stress has been shown to accelerate atherosclerosis, Type II diabetes, abdominal obesity, and hypertension (McEwen and Seeman 1999). It can also lead to “immunosuppressive effects” causing you to get sick more often.  \n\n•	Solution: Make stress management a priority and find time during your day to de-stress. Methods such as yoga, tai chi, meditation, and exercise have all been shown in clinical settings to reduce blood cortisol levels (the body’s stress hormone). \n\n\n3) <strong>Maintain a Proper Diet</strong>\n\n•	Problem: The modern American diet is high in trans- and saturated fats, refined carbohydrates, and sugar (both from sucrose and high-fructose corn syrup). This type of diet has been linked on many accounts to numerous diseases such as heart disease, obesity, Type II diabetes, and even some cancers!  \n\n•	Solution: Maintain a diet that is high in fruits and vegetables (rich in anti-oxidants), lean protein (mainly egg whites, poultry, and fish), nuts and seeds, and whole grains. The only supplement I take is EPA-DHA fish oil (approximately 3 grams per day). Avoid eating out whenever possible. If time is an issue, make all of your meals ahead of time on Sunday for the following week. Don’t forget to drink between 1-3 liters of water (depending on physical activity) daily to help flush out toxins from the liver. \n\n\n4) <strong>Limit Alcohol Consumption</strong>\n\n•	Problem: Alcohol is a poison, and thus should be consumed in very small quantities. The side effects are seemingly endless: weight gain, hypertension, impaired immunity, some cancers, fatty liver, hepatitis, liver cirrhosis, and liver cancer. Your liver can only metabolize about 1 drink per hour. Chronic alcohol use will accelerate the aging process. \n\n•	Solution: Limit alcohol consumption to 1-2 drinks per weekend, or even better, 1-2 drinks per month. \n\n5) <strong>Don’t Smoke Anything, Period! </strong>\n\n•	Problem: There is no benefit to smoking. Whether a substance is addictive or not, smoking causes cancer of the bladder, cervix, esophagus, kidneys, larynx, lungs, pharynx, pancreas, oral cavity, and stomach, as well as birth defects, coronary heart disease, emphysema, bronchitis, and COPD, just to name a few. Given the correlation between disease and aging, smoking will cause you to age faster.     \n\n•	Solution: Don’t smoke anything, Period! \n\n\n6) <strong>Limit Prescription Drug Use</strong>\n\n•	Problem: These days there is a drug for everything. Sometimes (more often than not), the long-term side effects of these drugs outweigh the benefits. Living a healthy lifestyle can often fix some health problems without drug use. For example, simply changing dietary and exercise habits can alleviate the hypertension and Type II diabetes caused by obesity. \n\n•	Solution: Prescription drugs should be an absolute last resort. Talk to your doctor about weighing the long-term risks and benefits of the drugs you are taking. \n\n\n7) <strong>Get Proper Sleep</strong>\n\n•	Problem: Most people don’t get enough sleep and vary the times that they go to bed. Altering your circadian rhythm can cause metabolic and hormonal fluctuations, leading to increases in stress and fat storage.  \n\n•	Solution: Get a consistent 7-8 hours of sleep per night and try to go to bed and wake up at the same times every day. \n', '7 Tips to Help Slow the Aging Process', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '7-tips-to-help-slow-the-aging-process', '', '', '2012-10-12 05:00:12', '2012-10-12 12:00:12', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1525', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1531, 3, '2012-11-20 05:00:00', '2012-11-20 12:00:00', 'I like to complain, I''m afraid, and it''s not something I''m proud of. I''m working on it, though, and November especially is a great time for me to focus on the positive and on being grateful. It''s interesting - when you make yourself focus on all the good in your life, you complain a lot less.. and being grateful becomes more and more natural. So here are a few things I''m grateful for this season.\n\n1. <strong>Health.</strong> It''s the most important thing, really - and the older you get, the more you realize how important your health is. And after having to deal with a family member''s (minor) surgery earlier this year, I am especially grateful for having access to one of the best, most advanced medical systems in the world. Yes, it''s expensive, and healthcare is a big problem in the US, but most of us still enjoy a level of healthcare that our predecessors could only dream about. So when something does go wrong, we have a much better chance of surviving - and thriving - than our ancestors had, or than people in other parts of the world have. \n\nSince November is American Diabetes Month, this is another important reminder of how important it is to do everything in our power to stay as healthy as possible, and to make the most of modern medicine to manage chronic conditions.\n\n2. <strong>Plenty of Food.</strong> We are surrounded by food, and we worry so much about gaining weight, that we sometimes forget to give thanks for all this bounty. No doubt, too much food presents a challenge - but it is so much better than scarcity and hunger. We are so very lucky that the vast majority of us have never experienced true hunger. \n\n3. <strong>Knowledge. </strong> The other day, I wanted to know how long a certain movie was, so I started typing the question on Google: "How long is the ______ movie." I didn''t even have to finish typing the question, when the software guessed what I wanted to ask and promptly gave me a clear answer. I was amazed. How amazing is it, that we have such easy access to so much information? Almost anything we want to know is  at the tip of our fingers. We now have access to information that used to be unavailable, or that required hours of research in a library. \n\nSo I give thanks. And whatever you''re grateful for, I''d love to hear about it in the comments. ', 'Things to be Grateful For This Month', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'things-to-be-grateful-for', '', '', '2012-11-20 05:00:00', '2012-11-20 12:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1531', 0, 'post', '', 0);
