(1536, 3, '2011-11-08 07:00:41', '2011-11-08 14:00:41', '*This recipe is part of the Voskos Thanksgiving 2011 Menu. Make this recipe, photograph it and upload a photo <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt?sk=app_95936962634" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a> to enter our Thanksgiving Menu Contest. You could win up to a $250 gift card, just in time for the holidays! \n\nPreparation Time: 1 hour \nTotal Time: 1 hour 20 minutes\nServings: 10 turnovers\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1/2 onion, chopped\n3 tablespoons grape seed oil\n2 garlic cloves, chopped\n1 16oz package frozen chopped spinach, drained and squeezed dry\n4 oz crumbled feta cheese\n1 egg, slightly beaten\n3 tablespoons parsley, chopped\n3 tablespoons cilantro, chopped\nSalt and pepper to taste\n20 sheets store-bought phyllo dough\n1/2 cup grape seed oil, for brushing the phyllo\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a small skillet, sauté onion in grape seed oil over medium high heat until soft. Add garlic, cook for 30 seconds. Remove from heat and set aside.\n\n2. In a medium bowl, combine spinach, feta, egg, parsley, cilantro, salt and pepper. Stir until well combined. Set aside.\n\n3. Remove one sheet of  phyllo from stack (cover the remaining sheets with a damp cloth to keep from drying out) and lay it on a work surface. Brush entire sheet with a thin layer of grape seed oil. Place another sheet on top, brush with oil and repeat two more times (you will have four sheets stacked with a layer of oil on the sheet). Cut this stack in half  lengthwise with a knife.\n\n4. You now have two long rectangles of phyllo in front of you. Place about 2 tablespoons of filling on the bottom right side of one of the rectangles. Fold the bottom left corner up and over the filling so that the bottom edge is now even with the right side. Continue folding up and over until you end up with a triangle. Brush triangle with oil and place on baking sheet.\n\n5. Repeat this procedure with the other phyllo rectangle.\n\n6. Repeat steps 3 and 4 until you have 10 triangles on your baking sheet.\n\n7. Bake at 375 degree oven for about 20 minutes or until golden brown.\n\n8. Cool on wire rack and enjoy either warm or at room temperature.\n\nNote*- Turnovers can be prepared a week ahead of time and placed in the freezer.\nThaw-out for about 15 minutes before baking.\n\n<strong>Nutrition Facts Using Phyllo Dough and Grape Seed Oil:  </strong>       \nCalories Per Serving:     205                                        \nTotal Fat:                20.4g                                        \nSaturated Fat:           4.5g                                       \nTotal Carbohydrates:   2.6g                                        \nDietary Fiber:             1.2g                                      \nProtein:                     3.5g\n\n<strong>Nutrition Facts Using Puff Pastry Dough:</strong>\nCalories Per Serving: 305\nTotal Fat: 25.2g\nSaturated Fat: 6.1\nTotal Carbohydrates: 14.7\nDietary Fiber: 1.4g\nProtein: 5.3\n', 'Spinach and Feta Turnovers (Thanksgiving Menu)', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'spinach-and-feta-turnovers', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1536', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(1542, 3, '2012-10-31 07:56:10', '2012-10-31 14:56:10', 'It all started with an innocent tweet. Bridget Daly, Deidre Behar and Joslyn Davis of ClevverTV and ClevverNews were discussing Greek yogurt, when Daly tweeted “I’ll assume u ladies have NOT had Voskos fig Greek yogurt? It''s life changing.”\nTo which Deidre Behar replied, “I propose a joint bday cake made of such "fig Greek yogurt" by @govoskos in honor of Oct 28th and 29th''s finest.”\n\n“How could we possibly refuse?” says Gohar Ohanian, Marketing Consultant at Voskos Greek Yogurt. “It was short notice, but we had to come up with a cake that would be delicious and beautiful – beautiful enough to be deserving of these gorgeous, vibrant young women.”\nKnowing that this was a task for a professional baker, Voskos had enlisted the help of the very talented Shantal DerBoghosian of Shakar Bakery. “I knew I wanted a layer cake, and I wanted to incorporate the flavors of Voskos fig yogurt, chocolate, and of course create frosting with the glamour girls’ images,” explains Shantal.\n\nThe delightful, multi-layer result was brought into the ClevverTV studios on Friday, October 26th, to the delight of the birthday girls. “We’re super grateful to Voskos for treating us to this amazing cake for our birthdays” says Deidre Behar. “We couldn’t have asked for a more special treat.”\n\nAbout Shakar Bakery \nShakar Bakery specializes in designer cakes, gourmet cookies, cupcakes and chocolates for birthdays, weddings, engagements, showers, and parties. The two most important qualities in any Shakar Bakery work are design and quality taste. To view the bakery’s creations, visit its online gallery.\n\nAbout ClevverTV and ClevverNews \nClevverTV features entertainment news, interviews with the hottest young Hollywood celebrities, gossip, movie previews, music info and more. Click here to subscribe. ClevverNews is your daily up to the minute entertainment news source, featuring celebrity interviews, television scoop, behind-the-scenes set visits, Hollywood headlines, and music & movie News. Click here to subscribe.\n\nAbout Voskos Greek Yogurt \nAward-winning for its thick, rich taste and nutritional value, Voskos Greek Yogurt is nature’s premium blend of authentic yogurt and is Better Than Good in more ways than one. Voskos Greek Yogurt is all-natural, GMO-free, hormone-free, gluten-free, and Kosher certified. Through Voskos’ proprietary ProStrain™ method, Voskos yields two times more protein, more probiotics, less lactose, and a thicker, creamier consistency. Blended with balance, Voskos products have the best protein to sugar ratio on the market. Available nationwide at Kroger, Safeway, Publix, Shoprite, Wakefern, Bi-Lo, Whole Foods, Sprouts, and more. For store locations, visit voskos.com or Facebook/voskos.greek.yogurt today.', 'ClevverTV Stars Celebrate Birthday with a Voskos Cake', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'clevvertv-stars-bridget-daly-and-deidre-behar-celebrate-birthday-with-a-voskos-greek-yogurt-fig-cake', '', '', '2012-10-31 07:56:10', '2012-10-31 14:56:10', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1542', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1548, 12, '2012-11-01 10:50:02', '2012-11-01 17:50:02', 'Genetically modified organisms, or GMOs, have been making headlines lately in the political arena. A GMO is an organism whose genetic makeup has been altered through genetic engineering. In other words, their DNA has been changed. \n\nCalifornia’s Proposition 37 – Genetically Engineered Foods. Labeling. Initiative Statute. – will be on the November 6th ballot. According to the state’s official voter guide, approval of this measure will require the following:\n\n1.	“Requires labeling on raw or processed food offered for sale to consumers if made from plants or animals with genetic material changed in specified ways.” \n\n2.	“Prohibits labeling or advertising such food, or other processed food, as ‘natural.’” \n\n3.	“Exempts foods that are: certified organic; unintentionally produced with genetically engineered material; made from animals fed or injected with genetically engineered material but not genetically engineered themselves; processed with or containing only small amounts of genetically engineered ingredients; administered for treatment of medical conditions; sold for immediate consumption such as in a restaurant; or alcoholic beverages.”\n\nThe California Legislative Analyst’s Office and Director of Finance estimate that if this measure passes there will be:\n\n1.	“Increased annual state costs ranging from a few hundred thousand dollars to over $1 million to regulate the labeling of genetically engineered foods.”\n\n2.	“Potential, but likely not significant, costs to state and local governments due to litigation resulting from possible violations of the requirements of this measure. Some of these costs would be supported by court filing fees that the parties involved in each legal case would be required to pay under existing law.” \n\nIn terms of support, the “Yes on 37” campaign has received $7,700,000 (as of October 14, 2012) in donations from companies like Mercola Health Resources, Clif Bar & Co., Nature’s Path Foods, and the Organic Consumers Fund. Supporters of this initiative claim that everyone should have the right to know what’s in the food we eat, and that over 40 countries already require GMO labeling. \n\nIn contrast, the “No on 37” campaign has received $35,600,000 (as of October 14, 2012) in donations from companies like Monsanto, E.I. Dupont De Nemours & Co., DOW Agrisciences, Pepsico, Inc., Coca-Cola North America, and Nestle USA. Opponents of this initiative claim that the bill is “deceptive,” and “full of special interest exemptions.” Opponents also claim that this would “increase food costs by billions, without providing any health or safety benefits.” \n\nRegardless of how the bill turns out, Voskos takes great pride in producing all natural and GMO free products, and will always take the time to ensure that the finest and freshest ingredients are utilized to create a delicious and healthy meal. \n\n', 'Prop 37 – The GMO Labeling Initiative ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'prop-37-gmo-labeling-initiative', '', '', '2012-11-01 10:50:02', '2012-11-01 17:50:02', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1548', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1555, 12, '2012-11-07 05:00:57', '2012-11-07 12:00:57', 'November is American Diabetes Month. It’s no secret that diabetes has become an epidemic in this country. This disease currently affects 25.8 million Americans, with an additional 79 million Americans (ages 20 and up) being prediabetic. The most concerning statistic is the fact that type II diabetes constitutes between 90% and 95% of all diagnosed cases. In other words, the majority of these cases are preventable. \n\nA proper diet and exercise regiment is the easiest and cheapest way to help prevent type II diabetes. All Americans should aim to get 45 – 60 minutes of cardiovascular and strength training at least 5-6 days per week. In addition, regardless of previous or current medical history, people should not excessively eat foods with added sugar or high glycemic indexes. Chronic consumption of high sugar and high glycemic carbohydrates over-stimulates insulin receptors, leading to type II diabetes. Two interesting studies have revealed the potential for dairy products to help combat this epidemic.  \n\nA study conducted in 2005 by scientists and doctors affiliated with Harvard Medical School and Massachusetts General Hospital concluded that higher consumption of low-fat dairy products may reduce the risk of type II diabetes in men. The mechanisms behind these results are not entirely clear, however it is possible that the high protein content found in foods like Greek yogurt can increase satiety, leading to a decrease in overall daily caloric intake. \n\nFurthermore, lactose (the sugar found in dairy products) has a relatively lower glycemic index when compared to table sugar or foods like white breads, pastas, and cereals. Another study done by the Health Partners Research Foundation discovered that a diet high in low-fat dairy and yogurt products lead to a decrease in the incidence of type II diabetes among postmenopausal women, especially those who were obese. \n\nThese results are encouraging. For diabetics and non-diabetics alike, I recommend Voskos’s plain non-fat Greek yogurt as the main method of daily dairy intake. Voskos’s plain non-fat yogurt only has 9g of carbohydrates per 8 oz serving, which is suitable for diabetics. Greek yogurt has lower sugar than standard yogurt because of the way in which it is strained. It is also higher in protein than other dairy products and has the added benefits of probiotics. \n', 'Could Eating Dairy Help Prevent Diabetes? ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'could-eating-dairy-help-prevent-diabetes', '', '', '2012-11-07 05:00:57', '2012-11-07 12:00:57', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1555', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1561, 3, '2012-12-27 05:00:18', '2012-12-27 12:00:18', 'For years it has been my dream to enjoy all the scrumptiousness of cheesecake without the guilty morning-after effect.  Enter the best ingredient ever: Voskos Greek Yogurt!  \n\nRecipe substitutions don’t always work out well. It’s difficult to make a new ingredient take the place of the original ingredient.  There are so many factors involved:  texture (vital to the outcome), sugars & fat (must always be taken into account) and taste. But take a look at the chart below to see how Greek yogurt stacks up:\n\n<img src="http://www.voskos.com/fresh/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/table.jpg" alt="" title="table" width="600" height="142" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1562" />\n\nThe nice thing about Greek yogurt is that it’s something we already eat.  As it is.  I have never grabbed a 1/3 cup of olive oil and a spoon for a midday snack.  Nor have I taken two tablespoons of Crisco to my lips.  Ditto for butter...though I may have considered that on one really awful 3pm crash when I was shocked to find that ALL of the Halloween mini-candy bars were missing from my daughter’s haul.  \n\nBut Greek yogurt is actually delicious as it is, it’s creamy and not too sweet.  I do eat it for a midday snack and have fallen madly in love with it, because I just can’t seem to eat things based entirely on health benefits.  I can love something that tastes great if it happens to be good for me. Did I mention that Voskos Greek yogurt has much less fat than butter and sour cream?\n\nSo, in the Voskos Kitchen, how do we use Voskos to make our recipes delicious AND good for you? Let’s take a look at our December recipes. \n\n<strong><a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/dinner/herb-poached-salmon-with-creamy-herb-sauce">Salmon with yogurt sauce</a></strong>\nSalmon is beautiful, easy to cook and packed with health benefits.  This simple recipe goes gourmet when you add the rich, cool Greek yogurt sauce.  Pair it with the beet side dish below and you’ve got brand new flavors to enjoy! When you eat this, your body – and your taste buds - will thank you for it.\n\n<strong><a href="http://www.marthastewart.com/331825/roasted-beets-with-mint-yogurt-sauce" target="_blank">Beets with mint & yogurt</a></strong>\nHere’s a colorful addition that will surprise everyone.  Purple/magenta on my dinner plate? Yes, please!  This recipe is a delicious twist on beets.  Mashed potatoes are boring!  The flavors of the Greek yogurt and beets complement one another in tangy harmony with a pinch of sweetness just for fun. \n\n<strong><a href="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/dessert/greek-yogurt-cheesecake-recipe">Cheesecake</a></strong>\nIn Greek yogurt substitutions, this recipe really takes the (cheese)cake!  The Greek yogurt addition makes for the creamiest of bites.  When you slide your fork into the first piece you’ll know just what I’m talking about.  As for the post-dessert guilt?  Forget about it, especially if it’s NY cheesecake.  One smart cookie just made this less fattening.  It’s time to bask in the euphoria of a full tummy and time with friends (no one eats cheesecake alone, right?)\n', 'How We Use Greek Yogurt to Make Recipes Better', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'use-greek-yogurt-to-make-recipes-better', '', '', '2012-12-27 05:00:18', '2012-12-27 12:00:18', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1561', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1565, 3, '2011-11-08 04:00:46', '2011-11-08 11:00:46', 'Win $250, $100 or $50 – just in time for the holiday season! We’re super excited to announce The Voskos Thanksgiving Feast, a not-so-traditional Thanksgiving meal featuring creative recipes that you’ll want to enjoy all year! \n\nOur chefs have created a yummy and healthy Voskos Thanksgiving Menu and are inviting you to try it out. During the upcoming weeks, leading up to Thanksgiving, we will post the recipes. You’re invited to try them, photograph your creation, upload the photos, and get your friends to vote. \n\nAfter Thanksgiving, on Wednesday November 30th, the Voskos team will pick three winners to receive gift cards – our contribution to your holiday shopping. First prize gets $250, second prize gets $100 and third prize gets $50. We will post the first recipe later today. Head over to the Contests link on our <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Facebook page</a> to enter the contest, or click <a href="http://tinyurl.com/thanksgiving-menu-contest" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a>. \n\nHere’s the full menu:\n1. Spinach and Feta turnovers\n2. Onion-Bacon Dip\n3. Arugula, Green Bean Salad\n4. Cabbage Salad with Granny Smith Apples and Pomegranates\n5. Mashed Sweet Potato, Turnips with Herbs\n6. Cranberry Relish with Apple Cider\n7. Curry-Roasted Butternut Squash and Chickpeas Over Quinoa Pilaf\n8. Herb Roasted Turkey with Garlic-Lemon Gravy\n9. Apple-Walnut Strudel\n\nGOOD LUCK!\n', 'Announcing the Voskos Thanksgiving Menu Contest!', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-thanksgiving-menu-contest', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '2013-08-05 21:02:39', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1565', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1568, 12, '2012-12-03 05:00:00', '2012-12-03 12:00:00', 'Lets face it, there is never a convenient time to get sick. Juggling a busy schedule is stressful enough. Trying to seize the day when sick can seem next to impossible. Preventing colds and the flu is actually quite easy and can be accomplished without the use of over-the-counter or prescription drugs. Add these basic steps to your routine to stay healthy: \n\n<strong>1.	Hand Washing</strong>\n\nFrequent hand washing is one of the easiest and most important ways to avoid getting sick and transmitting germs. According to the CDC, people should wash their hands with soap and running water for at least 20 seconds (the equivalent of singing the “happy birthday” song to yourself twice). Make sure to scrub in between your fingers and under your nails as well. You can also use a hand sanitizer that is at least 60 percent alcohol if access to soap and water is an issue. \n\n<strong>2.	Don’t Touch Your Face</strong>\n\nYour body has a couple weak points. The eyes, nose, and mouth are susceptible to bacterial and viral transmission. Simply avoid touching your face all together to help prevent getting sick. \n\n<strong>3.	Cover Your Mouth</strong>\n\nAlways remember to cover your mouth out of courtesy when coughing or sneezing. The CDC recommends coughing or sneezing into a tissue or the upper arm, not the hands. Whenever possible try avoiding close or physical contact with infected individuals. \n\n<strong>4.	Minimize Stress</strong>\n\nChronic stress can lead to abnormally high levels of cortisol, the body’s stress hormone. Cortisol suppresses the immune system, which can inhibit your body’s ability to fight infections. Finding time to practice stress-relieving practices can work to minimize the constant stressors one might experience throughout the day. Techniques might include deep breathing, positive self-talk, meditation, yoga, or a combination of the four.  \n\n<strong>5.	Get Plenty of Sleep</strong>\n\nProper sleep allows the body to recover, heal itself, and maintain hormonal balance. Abnormal or insufficient sleep patterns can create abnormal cortisol levels, which can inhibit the immune system and hamper the body’s ability to fight off infections. \n\n<strong>6.	Stay Hydrated</strong>\n\nDrinking water can help flush toxins and other waste products out of your body. Avoid sports drinks or vitamin waters, and stick to plain water, which has no sugar and zero calories. \n\n<strong>7.	Garlic</strong>\n\nAlthough not studied extensively among western doctors and scientists, garlic has been used for centuries in eastern medicinal practices as an antibacterial and antiviral. Garlic gets some of these properties from a sulfur compound called allicin, which according to one study by the Department of Biological Chemistry at the Weizmann Institute of Science in Israel, has multiple antimicrobial properties. Although garlic might not prevent colds entirely, it could reduce the duration and severity of it. Eating raw garlic is not for everyone as it can cause stomach aches and diarrhea. Try easing into it by slightly cooking the garlic. \n\nHere at Voskos we practice these preventative measures on a daily basis. As a result, our office has managed to minimize flu occurrences. Give them a try and see how they work for you! \n', '7 Natural Ways To Minimize Colds This Season ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'natural-ways-to-minimize-colds', '', '', '2012-12-03 05:00:00', '2012-12-03 12:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1568', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1573, 12, '2012-12-14 05:00:29', '2012-12-14 12:00:29', 'Growing evidence suggests that disruption of the human gut bacteria causes Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS), and IBS like symptoms.1 These symptoms can include gas, bloating, diarrhea, constipation, and gastroesophageal reflux (GERD). Many people experience these symptoms on a daily basis, while the problem remains undiagnosed or misdiagnosed. Although the root cause of IBS has yet to be discovered, many treatment options are available, including prescription and over-the-counter drugs, herbal remedies, and lifestyle changes. New research suggests that probiotic supplementation can help mitigate IBS symptoms.1 Probiotics are now emerging as a legitimate treatment for IBS. \n\nThe human gut houses trillions of good bacteria that aid in supporting immune functions, digestion and metabolism, as well as vitamin production.1 Any alterations to the quantity and species of bacteria in your gut could cause IBS and IBS like symptoms.1 It is thought that these changes could be due to environmental factors, dietary changes, and antibiotic consumption.1 When the composition of the bacteria in your gut changes, IBS symptoms could arise. Probiotics could help bring the gut back to homeostasis. In other words, they could help restore the gut bacterial concentrations back to normal. \n\nResearchers have been extensively looking at probiotic supplementation over the past few years. One study determined that administration of probiotics helped to reduce IBS symptoms, reduce inflammation, and improve intestinal wall “integrity.”1 Probiotics have also been shown to help alleviate travelers diarrhea and diarrhea induced by antibiotics.1 A separate 8-week study revealed that probiotic supplementation reduces bloating, abdominal pain, and distension compared to the placebo group.1 \n\nGiven these findings, it’s worth giving probiotics a chance. They offer a minimal risk, low-cost, high benefit opportunity. Voskos Greek Yogurt contains live and active probiotic cultures, which could help mitigate IBS and IBS like symptoms. Yogurt can also be used as a probiotic supplement when taking antibiotics. Antibiotics kill both the bad and good bacteria in your gut. Eating yogurt when taking antibiotics can work to help replenish the good bacteria. For these circumstances I recommend eating Voskos Plain Non-fat Greek Yogurt. \n\nSource\n1. Ghoshal U, Shukla R, Ghoshal U, Gwee K, Ng S, and Quigley E. 2012. The gut microbiota and irritable bowel syndrome. International Journal of Inflammation 2012: 1-13. \n', 'Probiotics – A Potential Treatment for IBS  ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'probiotics-a-potential-treatment-for-ibs', '', '', '2012-12-14 05:00:29', '2012-12-14 12:00:29', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1573', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1577, 3, '2011-11-13 05:00:02', '2011-11-13 12:00:02', '*This recipe is part of the Voskos Thanksgiving 2011 Menu. Make this recipe, photograph it and upload a photo <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt?sk=app_95936962634" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a> to enter our Thanksgiving Menu Contest. You could win up to a $250 gift card, just in time for the holidays! \n\nYield: Serves 8\n \n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 medium head of cabbage, thinly sliced\n2 medium Granny Smith apples, chopped\n1 small red onion, minced\n1 1/2 cups pomegranates\n1/2 cup parsley, minced\n1 cup Plain Voskos Greek Yogurt\n3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice\nSalt and Pepper to taste\n \n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. In a small bowl place yogurt, lemon, salt and pepper, whisk and set aside.\n2. Combine cabbage, apples, onions, parsley and toss. Add yogurt mixture and pomegranates and gently toss once again to coat well.\n \n*Note: To keep the apples from discoloring, squeeze a few drops of lemon juice.\n \n<strong>Nutrition </strong>                               \nUsing Voskos Greek Yogurt:                                                                \nCalories: 37\nTotal Carbohydrates: 2.6g                        \nDietary Fiber: 0.7g                                \nProtein: 1.2g                                                                                \nTotal Fat: 2.2g                                      \n\nUsing Mayonnaise:\nCalories: 107\nTotal Carbohydrates: 2.0g\nDietary Fiber: 0.9g\nProtein: 0.6g                                        \nTotal Fat: 11.0g      \n', 'Cabbage Salad with Apples and Pomegranates', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'cabbage-salad-with-apples-and-pomegranates', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1577', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1581, 3, '2013-01-08 09:59:47', '2013-01-08 16:59:47', 'Can''t stand Brussels sprouts? The little ones refuse anything green? No worries. Just get a little sneaky with your cooking and include healthy additions in standard recipes.  I''m usually one to try something new…but it rarely sticks.  But when it comes to experimenting with healthy add-ins, I''ve been doing it on a daily basis - and even my kids enjoy it (gasp!).\n\nHere''s how I''ve found my way to scientific satisfaction and more energy in the kitchen:\n \n1. <strong>Breakfast burritos.</strong> I have mixed these up in all sorts of ways, adding in pureed onions and peppers until they look like ''sauce''.  Which makes them less detectable to the kids (visible pepper avoiders) and adds in tasty flavors.  I''ve substituted brown rice for white and still no one has noticed!  I''ve replaced sour cream with Voskos Greek yogurt (Voskos is one of my favorite add-ins…you may notice as you read on) to reduce the amount of fat and increase protein. \n\n2.<strong> Muffins</strong>.  This is a great go-to snack that everyone loves.  Few can resist the smell of fresh bread baking in the oven, at it''s best in the form of a muffin that fits in your hand.  Sweet or savory, muffins have become a vehicle for me to include whatever is on hand: oatmeal, greek yogurt, flax seed, etc.  Get creative- a puree of blueberries and kale made for a bright muffin adventure one morning!\n\n3.<strong> Dessert.</strong>  Cake batter is delicate so you have to be careful here. I did have one memorable disaster that led me to my first (and only) rule of additions: Add in small portions first, larger portions later.  A quarter cup of something is likely to go undetected in desserts - replace some of the butter with applesauce or Voskos greek yogurt, add in a fruit or even carrot puree. Sweet potatoes are an excellent addition to a rich dessert.  It feels great to make recipes more healthful and see how the detectives…er, I mean family try to determine what I''ve done differently.  Often they don''t notice at all…shh!\n\n4. <strong>Dips.</strong>  We are all prey to the allure of dips; hummus, ranch dressing, salsa…it adds flavor and texture to veggies or chips. I''ve been able to add in roasted peppers, garlic, onions, beans, olive oil, carrots and squash to create some well-received dressings for carrots and pretzels.  Replacing part or all of the sour cream with Greek yogurt should go without saying at this point. \n\nOne final tip: Parties and movie nights are good times to introduce a new dish…picky folks tend to inspect a little less and feel inclined to enjoy the food when they''re content with the activities going on around them.\n\nBest of all, when yo start experimenting with healthifying your recipes, the kids aren''t the only ones eating healthier.  The adults in my household are enjoying the fruits of my experiments too.  Try it for yourself! include a sneaky, nutritious addition (such as oats or pureed beans) in Grandma''s meatloaf for tonight''s dinner! ', '4 Ways to Sneak in Nutrition ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '4-ways-to-sneak-in-nutrition', '', '', '2013-01-08 09:59:47', '2013-01-08 16:59:47', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1581', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1586, 3, '2011-11-16 05:00:11', '2011-11-16 12:00:11', '*This recipe is part of the Voskos Thanksgiving 2011 Menu. Make this recipe, photograph it and upload a photo <a href="http://www.facebook.com/Voskos.Greek.Yogurt?sk=app_95936962634" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">here</a> to enter our Thanksgiving Menu Contest. You could win up to a $250 gift card, just in time for the holidays! \n\nYield: Serves 8\n\n<strong>For Roasted Butternut Squash:</strong>\n\nIngredients\n \n2 large butternut squash (about 5 pounds) peeled, seeded and cut into 1-inch dice\nOne 19-ounce can chickpeas--drained, rinsed and dried\n1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil\n1 tablespoon mild curry powder\n1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper\nSalt and freshly ground pepper\n3 cups Plain Voskos Greek Yogurt\n3/4 cup finely chopped cilantro\n3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice\n \nDirections\n \n1. Preheat the oven to 375 degrees. In a large bowl, toss the butternut squash with the chickpeas, olive oil, curry and cayenne and season with salt and pepper. Spread the squash cubes and chick peas on a large rimmed baking sheet and roast for 1 hour, or until tender.\n\n2. Meanwhile, in a medium bowl, stir the yogurt with cilantro and lemon juice and season with salt and pepper.\n\n3. Spoon the roasted butternut squash and chickpeas over quinoa, drizzle with 1/2 cup of the yogurt sauce. Serve the remaining yogurt sauce on the side.\n\n<strong>For Quinoa Pilaf:</strong>\n \nIngredients\n1 cup quinoa, rinsed\n2 cups low-sodium chicken broth\n2 tablespoons light olive oil\n1/2 large onion, chopped\n1/3 cup chopped fresh parsley\n1 tablespoon lemon zest\nSalt and pepper to taste\n \nDirections\n\n1. Place broth and quinoa in a medium sized saucepan and bring to boil. Reduce heat, stir in lemon zest, cover and cook for 15 to 20 minutes, until liquid is absorbed and grain is tender.\n\n2. Meanwhile, heat a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add the onions and cook stirring occasionally, until the onions soften and begin to brown, about 6 minutes.\n\n3. When the quinoa is done, fluff with a fork and transfer to a large bowl. Stir in the onions, parsley, and season with salt and pepper. Enjoy!!\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nUsing Voskos Greek Yogurt and Quinoa:\nCalories Per Serving: 395\nTotal fat: 8.6\nTotal Carbohydrates: 64.4g\nDietary Fiber: 8.8g\nProtein: 14.8g\n\nUsing Mayonnaise and white rice:\nCalories Per Serving: 481\nTotal fat: 17.8\nTotal Carbohydrates: 70.3g\nDietary Fiber: 5.7g\nProtein: 8.7g\n\n\n', 'Curry Butternut Squash & Chickpeas with Quinoa Pilaf', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'curry-butternut-squash-chickpeas-with-quinoa-pilaf', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1586', 0, 'post', '', 7),
(1593, 3, '2011-11-18 05:00:00', '2011-11-18 12:00:00', 'Golden and crispy on the outside, tender and juicy on the inside. The perfect Thanksgiving turkey!\n\nYield: Makes 8 to 10 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n1 (17-pound) turkey, rinsed well and patted dry\n1 cup grape seed oil\n2 tablespoon finely chopped fresh flat-leaf parsley\n1 tablespoon finely chopped oregano\n1 tablespoon finely chopped thyme\nSea salt and freshly ground black pepper\n6 cups chicken stock, homemade or store-bought\n3 large carrots, cut into 1-inch pieces\n3 large stalks celery, cut into 1-inch pieces\n2 large onions, quartered\n \n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Remove the turkey from the refrigerator 1 hour before roasting.\n \n2. Whisk the grape seed oil with parsley, oregano and thyme. Season with salt and pepper.\n\n3. Preheat the oven to 450 degrees.\n \n4. Put 4 cups of the chicken stock in a medium saucepan and keep warm over low heat.\n \n5. Season the cavity of the turkey with salt and pepper and fill the cavity with half of the carrots, celery, and onions. Rub the entire turkey with herb-oil and season liberally with salt and pepper.\n\n6. Scatter the remaining vegetables on the bottom of a large roasting pan. Fit a rack over the vegetables and put the turkey on top of rack. Pour the remaining 2 cups stock into the bottom of the roasting pan and carefully put the pan in the oven. Roast until the turkey is light golden brown, about 45 minutes.\n\n7. Reduce the oven temperature to 350 degrees and continue roasting, basting with the warm chicken stock every 15 minutes, until an instant-read thermometer inserted in the thigh registers 160 degrees, about 2 1/2 hours longer.\n\n8. Remove the turkey from the oven, transfer to a large cutting board, and tent loosely with foil. Let rest for 30 minutes before carving.\n\n<strong>Gravy Ingredients</strong>\n 2 cups (or more) Stock From Pan Juices.\n3 garlic cloves, chopped\n1 small shallot, chopped\n1/4 cup whole wheat flour\n1 teaspoon finely grated lemon peel\n2 tablespoon lemon juice\n1/2 teaspoon sugar\n1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley\n \n<strong>Gravy Directions</strong>\nScrape juices and browned bits from reserved roasting pan into large glass\nmeasuring cup. Spoon off fat, reserving 2 tablespoons. Add enough stock to juices to 1 2/3 cups. Heat reserved 2 tablespoons fat in heavy large saucepan over medium-high heat. Add garlic and shallot; sauté'' 2 minutes. Add flour; whisk until golden, about 4 minutes. Add degreased pan juiced and 2 cups stock. Bring to boil, whisking until smooth. Reduce heat and simmer until gravy is reduced to desired consistency, about 4 minutes. Whisk in lemon juice, lemon peel, sugar, then parsley. Season to taste with salt and pepper.  \n\n<img src="http://www.voskos.com/recipes/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/gravy-op1.jpg" alt="gravy" title="gravy op" width="589" height="399" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1597" />\n\n<strong>Roasted Turkey Nutrition Facts</strong>\nCalories Per Serving:               150.8 cal\nTotal Fat:                                   6g\nSaturated Fat:                            1.5g\nCarbs:                                         0g \nProtein:                                 22.6g  \n\n<strong>Herb Gravy Nutrition Facts</strong>\nCalories Per Serving: 39 cal\nTotal Fat:    4.3g \nSaturated Fat:  0.6g\nCarbs:      0.2g\nProtein:  0g  \n\n\n', 'Herb Roasted Turkey With Lemon-Garlic Gravy', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'herb-roasted-turkey', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1593', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1599, 12, '2013-02-11 05:00:09', '2013-02-11 12:00:09', 'How often do you find yourself wandering through the aisles of your local vitamin store? Searching for the “right” supplements can often be a daunting task. With countless rows of colorful bottles making remarkable claims and promising magical results, it’s hard to know exactly who is telling the truth. \n\n	One of the major problems with the supplement industry in general is the fact that the FDA does not regulate them. This lack of oversight allows companies to utilize poor quality ingredients and substitute effective ingredients with “cutting” agents such as baking powder. Supplement companies can also avoid having to display the true amount of each ingredient contained in each serving by using the name “proprietary blend.” This leaves consumers completely in the dark, and the result is a sense of uneasiness about what you are really putting into your body. In other words, you might not be getting exactly what you are paying for. Whenever possible I try and get my nutrition from natural sources. \n\n	One of the most common supplements on the market today is protein powder. They come in a wide array of variations, and they are often used as a post-workout supplement. The goal of a post-workout supplement is two-fold. First, it needs to contain carbohydrates to replace the stored glycogen lost after an intense workout. Glycogen is a stored form of glucose that your body utilizes as it’s primary source of fuel. Second, it needs to contain protein to assist with the repair and recovery of muscle tissue. Protein is broken down to amino acids, which are the building blocks of muscle fibers. \n\n	Voskos Greek Yogurt can in fact be utilized as an all-natural post-workout supplement. The flavored yogurts contain a carbohydrate to protein ratio of about 2:1, which is ideal after a moderate workout. I recommend the plain non-fat yogurt to those who are trying to lose weight because it has fewer carbohydrates per serving. The reassuring part is the fact that you know exactly what you are putting in your body. What you see on the ingredient list is exactly what you are buying. \n\n	Greek yogurt can also be utilized as a healthy snack. The carbohydrate to protein ratio in Greek yogurt will not only provide you with sustainable energy, but will increase the feeling of satiety, which will prevent you from binging on other junk foods. With the added benefits of probiotics working to sustain a “healthy” gut, Greet yogurt might just be the perfect snack. \n	 \n	Kick-start your new workout program this year, and give Voskos Greek Yogurt a try. Stick to your goals, and never quit! \n	\n\n', 'Feed Your Muscles With Voskos Greek Yogurt', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'yogurt-after-workout', '', '', '2013-02-11 05:00:09', '2013-02-11 12:00:09', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1599', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(1603, 12, '2013-02-19 05:00:58', '2013-02-19 12:00:58', '		For some people, January marks the beginning of a new undertaking to lose weight. Before choosing a specific program, consider the following study, which found a link between dietary calcium and weight loss. \n\n	A review study done by researchers at the University of Tennessee discovered a link between high calcium diets and weight loss. Scientists determined that calcium inside human cells has the power to regulate fat cell metabolism.1 Here is a brief summary of what the researchers concluded from the study:\n\n1.	Dietary calcium controls the levels of a hormone called calcitriol (the active form of vitamin D), which in turn modifies the amount of calcium taken in by fat cells.1 Researchers determined that this mechanism has the power to control fat metabolism in human fat cells.1 \n\n2.	High calcium diets increase fat loss during periods of caloric restriction.1 \n\n3.	Calcium consumed from dairy products is significantly more effective than calcium supplements at reducing body weight and body fat during periods of caloric restriction.1 \n\n4.	Increasing dietary calcium through dairy products can reduce the effects of weight gain and fat accumulation during periods of over-eating.1 \n\n5.	Dairy demonstrated an ACE-inhibitory effect in hypertensive humans.1 In other words, dairy was found to have similar effects to that of high blood pressure medications. \n\n6.	Addition of dairy products to a caloric restriction diet is associated with the conservation of lean body mass.1 Dairy products have a high concentration of branched chain amino acids (BCAAs) which are needed to build muscle tissue.1   \n\n7.	It is important to note that these findings are not independent of “energy balance.”1 In other words, one still needs to consider the ratio of calories ingested to calories burned on a daily basis. \n\nKeep these points in mind when creating your nutrition plan this year. As I’ve stated in previous articles, a weight loss program should include both diet and exercise. A proper weight loss diet includes moderate calorie restriction, along with eating quality ingredients. Remember, not all calories are created equal. Maintain a diet that is high in fruits and vegetables (rich in anti-oxidants), lean protein (mainly fish, poultry, egg whites, and dairy), nuts and seeds (high in omega-3s), beans and legumes, and whole grains (mainly from buckwheat, brown rice, quinoa, steel-cut oats, barley, and wild rice). Avoid eating out whenever possible. If time is an issue, make all of your meals ahead of time on Sunday for the following week. Avoid drinking alcohol in excess, as it can quickly add unwanted calories to your daily intake. Try adding Voskos yogurt to complement your diet plan this year, and see if it makes a difference for you. \n\nSource\n\n1. Zemel MB. The role of dairy foods in weight management. Journal of the American College of Nutrition 2005; 24: 537S-546S. \n\n', 'Calcium-Rich Diet Linked To Weight Loss ', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'calcium-rich-diet-linked-to-weight-loss', '', '', '2013-02-19 05:00:58', '2013-02-19 12:00:58', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1603', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(1604, 3, '2011-11-18 05:00:42', '2011-11-18 12:00:42', 'Yield: Makes 10 servings\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n2 cups apple cider\n1/2 cup agave nectar syrup\n1 12-ounce bag fresh cranberries, rinsed in cold water\n1 medium Granny Smith apple, peeled, cored, diced\n1 1/2 teaspoon finely grated lemon peel\n1 tablespoon chopped fresh parsley \n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\nBoil apple cider in heavy small saucepan until reduced to generous 1/2 cup, about 15 minutes. Stir in agave and transfer to a bowl and chill until cold, about 1 hour. Using on/off turns, coarsely chop cranberries, apple, and lemon peel in processor. Add cider syrup; using on/off turns, chop finely. Transfer to bowl, cover and chill  overnight. \n\nDO AHEAD: Can be made 2 days ahead. keep chilled. Bring to room temperature before serving.\n\nStir in chopped parsley and serve.\n\nNote*: Boiling down the cider gives great apple flavor; parsley adds color and freshness. You may add agave for more sweetness. Enjoy!\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nUsing Agave: \nCalories per serving: 87\nTotal Carbohydrates: 22.4g   \nDietary Fiber: 2.1g\nSugars: 18.7g \n\nUsing sugar:\nCalories per serving: 126\nTotal Carbohydrates: 32.4g   \nDietary Fiber: 2.1g\nSugars: 28.7g \n\n\n', 'Voskos Cranberry Relish with Apple Cider', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'voskos-cranberry-relish', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1604', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(1611, 3, '2011-11-19 05:00:40', '2011-11-19 12:00:40', 'Serves 6\n\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n3 medium Golden Delicious apples, peeled and diced into 1/4-inch cubes\n1/2 cup apple juice\n1/4 cup apricot spread (100 percent fruit)\n1 teaspoon lemon juice\n2 tablespoons currants\n1/2 cup walnuts\n2 tablespoons sugar\n1/4 teaspoon cinnamon\n4 sheets of phyllo dough (13 x 17 inches), thawed\n3 tablespoon melted butter\nPowdered sugar for dusting\n\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a medium nonstick skillet, combine apples, apple juice, apricot spread, lemon juice, and currants. Cook over medium heat for 10 minutes, until liquid is absorbed and apples are tender. Remove from heat.\n\n2. Combine the walnuts, sugar, and cinnamon in a small food processor and pulse until finely ground.\n\n3. Lay the phyllo sheet on a flat tray and cover with a piece of plastic wrap to keep them from drying out. Remove one sheet of dough at a time, keeping the rest covered, and place on a work surface with the short end facing you. Brush the sheet with melted butter and sprinkle with 2 tablespoons of the walnut mixture.\n\n4. Repeat the layering with the next three sheets of phyllo. Spread the apple filling over the pastry, leaving a 2-inch border at the top and the bottom and 1-inch border on the sides. Fold the bottom border over the filling, and roll up the pastry like a jelly roll. \n\n5. Place the strudel on a baking sheet with the seam down. Brush the top with melted butter and top with the remaining walnut mixture. Put strudel in the oven and bake for 15 minutes. Reduce oven heat to 350 degrees and bake for another 15 minutes, until nicely browned. Remove from oven and cool for at least 15 minutes before slicing, or cool completely and serve later. Dust lightly with powdered sugar at serving time.\n\n<strong>Nutrition</strong>\nUsing Phyllo Dough\nCalories per serving: 199 \nTotal Fat: 9.0g\nTotal Carbohydrates: 27.7g\nDietary Fiber: 2.6g  \nProtein: 1.6g \n\nUsing puff pastry\nCalories per serving: 382\nTotal Fat: 21.3g\nTotal Carbohydrates: 46.4\nDietary Fiber: 3.1g\nProtein: 4.5g\n', 'Apple-Walnut Strudel ', '', 'trash', 'open', 'open', '', 'apple-walnut-strudel', '', '', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '2013-08-05 21:02:27', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/recipes/?p=1611', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1622, 3, '2013-02-22 05:00:09', '2013-02-22 12:00:09', 'Living a healthy lifestyle doesn’t have to mean putting yourself on a juice fast and/or becoming a marathon runner.  A more realistic way to become health-conscious is to make small changes to your daily routine. Here are a few ideas: \n\n1.	<strong>Cut out the empty calories</strong>.  Replace "easy" sugary snacks like a can of soda and a candy bar with something just as simple but nutritious, like a water bottle and a cup of high-protein Greek yogurt.  \n\n2.	<strong>Take the stairs</strong>.  Sure, even one flight seems daunting after a long day at the office.  But try to push yourself to climb the staircase instead of copping out with that relaxing (and ever-so-tempting) ride up the elevator.\n\n3.	<strong>Go for a walk</strong>.  If you’re bored and can’t decide how to pass your waking hours, why not stroll through your neighborhood instead of planting yourself in front of the television for the entire afternoon.  As a bonus, you’ll not only burn some extra calories, but you’ll also get to know your hometown.\n\n4.	<strong>Cook more at home</strong>.  Eating out can add up to a lot of excess calories.  When someone else is cooking for you, you can’t know how much oil, cream, and sodium goes into the dish (and usually you''ll get a lot of those when you eat out).  When you prepare your own food, you know exactly what goes into it.\n\n5.	<strong>Notice the colors on your plate</strong>.  Different nutrients color foods differently, so a rainbow meal means that you’re filling up on all the proper nutrients.  Pile on green, orange, and red, and limit yourself on the browns and whites.  We''re talking natural colors here, of course... a rainbow-frosted cupcake is not the right choice to stay healthy. :)\n\n6.	<strong>Limit processed foods</strong>.  Instead of spending your grocery money on fancy microwavable meals with three thousand ingredients, just keep it simple.  Try to make time to prepare food yourself, and stick with ingredients whose names you can recognize (and not from chemistry class).\n\n7.	<strong>Pile on the veggies</strong>.  Be sure to incorporate vegetables into all your meals.   If you’re eating eggs, add some spinach and onions.  If you’re having chicken, add a salad on the side.  \n\n8.	<strong>Eat more protein</strong>. Protein keeps you fuller for longer and does not cause the famous cravings, or sugar crashes, that carbohydrates often cause. Including some form of protein (eggs, yogurt, lean meat, cheese) in every meal and snack will help you feel satiated and help prevent snack attacks. \n\n9. <strong>Don''t be afraid of good fats</strong>. Low fat diets often backfire, because they tend to be very high in simple carbohydrates. Fat is good for you - especially the fat found in foods such as avocado, salmon, and olive oil, and recent research shows that <a href="http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2010/12/dairy-diabetes/" target="_blank">dairy fat can be beneficial too</a>.  \n\n10.	<strong>Walk or bike short distances</strong>.  Though many of us are used to driving anywhere outside a 20-foot radius, distances of less than a mile are easily walkable, and distances less than three miles (especially on flat terrain) are easy to bike.  Plus, gas prices are only rising… so you’ll be doing your wallet a favor as well.\n', '10 Easy Steps for a Healthier Lifestyle', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'tips-healthier-lifestyle', '', '', '2013-02-22 05:00:09', '2013-02-22 12:00:09', '', 0, 'http://www.voskos.com/fresh/?p=1622', 0, 'post', '', 1);
